 They're replicating.

14:36.480 --> 14:38.640
 I mean, there's no sense in which they're trying

14:38.640 --> 14:39.640
 to do anything.

14:39.640 --> 14:42.040
 They're just a kind of an outgrowth of the earth,

14:42.040 --> 14:42.880
 you might say.

14:42.880 --> 14:44.800
 Of course, the aliens would describe us humans

14:44.800 --> 14:45.800
 in that same way.

14:45.800 --> 14:47.280
 They might be right.

14:47.280 --> 14:52.280
 This primitive life is just ants that are hairless,

14:52.520 --> 14:53.360
 mostly hairless.

14:53.360 --> 14:54.360
 Overgrown ants.

14:54.360 --> 14:55.640
 Overgrown ants.

14:55.640 --> 14:56.840
 Okay.

14:56.840 --> 14:59.360
 What do you think about the idea of panspermia,

14:59.360 --> 15:03.440
 that the theory that life did not originate on earth

15:03.440 --> 15:06.920
 and was planted here from outer space?

15:06.920 --> 15:08.560
 Or pseudo panspermia,

15:08.560 --> 15:10.680
 which is like the basic ingredients,

15:10.680 --> 15:12.920
 the magic that you mentioned was planted here

15:12.920 --> 15:14.680
 from elsewhere in space.

15:14.680 --> 15:16.360
 I don't find them helpful.

15:16.360 --> 15:17.840
 That's not to say they're wrong.

15:18.840 --> 15:20.760
 So pseudo transpermia,

15:20.760 --> 15:23.120
 the idea that the chemicals, the amino acids,

15:23.120 --> 15:24.800
 the nucleotides are being delivered from space.

15:24.800 --> 15:25.800
 Well, we know that happens.

15:25.800 --> 15:27.080
 It's unequivocal.

15:27.080 --> 15:29.600
 They're delivered on meteorites, comets and so on.

15:30.840 --> 15:31.840
 So what do they do next?

15:31.840 --> 15:33.120
 That's to me the question.

15:33.120 --> 15:34.960
 Well, what do they do is they stock a soup,

15:34.960 --> 15:36.680
 like presumably they land in a pond

15:36.680 --> 15:39.000
 or in an ocean or wherever they land.

15:39.000 --> 15:42.120
 And then you end up with a best possible case scenario

15:42.120 --> 15:43.920
 as you end up with a soup of nucleotides

15:43.920 --> 15:44.760
 and amino acids.

15:44.760 --> 15:45.600
 And then you have to say,

15:45.600 --> 15:46.440
 so now what happens?

15:46.440 --> 15:47.280
 And the answer is,

15:47.280 --> 15:50.800
 oh, well, they have to go become alive.

15:50.800 --> 15:51.760
 So how did they do that?

15:51.760 --> 15:54.760
 You may as well say that a miracle happened.

15:54.760 --> 15:57.120
 I don't believe in soup.

15:57.120 --> 16:00.720
 I think what we have in event is a continuous conversion,

16:00.720 --> 16:02.720
 a continuous growth, a continuous reaction,

16:02.720 --> 16:05.880
 a continuous converting a flow of molecules

16:05.880 --> 16:07.920
 into more of yourself, you might say,

16:07.920 --> 16:08.880
 even if it's a small bit.

16:08.880 --> 16:13.040
 So you've got a kind of continuous self organization

16:13.040 --> 16:14.760
 and growth from the very beginning.

16:14.760 --> 16:17.000
 You never have that in a soup.

16:17.000 --> 16:19.160
 Isn't the entire universe

16:19.160 --> 16:21.640
 and living organisms in the universe,

16:21.640 --> 16:25.000
 isn't it just a soup all the way down?

16:25.000 --> 16:25.840
 Isn't it all soup?

16:25.840 --> 16:27.760
 No, no, I mean soup almost by definition

16:27.760 --> 16:29.560
 doesn't have a structure.

16:29.560 --> 16:32.200
 But soup is a collection of ingredients

16:32.200 --> 16:34.040
 that are like randomly.

16:34.040 --> 16:36.200
 Yeah, but they're not random.

16:36.200 --> 16:38.760
 They're not, I mean, we have chemistry going on here.

16:38.760 --> 16:40.160
 We have membranes forming,

16:40.160 --> 16:43.360
 which are effective oil, water interactions.

16:43.360 --> 16:45.920
 Okay, so it feels like there's a direction to process,

16:45.920 --> 16:47.440
 like a directive process.

16:47.440 --> 16:49.880
 There are directions to processes, yeah.

16:49.880 --> 16:52.600
 And if you're starting with CO2

16:52.600 --> 16:55.560
 and you've got two reactive fluids being brought together

16:55.560 --> 16:57.680
 and they react, what are they gonna make?

16:57.680 --> 16:59.840
 Well, they make carboxylic acids,

16:59.840 --> 17:01.680
 which include the fatty acids

17:01.680 --> 17:03.000
 that make up the cell membranes.

17:03.000 --> 17:06.480
 And they form directly into bilayer membranes.

17:06.480 --> 17:07.640
 They form like soap bubbles.

17:07.640 --> 17:10.000
 It's spontaneous organization

17:10.000 --> 17:11.920
 caused by the nature of the molecules.

17:11.920 --> 17:14.000
 And those things are capable of growing

17:14.000 --> 17:16.400
 and are capable in effect of being selected

17:16.400 --> 17:18.280
 even before there are genes.

17:18.280 --> 17:20.040
 We have this, so we have a lot of order.

17:20.040 --> 17:22.520
 And that order is coming from thermodynamics.

17:22.520 --> 17:24.520
 And the thermodynamics is always

17:24.520 --> 17:27.000
 about increasing the entropy of the universe.

17:27.000 --> 17:30.440
 But if you have oil and water and they're separating,

17:30.440 --> 17:32.000
 you're increasing the entropy of the universe,

17:32.000 --> 17:33.120
 even though you've got some order,

17:33.120 --> 17:36.480
 which is the soap and the water are not missable.

17:36.480 --> 17:41.480
 Now, to come back to your first question about pan spermia

17:41.600 --> 17:45.440
 properly, that just pushes the question somewhere else.

17:45.440 --> 17:46.840
 That just, even if it's true,

17:46.840 --> 17:48.920
 maybe life did start on earth by pan spermia.

17:48.920 --> 17:52.160
 But so what are the principles

17:52.160 --> 17:55.160
 that govern the emergence of life on any planet?

17:55.160 --> 17:57.560
 It's an assumption that life started here.

17:57.560 --> 18:01.000
 And it's an assumption that it started

18:01.000 --> 18:02.000
 in a hydrothermal vent

18:02.000 --> 18:04.680
 or it started in a terrestrial geothermal system.

18:04.680 --> 18:07.560
 The question is, can we work out a testable sequence

18:07.560 --> 18:10.480
 of events that would lead from one to the other one

18:10.480 --> 18:12.640
 and then test it and see if there's any truth in it or not?

18:12.640 --> 18:14.880
 With pan spermia, you can't do any of that.

18:14.880 --> 18:17.680
 But the fundamental question of pan spermia is,

18:17.680 --> 18:21.960
 do we have the machine here on earth to build life?

18:22.960 --> 18:25.680
 Is the vents enough?

18:25.680 --> 18:30.680
 Is oxygen and hydrogen and whatever the heck else we want

18:30.680 --> 18:35.680
 and some source of energy and heat, is that enough to build life?

18:35.680 --> 18:40.680
 Well, that's, of course you would say that as a human,

18:41.680 --> 18:45.680
 but there could be aliens are now chuckling at that idea.

18:45.680 --> 18:50.680
 Maybe you need some special sauce, special elsewhere sauce.

18:51.680 --> 18:53.680
 So your sense is we have everything here.

18:53.680 --> 18:56.680
 I mean, this is precisely the question.

18:56.680 --> 18:58.680
 I like to, when I'm talking in schools,

18:58.680 --> 19:00.680
 I like to start out with the idea of,

19:00.680 --> 19:02.680
 we can make a time machine.

19:02.680 --> 19:04.680
 We go back four billion years

19:04.680 --> 19:06.680
 and we go to these environments that people talk about.

19:06.680 --> 19:08.680
 We go to a deep sea hydrothermal vent.

19:08.680 --> 19:13.680
 We go to a kind of Yellowstone Park type place environment

19:13.680 --> 19:17.680
 and we find some slime that looks like we can test it.

19:17.680 --> 19:19.680
 It's made of organic molecules.

19:19.680 --> 19:21.680
 It's got a structure, which is not obviously cells,

19:21.680 --> 19:26.680
 but is this a stepping stone on the way to life or not?

19:26.680 --> 19:28.680
 How do we know?

19:28.680 --> 19:31.680
 Unless we've got an intellectual framework that says,

19:31.680 --> 19:33.680
 this is a stepping stone and that's not a step.

19:33.680 --> 19:34.680
 We'd never know.

19:34.680 --> 19:36.680
 We wouldn't know which environment to go to,

19:36.680 --> 19:38.680
 what to look for, how to say this.

19:38.680 --> 19:39.680
 So all we can ever hope for,

19:39.680 --> 19:41.680
 because we're never going to build that time machine,

19:41.680 --> 19:43.680
 is to have an intellectual framework that can explain

19:43.680 --> 19:46.680
 step by step, experiment by experiment,

19:46.680 --> 19:50.680
 how we go from a sterile inorganic planet to living cells

19:50.680 --> 19:51.680
 as we know them.

19:51.680 --> 19:54.680
 And in that framework, every time you have a choice,

19:54.680 --> 19:56.680
 it could be this way or it could be that way,

19:56.680 --> 20:00.680
 or there's lots of possible forks down that road.

20:00.680 --> 20:02.680
 Did it have to be that way?

20:02.680 --> 20:04.680
 Could it have been the other way

20:04.680 --> 20:07.680
 and would that have given you life with very different properties?

20:07.680 --> 20:11.680
 And so if you come up with a, it's a long hypothesis,

20:11.680 --> 20:13.680
 because as I say, we're going from really simple

20:13.680 --> 20:15.680
 prebiotic chemistry all the way through

20:15.680 --> 20:17.680
 to genes and molecular machines.

20:17.680 --> 20:19.680
 That's a long, long pathway.

20:19.680 --> 20:21.680
 And nobody in the field would agree on the order

20:21.680 --> 20:22.680
 in which these things happened,

20:22.680 --> 20:24.680
 which is not a bad thing because it means

20:24.680 --> 20:26.680
 that you have to go out and do some experiments

20:26.680 --> 20:29.680
 and try and demonstrate that it's possible or not possible.

20:29.680 --> 20:36.680
 It's so freaking amazing that it happened, though.

20:36.680 --> 20:41.680
 It feels like there's a direction to the thing.

20:41.680 --> 20:47.680
 Can you try to answer from a framework perspective

20:47.680 --> 20:50.680
 of what is life?

20:50.680 --> 20:56.680
 So you said there's some order and yet there's complexity.

20:56.680 --> 20:58.680
 So it's not perfectly ordered.

20:58.680 --> 20:59.680
 It's not boring.

20:59.680 --> 21:01.680
 There's still some fun in it.

21:01.680 --> 21:05.680
 And it also feels like the processes have a direction

21:05.680 --> 21:07.680
 through the selection mechanism.

21:07.680 --> 21:11.680
 They seem to be building something always better,

21:11.680 --> 21:13.680
 always improving.

21:13.680 --> 21:14.680
 I mean, maybe it's...

21:14.680 --> 21:15.680
 I mean, that's a perception.

21:15.680 --> 21:19.680
 That's our romanticization of things are always better.

21:19.680 --> 21:21.680
 Things are getting better.

21:21.680 --> 21:22.680
 We'd like to believe that.

21:22.680 --> 21:24.680
 I mean, you think about the world from the point of view

21:24.680 --> 21:27.680
 of bacteria and bacteria are the first things to emerge

21:27.680 --> 21:29.680
 from whatever environment they came from.

21:29.680 --> 21:32.680
 And they dominated the planet very, very quickly.

21:32.680 --> 21:34.680
 And they haven't really changed.

21:34.680 --> 21:36.680
 Four billion years later, they look exactly the same.

21:36.680 --> 21:38.680
 So about four billion years ago,

21:38.680 --> 21:42.680
 bacteria started to really run the show.

21:42.680 --> 21:44.680
 And then nothing happened for a while.

21:44.680 --> 21:46.680
 Nothing happened for two billion years.

21:46.680 --> 21:49.680
 Then after two billion years, we see another single event,

21:49.680 --> 21:52.680
 origin, if you like, of our own type of cell,

21:52.680 --> 21:53.680
 the eukaryotic cells.

21:53.680 --> 21:56.680
 So cells with a nucleus and lots of stuff going on inside.

21:56.680 --> 21:59.680
 Another single origin, it only happened once

21:59.680 --> 22:00.680
 in the history of life on Earth.

22:00.680 --> 22:02.680
 Maybe it happened multiple times and there's no evidence.

22:02.680 --> 22:03.680
 Everything just disappeared.

22:03.680 --> 22:06.680
 But we have to at least take it seriously

22:06.680 --> 22:09.680
 that there's something that stops bacteria

22:09.680 --> 22:12.680
 from becoming more complex because they didn't.

22:12.680 --> 22:16.680
 That's a fact that they emerged four billion years ago.

22:16.680 --> 22:18.680
 And something happened two billion years ago,

22:18.680 --> 22:20.680
 but the bacteria themselves didn't change.

22:20.680 --> 22:21.680
 They remain bacterial.

22:21.680 --> 22:23.680
 So there is no trajectory,

22:23.680 --> 22:26.680
 necessary trajectory towards great complexity

22:26.680 --> 22:27.680
 in human beings at the end of it.

22:27.680 --> 22:30.680
 It's very easy to imagine that without photosynthesis arising

22:30.680 --> 22:32.680
 or without eukaryotes arising,

22:32.680 --> 22:35.680
 that a planet could be full of bacteria and nothing else.

22:35.680 --> 22:38.680
 We'll get to that because that's a brilliant invention.

22:38.680 --> 22:40.680
 And there's a few brilliant invention along the way.

22:40.680 --> 22:42.680
 But what is life?

22:42.680 --> 22:46.680
 If you were to show up on Earth to take that time machine

22:46.680 --> 22:49.680
 and you said, asking yourself the question,

22:49.680 --> 22:51.680
 is this a stepping stone towards life?

22:51.680 --> 22:55.680
 As you step along, when you see the early bacteria,

22:55.680 --> 22:57.680
 how would you know it's life?

22:57.680 --> 23:00.680
 And then this is really important question

23:00.680 --> 23:03.680
 when you go to other planets and look for life.

23:03.680 --> 23:07.680
 Like what is the framework of telling a difference

23:07.680 --> 23:11.680
 between a rock and a bacteria?

23:11.680 --> 23:14.680
 I mean, the question's kind of both impossible to answer

23:14.680 --> 23:15.680
 and trivial at the same time.

23:15.680 --> 23:17.680
 And I don't like to answer it

23:17.680 --> 23:18.680
 because I don't think there is an answer.

23:18.680 --> 23:19.680
 I think we're trying to describe...

23:19.680 --> 23:20.680
 Those are the most fun questions.

23:20.680 --> 23:22.680
 Approach me if there's no answer.

23:22.680 --> 23:23.680
 No, there is no answer.

23:23.680 --> 23:24.680
 I mean, there's lots of...

23:24.680 --> 23:28.680
 At least 40 or 50 different definitions of life out there.

23:28.680 --> 23:30.680
 And most of them are, well...

23:30.680 --> 23:31.680
 Not convincing.

23:31.680 --> 23:33.680
 Obviously bad in one way or another.

23:33.680 --> 23:36.680
 I mean, there's freaks.

23:36.680 --> 23:39.680
 I can never remember the exact words that people use,

23:39.680 --> 23:42.680
 but there's a NASA working definition of life,

23:42.680 --> 23:46.680
 which more or less says a system which is capable

23:46.680 --> 23:49.680
 of a self sustaining system capable of evolution

23:49.680 --> 23:51.680
 or something along those lines.

23:51.680 --> 23:55.680
 And I immediately have a problem with the words self sustaining

23:55.680 --> 23:57.680
 because it's sustained by the environment.

23:57.680 --> 23:59.680
 And I know what they're getting at.

23:59.680 --> 24:00.680
 I know what they're trying to say,

24:00.680 --> 24:02.680
 but I pick a hole in that.

24:02.680 --> 24:04.680
 And there's always wags who say,

24:04.680 --> 24:07.680
 but by that definition, a rabbit is not alive.

24:07.680 --> 24:09.680
 Only a pair of rabbits would be alive

24:09.680 --> 24:12.680
 because a single rabbit is incapable of copying itself.

24:12.680 --> 24:15.680
 There's all kinds of pedantic, silly,

24:15.680 --> 24:18.680
 but also important objections to any hypothesis.

24:18.680 --> 24:21.680
 The real question is what is...

24:21.680 --> 24:24.680
 We can argue all day, or people do argue all day about,

24:24.680 --> 24:26.680
 is a virus alive or not?

24:26.680 --> 24:28.680
 And it depends on the content.

24:28.680 --> 24:30.680
 But most biologists could not agree about that.

24:30.680 --> 24:33.680
 So then what about a jumping gene, a retro element or something?

24:33.680 --> 24:35.680
 It's even simpler than a virus,

24:35.680 --> 24:39.680
 but it's capable of converting its environment

24:39.680 --> 24:41.680
 into a copy of itself.

24:41.680 --> 24:43.680
 And that's about as close.

24:43.680 --> 24:44.680
 This is not a definition,

24:44.680 --> 24:46.680
 but this is a kind of a description of life,

24:46.680 --> 24:51.680
 is that it's able to parasitize the environment.

24:51.680 --> 24:53.680
 And that goes for plants as well as animals

24:53.680 --> 24:55.680
 and bacteria and viruses

24:55.680 --> 25:00.680
 to make a relatively exact copy of themselves,

25:00.680 --> 25:03.680
 information on the exact copy of themselves.

25:03.680 --> 25:07.680
 By the way, it doesn't really have to be a copy of itself, right?

25:07.680 --> 25:08.680
 It just has to be...

25:08.680 --> 25:12.680
 You have to create something that's interesting.

25:12.680 --> 25:15.680
 The way evolution is...

25:15.680 --> 25:19.680
 So it is extremely powerful process of evolution,

25:19.680 --> 25:21.680
 which is basically make a copy yourself

25:21.680 --> 25:23.680
 and sometimes mess up a little bit.

25:23.680 --> 25:24.680
 Absolutely.

25:24.680 --> 25:25.680
 That seems to work really well.

25:25.680 --> 25:27.680
 I wonder if it's possible to...

25:27.680 --> 25:28.680
 Mess up big time.

25:28.680 --> 25:31.680
 Mess up big time as a standard, as the default.

25:31.680 --> 25:33.680
 It's called the hopeful monster.

25:33.680 --> 25:35.680
 It doesn't work.

25:35.680 --> 25:36.680
 In principle, it can.

25:36.680 --> 25:37.680
 Actually, it turns out,

25:37.680 --> 25:40.680
 I would say that this is due a reemergence.

25:40.680 --> 25:43.680
 This is some amazing work from Michael Levin.

25:43.680 --> 25:44.680
 I don't know if you came across him,

25:44.680 --> 25:46.680
 but if you haven't interviewed him,

25:46.680 --> 25:47.680
 you should interview him.

25:47.680 --> 25:48.680
 Yeah.

25:48.680 --> 25:50.680
 About, yeah.

25:50.680 --> 25:52.680
 I'm talking to him in a few days.

25:52.680 --> 25:54.680
 Oh, fantastic.

25:54.680 --> 25:58.680
 So I mentioned off, there's two people that,

25:58.680 --> 25:59.680
 if I may mention,

25:59.680 --> 26:03.680
 Andre Capati is a friend who's really admired in the AI community,

26:03.680 --> 26:08.680
 said you absolutely must talk to Michael and to Nick.

26:08.680 --> 26:11.680
 So this, of course, I'm a huge fan of yours,

26:11.680 --> 26:14.680
 so I'm really fortunate that we can actually make this happen.

26:14.680 --> 26:15.680
 Anyway, your second.

26:15.680 --> 26:18.680
 Well, Michael Levin is doing amazing work,

26:18.680 --> 26:21.680
 basically about the way in which electrical fields

26:21.680 --> 26:23.680
 control development.

26:23.680 --> 26:26.680
 And he's done some work with planarian worms,

26:26.680 --> 26:27.680
 so flat worms,

26:27.680 --> 26:29.680
 where he'll tell you all about this.

26:29.680 --> 26:30.680
 So I won't say any more than the minimum,

26:30.680 --> 26:32.680
 but basically you can cut their head off

26:32.680 --> 26:35.680
 and they'll redevelop a different, a new head.

26:35.680 --> 26:37.680
 But the head that they develop depends,

26:37.680 --> 26:42.680
 if you knock out just one iron pump in a membrane,

26:42.680 --> 26:45.680
 so you change the electrical circuitry just a little bit,

26:45.680 --> 26:47.680
 you can come up with a completely different head.

26:47.680 --> 26:48.680
 It can be a head,

26:48.680 --> 26:52.680
 which is similar to those that diverged 150 million years ago,

26:52.680 --> 26:54.680
 a head which no one's ever seen before,

26:54.680 --> 26:56.680
 a different kind of head.

26:56.680 --> 26:59.680
 Now, that is really, you might say, a hopeful monster.

26:59.680 --> 27:01.680
 This is a kind of leap into a different direction.

27:01.680 --> 27:04.680
 The only question for natural selection is, does it work?

27:04.680 --> 27:07.680
 Is the change itself feasible as a single change?

27:07.680 --> 27:08.680
 And the answer is yes,

27:08.680 --> 27:10.680
 it's just a small change to a single gene.

27:10.680 --> 27:12.680
 And the second thing is it gives rise

27:12.680 --> 27:14.680
 to a completely different morphology.

27:14.680 --> 27:15.680
 Does it work?

27:15.680 --> 27:20.680
 And if it works, that can easily be a shift.

27:20.680 --> 27:22.680
 But for it to be a speciation,

27:22.680 --> 27:24.680
 for it to continue,

27:24.680 --> 27:28.680
 for it to give rise to a different morphology over time,

27:28.680 --> 27:31.680
 then it has to be perpetuated.

27:31.680 --> 27:36.680
 So that shift, that change in that one gene

27:36.680 --> 27:40.680
 has to work well enough that it is selected and it goes on.

27:40.680 --> 27:43.680
 And copied enough times to where you can really test it.

27:43.680 --> 27:45.680
 So the likelihood it would be lost,

27:45.680 --> 27:48.680
 but there will be some occasions where it survives.

27:48.680 --> 27:50.680
 And yes, the idea that we can have sudden,

27:50.680 --> 27:52.680
 fairly abrupt changes in evolution,

27:52.680 --> 27:54.680
 I think it's time for a rebirth.

27:54.680 --> 27:58.680
 What about this idea that kind of trying to

27:58.680 --> 28:01.680
 mathematicalize a definition of life

28:01.680 --> 28:03.680
 and saying how many steps,

28:03.680 --> 28:06.680
 the shortest amount of steps it takes to build the thing.

28:06.680 --> 28:09.680
 Almost like an engineering view of it.

28:09.680 --> 28:12.680
 I like that view because I think that in a sense,

28:12.680 --> 28:16.680
 that's not very far away from what a hypothesis needs to do

28:16.680 --> 28:18.680
 to be a testable hypothesis for the origin of life.

28:18.680 --> 28:21.680
 You need to spell out, here's each step.

28:21.680 --> 28:24.680
 And here's the experiment to do for each step.

28:24.680 --> 28:26.680
 The idea that we can do it in the lab,

28:26.680 --> 28:27.680
 some people say,

28:27.680 --> 28:30.680
 well, we'll have created life within five years,

28:30.680 --> 28:33.680
 but ask them what they mean by life.

28:33.680 --> 28:36.680
 We have a planet four billion years ago

28:36.680 --> 28:39.680
 with these vent systems across the entire surface of the planet.

28:39.680 --> 28:41.680
 And we have millions of years if we wanted.

28:41.680 --> 28:43.680
 I have a feeling that we're not talking about millions of years.

28:43.680 --> 28:46.680
 I have a feeling we're talking about, you know,

28:46.680 --> 28:49.680
 maybe millions of nanoseconds or picoseconds.

28:49.680 --> 28:53.680
 We're talking about chemistry, which is happening quickly.

28:53.680 --> 28:56.680
 But we still need to constrain those steps,

28:56.680 --> 29:00.680
 but we've got a planet doing similar chemistry.

29:00.680 --> 29:02.680
 You asked about a trajectory.

29:02.680 --> 29:04.680
 The trajectory is the planetary trajectory.

29:04.680 --> 29:06.680
 The planet has properties.

29:06.680 --> 29:08.680
 It's basically, it's got a lot of iron at the center of it.

29:08.680 --> 29:10.680
 It's got a lot of electrons at the center of it.

29:10.680 --> 29:12.680
 It's more oxidized on the outside partly because of the sun.

29:12.680 --> 29:16.680
 And partly because the heat of volcanoes puts out oxidized gases.

29:16.680 --> 29:18.680
 So the planet is a battery.

29:18.680 --> 29:20.680
 It's a giant battery.

29:20.680 --> 29:23.680
 And we have a flow of electrons going from inside to outside

29:23.680 --> 29:25.680
 in these hydrothermal vents.

29:25.680 --> 29:28.680
 And that's the same topology that a cell has.

29:28.680 --> 29:33.680
 A cell is basically just a micro version of the planet.

29:33.680 --> 29:36.680
 And it's, there is a trajectory in all of that.

29:36.680 --> 29:39.680
 And there's an inevitability that certain types of chemical reaction

29:39.680 --> 29:41.680
 are going to be favored over others.

29:41.680 --> 29:45.680
 And there's an inevitability in what happens in water,

29:45.680 --> 29:47.680
 the chemistry that happens in water.

29:47.680 --> 29:51.680
 Some will be immiscible with water and will form membranes

29:51.680 --> 29:53.680
 and will form insoluble structures.

29:53.680 --> 29:57.680
 And you know, water is a, nobody really understands water very well.

29:57.680 --> 30:01.680
 And it's another big question for pre experiments on the origin of life.

30:01.680 --> 30:03.680
 What do you put it in?

30:03.680 --> 30:06.680
 What kind of structure do we want to induce in this water?

30:06.680 --> 30:10.680
 Because the last thing is likely to be is just kind of bulk water.

30:10.680 --> 30:13.680
 How fundamental is water to life, would you say?

30:13.680 --> 30:16.680
 I would say pretty fundamental.

30:16.680 --> 30:21.680
 I wouldn't like to say it's impossible for life to start any other way.

30:21.680 --> 30:24.680
 But water is everywhere.

30:24.680 --> 30:27.680
 Water is extremely good at what it does.

30:27.680 --> 30:30.680
 And carbon, carbon works in water especially well.

30:30.680 --> 30:32.680
 So those things and carbon is everywhere.

30:32.680 --> 30:35.680
 So those things together make me think probabilistically,

30:35.680 --> 30:37.680
 if we found a thousand life forms,

30:37.680 --> 30:41.680
 995 of them would be carbon based and living in water.

30:41.680 --> 30:45.680
 Now the reverse question, if you found a puddle of water elsewhere

30:45.680 --> 30:49.680
 and some carbon, no, just a puddle of water.

30:49.680 --> 30:54.680
 Is a puddle of water a pretty damn good indication that life has,

30:54.680 --> 31:00.680
 either exists here or has once existed here?

31:00.680 --> 31:01.680
 No.

31:01.680 --> 31:04.680
 So it doesn't work the other way.

31:04.680 --> 31:06.680
 I think you need a living planet.

31:06.680 --> 31:10.680
 You need a planet which is capable of turning over its surface.

31:10.680 --> 31:12.680
 It needs to be a planet with water.

31:12.680 --> 31:17.680
 It needs to be capable of bringing those electrons from inside to the outside.

31:17.680 --> 31:19.680
 It needs to turn over its surface.

31:19.680 --> 31:22.680
 It needs to make that water work and turn it into hydrogen.

31:22.680 --> 31:24.680
 So I think you need a living planet.

31:24.680 --> 31:25.680
 But once you've got the living planet,

31:25.680 --> 31:29.680
 I think the rest of it is kind of thermodynamics all the way.

31:29.680 --> 31:35.680
 So if you were to run Earth over a million times up to this point,

31:35.680 --> 31:37.680
 maybe beyond to the end.

31:37.680 --> 31:39.680
 Let's run it to the end.

31:39.680 --> 31:42.680
 What is it, how much variety is there?

31:42.680 --> 31:47.680
 You kind of spoke to this trajectory that the environment dictates

31:47.680 --> 31:51.680
 like chemically, I don't know in which other way,

31:51.680 --> 31:59.680
 spiritually, like dictates kind of the direction of this giant machine

31:59.680 --> 32:04.680
 that seems chaotic, but it does seem to have order in the steps it's taking.

32:04.680 --> 32:10.680
 How often will life, how often will bacteria emerge?

32:10.680 --> 32:12.680
 How often will something like humans emerge?

32:12.680 --> 32:14.680
 How much variety do you think there would be?

32:14.680 --> 32:18.680
 I think at the level of bacteria, not much variety.

32:18.680 --> 32:23.680
 I think we would get, that's how many times you say you want to run it a million times.

32:23.680 --> 32:27.680
 I would say at least a few hundred thousand will get bacteria again.

32:27.680 --> 32:28.680
 Oh, wow.

32:28.680 --> 32:36.680
 Because I think there's some level of inevitability that a wet rocky planet will give rise through the same processes

32:36.680 --> 32:40.680
 to something very, I think this is not something I'd have thought a few years ago,

32:40.680 --> 32:43.680
 but we're working with a PhD student of mine, Stuart Harrison.

32:43.680 --> 32:48.680
 He's been thinking about the genetic code and we've just been publishing on that.

32:48.680 --> 32:52.680
 There are patterns that you can discern in the code, or he has discerned in the code,

32:52.680 --> 32:59.680
 that if you think about them in terms of we start with CO2 and hydrogen and these are the first steps of biochemistry,

32:59.680 --> 33:02.680
 you come up with a code which is very similar to the code that we see.

33:02.680 --> 33:07.680
 So it wouldn't surprise me any longer if we found life on Mars and it had a genetic code

33:07.680 --> 33:10.680
 that was not very different to the genetic code that we have here,

33:10.680 --> 33:13.680
 without it just being transferred across.

33:13.680 --> 33:17.680
 There's some inevitability about the whole of the beginnings of life in my view.

33:17.680 --> 33:25.680
 That's really promising because if the basic chemistry is tightly linked to the genetic code,

33:25.680 --> 33:29.680
 that means we can interact with other life if it exists out there.

33:29.680 --> 33:31.680
 Well, that's potentially...

33:31.680 --> 33:34.680
 That's really exciting if that's the case.

33:34.680 --> 33:35.680
 But then bacteria...

33:35.680 --> 33:37.680
 We've got bacteria.

33:37.680 --> 33:41.680
 How easy is photosynthesis?

33:41.680 --> 33:44.680
 Much harder, I would say.

33:44.680 --> 33:45.680
 Let's actually go there.

33:45.680 --> 33:48.680
 Let's go through the inventions.

33:48.680 --> 33:51.680
 What is photosynthesis and why is it hard?

33:51.680 --> 33:54.680
 Well, there are different forms.

33:54.680 --> 33:59.680
 Basically, you're taking hydrogen and you're sticking it onto CO2 and it's powered by the sun.

33:59.680 --> 34:02.680
 The question is where are you taking the hydrogen from?

34:02.680 --> 34:06.680
 And in photosynthesis that we know in plants, it's coming from water.

34:06.680 --> 34:10.680
 So you're using the power of the sun to split water, take out the hydrogen, stick it onto CO2

34:10.680 --> 34:14.680
 and the oxygen is a waste product and you just throw it out, throw it away.

34:14.680 --> 34:20.680
 So it's the single greatest planetary pollution event in the whole history of the Earth.

34:20.680 --> 34:22.680
 The pollutant being oxygen.

34:22.680 --> 34:23.680
 Yes.

34:23.680 --> 34:25.680
 It also made possible animals.

34:25.680 --> 34:29.680
 You can't have large active animals without an oxygenated atmosphere,

34:29.680 --> 34:32.680
 at least not in the sense that we know on Earth.

34:32.680 --> 34:35.680
 So that's a really big invention in the history of Earth.

34:35.680 --> 34:36.680
 Huge invention, yes.

34:36.680 --> 34:37.680
 And it happened once.

34:37.680 --> 34:41.680
 There's a few things that happen once on Earth and you're always stuck with this problem.

34:41.680 --> 34:47.680
 Once it happened, did it become so good so quickly that it precluded the same thing happening ever again?

34:47.680 --> 34:49.680
 Or are there other reasons?

34:49.680 --> 34:53.680
 And we really have to look at each one in turn and think, why did it only happen once?

34:53.680 --> 34:57.680
 In this case, it's really difficult to split water.

34:57.680 --> 35:02.680
 It requires a lot of power and that power, you're effectively separating charge across a membrane

35:02.680 --> 35:07.680
 and the way in which you do it, if it doesn't all rush back and kind of cause an explosion right at the site,

35:07.680 --> 35:10.680
 requires really careful wiring.

35:10.680 --> 35:18.680
 And that wiring, it can't be easy to get it right because the plants that we see around us,

35:18.680 --> 35:19.680
 they have chloroplasts.

35:19.680 --> 35:21.680
 Those chloroplasts were cyanobacteria ones.

35:21.680 --> 35:25.680
 Those cyanobacteria are the only group of bacteria that can do that type of photosynthesis.

35:25.680 --> 35:27.680
 So there's plenty of opportunity.

35:27.680 --> 35:29.680
 So not even many bacteria.

35:29.680 --> 35:31.680
 So who invented photosynthesis?

35:31.680 --> 35:33.680
 The cyanobacteria or their ancestors.

35:33.680 --> 35:35.680
 And there's not many...

35:35.680 --> 35:39.680
 No other bacteria can do what's called oxygenic photosynthesis.

35:39.680 --> 35:41.680
 Lots of other bacteria can split.

35:41.680 --> 35:43.680
 I mean, you can take your hydrogen from somewhere else.

35:43.680 --> 35:46.680
 You can take it from hydrogen sulfide bubbling out of a hydrothermal vent.

35:46.680 --> 35:48.680
 Grab your two hydrogens.

35:48.680 --> 35:51.680
 The sulfur is the waste now.

35:51.680 --> 35:52.680
 You can do it from iron.

35:52.680 --> 35:53.680
 You can take electrons.

35:53.680 --> 35:55.680
 So the early oceans were probably full of iron.

35:55.680 --> 35:58.680
 You can take an electron from ferrous iron.

35:58.680 --> 36:03.680
 So iron two plus and make it iron three plus, which now precipitates as rust.

36:03.680 --> 36:07.680
 And you take a proton from the acidic early ocean, stick it there.

36:07.680 --> 36:09.680
 Now you've got a hydrogen atom, stick it onto CO2.

36:09.680 --> 36:11.680
 You've just done the trick.

36:11.680 --> 36:15.680
 The trouble is you bury yourself in rusty iron.

36:15.680 --> 36:17.680
 And with sulfur, you can bury yourself in sulfur.

36:17.680 --> 36:25.680
 One of the reasons oxygenic photosynthesis is so much better is that the waste product is oxygen, which just bubbles away.

36:25.680 --> 36:28.680
 That seems like extremely unlikely.

36:28.680 --> 36:35.680
 And it's extremely essential for the evolution of complex organisms because of all the oxygen.

36:35.680 --> 36:38.680
 Yeah. And that didn't accumulate quickly either.

36:38.680 --> 36:41.680
 So it's converting, what is it?

36:41.680 --> 36:49.680
 It's converting energy from the sun and the resource of water into the resource needed for animals.

36:49.680 --> 36:51.680
 Both resources needed for animals.

36:51.680 --> 36:53.680
 We need to eat and we need to burn the food.

36:53.680 --> 36:58.680
 And we're eating plants, which are getting their energy from the sun.

36:58.680 --> 37:01.680
 And we're burning it with their waste product, which is the oxygen.

37:01.680 --> 37:11.680
 So there's a lot of kind of circularity in that, but without an oxygenated planet, you couldn't really have predation.

37:11.680 --> 37:16.680
 You can have animals, but you can't really have animals that go around and eat each other.

37:16.680 --> 37:19.680
 You can't have ecosystems as we know them.

37:19.680 --> 37:20.680
 Well, let's actually step back.

37:20.680 --> 37:25.680
 What about your periodic versus prokaryotic cells, prokaryotes?

37:25.680 --> 37:30.680
 What are each of those and how big of an invention is that?

37:30.680 --> 37:34.680
 I personally think that's the single biggest invention in the whole history of life.

37:34.680 --> 37:37.680
 Exciting. So what are they? Can you explain?

37:37.680 --> 37:42.680
 Yeah. So I mentioned bacteria and archaea. These are both prokaryotes.

37:42.680 --> 37:45.680
 They're basically small cells that don't have a nucleus.

37:45.680 --> 37:47.680
 If you look at them under a microscope, you don't see much going on.

37:47.680 --> 37:52.680
 If you look at them under a super resolution microscope, then they're fantastically complex.

37:52.680 --> 37:55.680
 In terms of their molecular machinery, they're amazing.

37:55.680 --> 38:02.680
 In terms of their morphological appearance under a microscope, they're really small and really simple.

38:02.680 --> 38:06.680
 The earliest life that we can physically see on the planet are stromatolites,

38:06.680 --> 38:10.680
 which are made by things like cyanobacteria and their large superstructures.

38:10.680 --> 38:19.680
 Effectively, biofilms plated on top of each other and you end up with quite large structures that you can see in the fossil record.

38:19.680 --> 38:24.680
 But they never came up with animals. They never came up with plants.

38:24.680 --> 38:28.680
 They came up with multicellular things, filamentous cyanobacteria, for example.

38:28.680 --> 38:31.680
 They're just long strings of cells.

38:31.680 --> 38:37.680
 But the origin of the eukaryotic cell seems to have been what's called an endosymbiosis.

38:37.680 --> 38:39.680
 So one cell gets inside another cell.

38:39.680 --> 38:43.680
 And I think that that's transformed the energetic possibilities of life.

38:43.680 --> 38:47.680
 So what we end up with is a kind of supercharged cell,

38:47.680 --> 38:53.680
 which can have a much larger nucleus with many more genes, all supported.

38:53.680 --> 38:57.680
 If you think about it, you could think about it as multi bacterial power without the overhead.

38:57.680 --> 39:00.680
 So you've got a cell and it's got bacteria living in it.

39:00.680 --> 39:03.680
 And those bacteria are providing it with the energy currency it needs.

39:03.680 --> 39:09.680
 But each bacterium has a genome of its own, which costs a fair amount of energy to express,

39:09.680 --> 39:14.680
 to kind of turn over and convert into proteins and so on.

39:14.680 --> 39:19.680
 What the mitochondria did, which are these power packs in our own cells,

39:19.680 --> 39:23.680
 they were bacteria once and they threw away virtually all their genes.

39:23.680 --> 39:25.680
 They've only got a few left.

39:25.680 --> 39:29.680
 So mitochondria is, like you said, is the bacteria that got inside a cell.

39:29.680 --> 39:34.680
 And then throw away all this stuff it doesn't need to survive inside the cell and then kept what?

39:34.680 --> 39:40.680
 So what we end up with, so it kept always a handful of genes in our own case, 37 genes.

39:40.680 --> 39:46.680
 But there's a few protists which are single cells, things that have got as many as 70 or 80 genes.

39:46.680 --> 39:50.680
 So it's not always the same, but it's always a small number.

39:50.680 --> 39:58.680
 And you can think of it as a paired down power pack where the control unit has really been kind of paired down to almost nothing.

39:58.680 --> 40:03.680
 So you're putting out the same power, but the investment in the overheads is really paired down.

40:03.680 --> 40:07.680
 That means that you can support a much larger nuclear genome.

40:07.680 --> 40:14.680
 So we've gone up in the number of genes, but also the amount of power you have to convert those genes into proteins.

40:14.680 --> 40:22.680
 We've gone up about fourfold in the number of genes, but in terms of the size of genomes and your ability to make the building blocks, make the proteins,

40:22.680 --> 40:24.680
 we've gone up 100,000 fold or more.

40:24.680 --> 40:29.680
 So it's huge step change in the possibilities of evolution.

40:29.680 --> 40:37.680
 And it's interesting then that the only two occasions that complex life has arisen on Earth, plants and animals,

40:37.680 --> 40:43.680
 fungi you could say are complex as well, but they don't form such complex morphology as plants and animals.

40:43.680 --> 40:45.680
 Start with a single cell.

40:45.680 --> 40:49.680
 They start with an oocyte and a sperm fused together to make as I got.

40:49.680 --> 40:55.680
 So we start development with a single cell and all the cells in the organism have identical DNA.

40:55.680 --> 41:02.680
 And you switch off in the brain, you switch off these genes and you switch on those genes and the liver, you switch off those and you switch on a different set.

41:02.680 --> 41:07.680
 And the standard evolutionary explanation for that is that you're restricting conflict.

41:07.680 --> 41:13.680
 You don't have a load of genetically different cells that are all fighting each other.

41:13.680 --> 41:14.680
 And so it works.

41:14.680 --> 41:22.680
 The trouble with bacteria, they form these biofilms and they're all genetically different and effectively they're incapable of that level of cooperation.

41:22.680 --> 41:25.680
 They would get in a fight.

41:25.680 --> 41:37.680
 Okay, so why is this such a difficult invention of getting this bacteria inside and becoming an engine, which the mitochondria is?

41:37.680 --> 41:40.680
 Why do you assign it such great importance?

41:40.680 --> 41:46.680
 Is it great importance in terms of the difficulty of how it was to achieve or great importance in terms of the impact it had on life?

41:46.680 --> 41:47.680
 Both.

41:47.680 --> 41:55.680
 It had a huge impact on life because if that had not happened, you can be certain that life on earth would be bacterial only.

41:55.680 --> 41:57.680
 And that took a really long time to...

41:57.680 --> 42:02.680
 It took two billion years and it hasn't happened since to the best of our knowledge.

42:02.680 --> 42:04.680
 So it looks as if it's genuinely difficult.

42:04.680 --> 42:14.680
 And if you think about it then from just an informational perspective, you think bacteria have got, they structure their information differently.

42:14.680 --> 42:17.680
 So a bacterial cell has a small genome.

42:17.680 --> 42:23.680
 You might have 4,000 genes in it, but a single E. coli cell has access to about 30,000 genes potentially.

42:23.680 --> 42:31.680
 It's got a kind of metagenome where other E. coli out there have got different gene sets and they can switch them around between themselves.

42:31.680 --> 42:35.680
 And so you can generate a huge amount of variation and they've got more...

42:35.680 --> 42:40.680
 An E. coli metagenome is larger than the human genome.

42:40.680 --> 42:42.680
 We have 20,000 genes or something.

42:42.680 --> 42:50.680
 And they've had 4 billion years of evolution to work out what can I do and what can't I do with this metagenome.

42:50.680 --> 42:53.680
 And the answer is you're stuck, you're still bacteria.

42:53.680 --> 43:05.680
 So they have explored genetic sequence space far more thoroughly than eukaryotes ever did because they've had twice as long at least and they've got much larger populations.

43:05.680 --> 43:07.680
 And they never got around this problem.

43:07.680 --> 43:08.680
 So why can't they?

43:08.680 --> 43:12.680
 It seems as if you can't solve it with information alone.

43:12.680 --> 43:14.680
 So what's the problem?

43:14.680 --> 43:16.680
 The problem is structure.

43:16.680 --> 43:18.680
 If cells...

43:18.680 --> 43:22.680
 If the very first cells needed an electrical charge on their membrane to grow.

43:22.680 --> 43:27.680
 And in bacteria, it's the outer membrane that surrounds the cell, which is electrically charged.

43:27.680 --> 43:31.680
 You try and scale that up and you've got a fundamental design problem.

43:31.680 --> 43:33.680
 You've got an engineering problem.

43:33.680 --> 43:38.680
 And there are examples of it and what we see in all these cases is what's known as extreme polyploidy,

43:38.680 --> 43:42.680
 which is to say they have tens of thousands of copies of their complete genome,

43:42.680 --> 43:51.680
 which is energetically hugely expensive and you end up with a large bacteria with no further development.

43:51.680 --> 44:01.680
 What you need is to incorporate these electrically charged power pack units inside with their control units intact.

44:01.680 --> 44:05.680
 And for them not to conflict so much with the host cell that it all goes wrong.

44:05.680 --> 44:07.680
 Perhaps it goes wrong more often than not.

44:07.680 --> 44:10.680
 And then you change the topology of the cell.

44:10.680 --> 44:16.680
 Now, you don't necessarily have any more DNA than a giant bacterium with extreme polyploidy.

44:16.680 --> 44:18.680
 But what you've got is an asymmetry.

44:18.680 --> 44:26.680
 You now have a giant nuclear genome surrounded by lots of subsidiary energetic genomes that do all the...

44:26.680 --> 44:31.680
 They're the control units that are doing all the control of energy generation.

44:31.680 --> 44:35.680
 Could this have been done gradually or does it have to be done?

44:35.680 --> 44:39.680
 The power pack has to be all intact and ready to go and work.

44:39.680 --> 44:44.680
 I mean, it's a kind of step change in the possibilities of evolution, but it doesn't happen overnight.

44:44.680 --> 44:47.680
 It's going to still require multiple, multiple generations.

44:47.680 --> 44:50.680
 So it could take millions of years.

44:50.680 --> 44:52.680
 It could take shorted times.

44:52.680 --> 44:56.680
 I would like to put the number of steps and try and work out what's required at each step.

44:56.680 --> 44:58.680
 We are trying to do that with sex.

44:58.680 --> 45:02.680
 You can't have a very large genome unless you have sex at that point.

45:02.680 --> 45:07.680
 So what are the changes to go from bacterial recombination to eukaryotic recombination?

45:07.680 --> 45:09.680
 What do you need to do?

45:09.680 --> 45:15.680
 Why do we go from passing around bits of DNA as if it's loose change to fusing cells together,

45:15.680 --> 45:18.680
 lining up the chromosomes, recombining across the chromosomes,

45:18.680 --> 45:21.680
 and then going through two rounds of cell division to produce your gametes?

45:21.680 --> 45:23.680
 All eukaryotes do it that way.

45:23.680 --> 45:26.680
 So again, why switch?

45:26.680 --> 45:28.680
 What are the drivers here?

45:28.680 --> 45:29.680
 So there's a lot of time.

45:29.680 --> 45:33.680
 There's a lot of evolution, but as soon as you've got cells living inside another cell,

45:33.680 --> 45:35.680
 what you've got is a new design.

45:35.680 --> 45:38.680
 You've got new potential that you didn't have before.

45:38.680 --> 45:47.680
 So the cell living inside another cell, that design allows for better storage of information,

45:47.680 --> 45:54.680
 better use of energy, more delegation, like a hierarchical control of the whole thing.

45:54.680 --> 45:59.680
 And then somehow that leads to ability to have multi cell organisms.

45:59.680 --> 46:02.680
 I'm not sure that you have hierarchical control necessarily,

46:02.680 --> 46:09.680
 but you've got a system where you can have a much larger information storage depot in the nucleus.

46:09.680 --> 46:11.680
 You can have a much larger genome.

46:11.680 --> 46:17.680
 And that allows multi cellularity, yes, because it allows you...

46:17.680 --> 46:25.680
 It's a funny thing, but to have an animal where I have 70% of my genes switched on in my brain

46:25.680 --> 46:28.680
 and a different 50% switched on in my liver or something,

46:28.680 --> 46:31.680
 you've got to have all those genes in the egg cell at the very beginning,

46:31.680 --> 46:35.680
 and you've got to have a program of development which says,

46:35.680 --> 46:38.680
 okay, you guys switch off those genes and switch on those genes,

46:38.680 --> 46:40.680
 and you guys, you do that.

46:40.680 --> 46:42.680
 All the genes are there at the beginning.

46:42.680 --> 46:44.680
 That means you've got to have a lot of genes in one cell,

46:44.680 --> 46:46.680
 and you've got to be able to maintain them.

46:46.680 --> 46:49.680
 And the problem with bacteria is they don't get close to having enough genes in one cell.

46:49.680 --> 46:53.680
 So if you were to try and make a multi cellular organism from bacteria,

46:53.680 --> 46:56.680
 you'd bring different types of bacteria together and hope they'll cooperate,

46:56.680 --> 46:58.680
 and the reality is they don't.

