1:02:24.680 --> 1:02:33.680
 When was that invented, and poetic and biological ways of putting it?

1:02:33.680 --> 1:02:37.680
 How do you describe a predator and prey relationship?

1:02:37.680 --> 1:02:42.680
 Is it a beautiful dance, or is it a violent atrocity?

1:02:42.680 --> 1:02:44.680
 Well, I guess it's both, isn't it?

1:02:44.680 --> 1:02:46.680
 I mean, when does it start? It starts in bacteria.

1:02:46.680 --> 1:02:49.680
 You see these amazing predators.

1:02:49.680 --> 1:02:54.680
 Well, the Vibrio is one that Lin Margulis used to talk about a lot.

1:02:54.680 --> 1:02:58.680
 It's got a kind of a drill piece that drills through the wall and the membrane of the bacterium,

1:02:58.680 --> 1:03:03.680
 and then it effectively eats the bacterium from just inside the periplasmic space,

1:03:03.680 --> 1:03:05.680
 and makes copies of itself that way.

1:03:05.680 --> 1:03:08.680
 So that's straight predation. There are predators among bacteria.

1:03:08.680 --> 1:03:17.680
 So predation in that, sorry to interrupt, means you murder somebody and use their body as a resource in some way.

1:03:17.680 --> 1:03:18.680
 Yeah.

1:03:18.680 --> 1:03:23.680
 Is it not parasitic in that you need them to be still alive?

1:03:23.680 --> 1:03:26.680
 No, no. I mean, predation is you kill them, really.

1:03:26.680 --> 1:03:27.680
 You murder.

1:03:27.680 --> 1:03:30.680
 Parasites, so you kind of live on them.

1:03:30.680 --> 1:03:35.680
 Okay. But it seems the predator is the really popular tool.

1:03:35.680 --> 1:03:44.680
 So what we see if we go back 560, 570 million years before the Cambrian explosion,

1:03:44.680 --> 1:03:51.680
 is what's known as the Ediacaran fauna, or sometimes they call Vendobionts, which is a lovely name.

1:03:51.680 --> 1:03:55.680
 And it's not obvious that they're animals at all.

1:03:55.680 --> 1:03:56.680
 They're stalked things.

1:03:56.680 --> 1:04:02.680
 They often have fronds that look a lot like leaves with kind of fractal branching patterns on them.

1:04:02.680 --> 1:04:11.680
 And the thing is, they're found sometimes geologists can figure out the environment that they were in

1:04:11.680 --> 1:04:15.680
 and say, this is more than 200 meters deep because there's no sign of any waves.

1:04:15.680 --> 1:04:19.680
 There's no storm damage down here, this kind of thing.

1:04:19.680 --> 1:04:22.680
 They were more than 200 meters deep, so they're definitely not photosynthetic.

1:04:22.680 --> 1:04:24.680
 These are animals.

1:04:24.680 --> 1:04:26.680
 And they're filter feeders.

1:04:26.680 --> 1:04:29.680
 And we know sponges and corals and things are filter feeding animals.

1:04:29.680 --> 1:04:31.680
 They're stuck to the spot.

1:04:31.680 --> 1:04:37.680
 And little bits of carbon that come their way, they filter it out and that's what they're eating.

1:04:37.680 --> 1:04:41.680
 So no predation involved in this, beyond stuff just dies anyway.

1:04:41.680 --> 1:04:46.680
 And it feels like a very gentle, rather beautiful, rather limited world, you might say.

1:04:46.680 --> 1:04:49.680
 There's not a lot going on there.

1:04:49.680 --> 1:04:52.680
 And something changes.

1:04:52.680 --> 1:04:54.680
 Oxygen definitely changes during this period.

1:04:54.680 --> 1:04:56.680
 Other things may have changed as well.

1:04:56.680 --> 1:05:00.680
 But the next thing you really see in the fossil record is the Cambrian explosion.

1:05:00.680 --> 1:05:02.680
 And what do we see there?

1:05:02.680 --> 1:05:05.680
 We're now seeing animals that we would recognize.

1:05:05.680 --> 1:05:08.680
 They've got eyes, they've got claws, they've got shells.

1:05:08.680 --> 1:05:14.680
 They're plainly killing things or running away and hiding.

1:05:14.680 --> 1:05:24.680
 And so we've gone from a rather gentle but limited world to a rather vicious, unpleasant world that we recognize.

1:05:24.680 --> 1:05:30.680
 And which leads to kind of arms races, evolutionary arms races.

1:05:30.680 --> 1:05:35.680
 Which again is something that when we think about a nuclear arms race, we think, Jesus, we don't want to go there.

1:05:35.680 --> 1:05:37.680
 It's not done anybody any good.

1:05:37.680 --> 1:05:40.680
 In some ways, maybe it does do good.

1:05:40.680 --> 1:05:43.680
 I don't want to make an argument for nuclear arms.

1:05:43.680 --> 1:05:53.680
 But predation as a mechanism forces organisms to adapt to change to be better to escape or to kill.

1:05:53.680 --> 1:05:55.680
 If you need to eat, then you've got to eat.

1:05:55.680 --> 1:06:03.680
 And a cheetah is not going to run at that speed unless it has to because the zebra is capable of escaping.

1:06:03.680 --> 1:06:09.680
 So it leads to much greater feats of evolution would ever have been possible without it.

1:06:09.680 --> 1:06:12.680
 And in the end, to a much more beautiful world.

1:06:12.680 --> 1:06:17.680
 And so it's not all bad by any means.

1:06:17.680 --> 1:06:20.680
 But the thing is you can't have this if you don't have an oxygenated planet.

1:06:20.680 --> 1:06:25.680
 Because it's all in the end, it's about how much energy can you extract from the food you eat.

1:06:25.680 --> 1:06:31.680
 And if you don't have an oxygenated planet, you can get about 10% out, not much more than that.

1:06:31.680 --> 1:06:35.680
 And if you've got an oxygenated planet, you can get about 40% out.

1:06:35.680 --> 1:06:42.680
 And that means you can have instead of having one or two trophic levels, you can have five or six trophic levels.

1:06:42.680 --> 1:06:45.680
 And that means things can eat things that eat other things and so on.

1:06:45.680 --> 1:06:51.680
 And you've gone to a level of ecological complexity, which is completely impossible in the absence of oxygen.

1:06:51.680 --> 1:07:01.680
 This reminds me of the Hunter S. Thompson quote, that for every moment of triumph, for every instance of beauty, many souls must be trampled.

1:07:01.680 --> 1:07:16.680
 The history of life on earth, unfortunately, is that of violence, just the trillions and trillions of multi cell organisms that were murdered in the struggle for survival.

1:07:16.680 --> 1:07:19.680
 It's a sorry statement, but yes, it's basically true.

1:07:19.680 --> 1:07:29.680
 And that somehow is a catalyst from an evolutionary perspective for creativity, for creating more and more complex organisms that are better and better at surviving.

1:07:29.680 --> 1:07:35.680
 I mean, survival of the fittest, if you just go back to that old phrase, means death the weakest.

1:07:35.680 --> 1:07:40.680
 Now, what's fit, what's weak, these are terms that don't have much intrinsic meaning.

1:07:40.680 --> 1:07:44.680
 But the thing is, evolution only happens because of death.

1:07:44.680 --> 1:07:51.680
 One way to die is the constraints, the scarcity of the resources and the environment.

1:07:51.680 --> 1:08:00.680
 But that seems to be not nearly as good of a mechanism for death than other creatures roaming about in the environment.

1:08:00.680 --> 1:08:03.680
 When I say environment, I mean like the static environment.

1:08:03.680 --> 1:08:09.680
 But then there's the dynamic environment of bigger things trying to eat you and use you for your energy.

1:08:09.680 --> 1:08:18.680
 It forces you to come up with a solution to your specific problem that is inventive and is new and hasn't been done before.

1:08:18.680 --> 1:08:25.680
 And so it forces, I mean, literally change, literally evolution on populations.

1:08:25.680 --> 1:08:27.680
 They have to become different.

1:08:27.680 --> 1:08:39.680
 And it's interesting that humans have channeled that into more, I mean, I guess what humans are doing is they're inventing more productive and safe ways of doing that.

1:08:39.680 --> 1:08:49.680
 This whole idea of morality and all those kinds of things, I think they ultimately lead to competition versus violence.

1:08:49.680 --> 1:08:55.680
 Because I think violence can have a cold, brutal, inefficient aspect to it.

1:08:55.680 --> 1:09:04.680
 But if you channel that into more controlled competition in the space of ideas, in the space of approaches to life,

1:09:04.680 --> 1:09:09.680
 maybe you can be even more productive than evolution is.

1:09:09.680 --> 1:09:11.680
 Because evolution is very wasteful.

1:09:11.680 --> 1:09:18.680
 Like the amount of murder required to really test a good idea, genetically speaking, is just a lot.

1:09:18.680 --> 1:09:20.680
 Many, many, many generations.

1:09:20.680 --> 1:09:25.680
 Morally, we cannot base society on the way that evolution works.

1:09:25.680 --> 1:09:26.680
 That's an invention, right?

1:09:26.680 --> 1:09:30.680
 But actually, in some respects, we do, which is to say, this is how science works.

1:09:30.680 --> 1:09:34.680
 We have competing hypotheses that have to get better, otherwise they die.

1:09:34.680 --> 1:09:36.680
 It's the way that society works.

1:09:36.680 --> 1:09:41.680
 In ancient Greece, we had the Athens and Sparta and city states.

1:09:41.680 --> 1:09:44.680
 And then we had the Renaissance and nation states.

1:09:44.680 --> 1:09:47.680
 And universities compete with each other.

1:09:47.680 --> 1:09:51.680
 A tremendous amount of companies competing with each other all the time.

1:09:51.680 --> 1:09:53.680
 It drives innovation.

1:09:53.680 --> 1:10:03.680
 And if we want to do it without all the death that we see in nature, then we have to have some kind of societal level control that says,

1:10:03.680 --> 1:10:06.680
 well, there's some limits, guys, and these are what the limits are going to be.

1:10:06.680 --> 1:10:10.680
 And society as a whole has to say, right, we want to limit the amount of death here.

1:10:10.680 --> 1:10:12.680
 So you can't do this and you can't do that.

1:10:12.680 --> 1:10:13.680
 And who makes up these rules?

1:10:13.680 --> 1:10:14.680
 And how do we know?

1:10:14.680 --> 1:10:22.680
 It's a tough thing, but it's basically trying to find a moral basis for avoiding the death of evolution and natural selection.

1:10:22.680 --> 1:10:26.680
 And keeping the innovation and the richness of it.

1:10:26.680 --> 1:10:31.680
 I forgot who said it, but that murder is illegal.

1:10:31.680 --> 1:10:37.680
 Probably curve, I don't get murder is illegal, except when it's done to the sound of trumpets and at a large scale.

1:10:37.680 --> 1:10:40.680
 So we still have wars.

1:10:40.680 --> 1:10:46.680
 But we are struggling with this idea that murder is a bad thing.

1:10:46.680 --> 1:10:57.680
 It's so interesting how we're channeling the best of the evolutionary imperative and trying to get rid of the stuff that's not productive.

1:10:57.680 --> 1:11:05.680
 So trying to almost accelerate evolution, the same kind of thing that makes evolution creative.

1:11:05.680 --> 1:11:06.680
 We're trying to use that.

1:11:06.680 --> 1:11:08.680
 I think we naturally do it.

1:11:08.680 --> 1:11:10.680
 I mean, I don't think we can help ourselves do it.

1:11:10.680 --> 1:11:16.680
 Capitalism as a form is basically about competition and differential rewards.

1:11:16.680 --> 1:11:22.680
 But society and we have a...

1:11:22.680 --> 1:11:29.680
 I keep using this word moral obligation, but we cannot operate as a society if we go that way.

1:11:29.680 --> 1:11:34.680
 It's interesting that we've had problems achieving balance.

1:11:34.680 --> 1:11:40.680
 So for example, in the financial crash in 2009, do you let banks go to the wall or not?

1:11:40.680 --> 1:11:42.680
 This is kind of question.

1:11:42.680 --> 1:11:44.680
 In evolution, certainly you let them go to the wall.

1:11:44.680 --> 1:11:50.680
 And in that sense, you don't need the regulation because they just die.

1:11:50.680 --> 1:11:58.680
 Whereas if we as a society think about what's required for society as a whole, then you don't necessarily let them go to the wall.

1:11:58.680 --> 1:12:07.680
 In which case you then have to impose some kind of regulation that the bankers themselves will in an evolutionary manner exploit.

1:12:07.680 --> 1:12:08.680
 Yeah.

1:12:08.680 --> 1:12:19.680
 We've been struggling with this kind of idea of capitalism, the cold brutality of capitalism that seems to create so much beautiful things in this world.

1:12:19.680 --> 1:12:26.680
 And then the ideals of communism that seem to create so much brutal destruction in history.

1:12:26.680 --> 1:12:30.680
 And we struggle with ideas of, well, maybe we didn't do it right.

1:12:30.680 --> 1:12:31.680
 How can we do things better?

1:12:31.680 --> 1:12:35.680
 And then the ideas are the things we're playing with as opposed to people.

1:12:35.680 --> 1:12:38.680
 If a PhD student has a bad idea, we don't shoot the PhD student.

1:12:38.680 --> 1:12:41.680
 We just criticize their idea and hope they improve.

1:12:41.680 --> 1:12:43.680
 You have a very humane lamp.

1:12:43.680 --> 1:12:44.680
 Yeah.

1:12:44.680 --> 1:12:46.680
 I don't know how you guys do it.

1:12:46.680 --> 1:12:49.680
 The way I run things, it's always life and death.

1:12:49.680 --> 1:13:01.680
 So it isn't interesting about humans that there is an inner sense of morality, which begs the question of how did homo sapiens evolve?

1:13:01.680 --> 1:13:14.680
 If we think about the invention of early invention of sex and early invention of predation, what was the thing invented to make humans?

1:13:14.680 --> 1:13:16.680
 What would you say?

1:13:16.680 --> 1:13:19.680
 I suppose a couple of things I'd say.

1:13:19.680 --> 1:13:26.680
 Number one is you don't have to wind the clock back very far, five, six million years or so, and let it run forwards again.

1:13:26.680 --> 1:13:31.680
 And the chances of humans, as we know them, is not necessarily that high.

1:13:31.680 --> 1:13:36.680
 Imagine as an alien, you find planet Earth and it's got everything apart from humans on it.

1:13:36.680 --> 1:13:39.680
 It's an amazing, wonderful, marvelous planet.

1:13:39.680 --> 1:13:45.680
 But nothing that we would recognize as extremely intelligent life and space varying civilization.

1:13:45.680 --> 1:13:51.680
 So when we think about aliens, we're kind of after something like ourselves or after a space faring civilization.

1:13:51.680 --> 1:13:55.680
 We're not after zebras and giraffes and lions and things.

1:13:55.680 --> 1:13:57.680
 Amazing though they are.

1:13:57.680 --> 1:14:12.680
 But the additional kind of evolutionary steps to go from large complex mammals, monkeys, let's say, to humans doesn't strike me as that long a distance.

1:14:12.680 --> 1:14:16.680
 It's all about the brain and where's the brain and morality coming from?

1:14:16.680 --> 1:14:21.680
 It seems to me to be all about groups, human groups and interactions between groups.

1:14:21.680 --> 1:14:23.680
 The collective intelligence of it.

1:14:23.680 --> 1:14:26.680
 Yes, the interactions really.

1:14:26.680 --> 1:14:33.680
 And there's a guy at UCL called Mark Thomas who's done a lot of really beautiful work, I think, on this kind of question.

1:14:33.680 --> 1:14:34.680
 So I talk to him every now and then.

1:14:34.680 --> 1:14:38.680
 So my view is influenced by him.

1:14:38.680 --> 1:14:42.680
 But a lot seems to depend on population density.

1:14:42.680 --> 1:14:56.680
 The more interactions you have going on between different groups, the more transfer of information, if you like, between groups of people moving from one group to another group, almost like lateral gene transfer in bacteria.

1:14:56.680 --> 1:15:07.680
 The more expertise you're able to develop and maintain, the more culturally complex your society can become and groups that have become detached.

1:15:07.680 --> 1:15:13.680
 Like on Easter Island, for example, very often degenerate in terms of the complexity of their civilization.

1:15:13.680 --> 1:15:15.680
 Is that true for complex organisms in general?

1:15:15.680 --> 1:15:18.680
 Population density is often productive.

1:15:18.680 --> 1:15:19.680
 Really matters.

1:15:19.680 --> 1:15:28.680
 But in human terms, I don't know what the actual factors were that were driving a large brain.

1:15:28.680 --> 1:15:30.680
 But you can talk about fire.

1:15:30.680 --> 1:15:32.680
 You can talk about tool use.

1:15:32.680 --> 1:15:33.680
 You can talk about language.

1:15:33.680 --> 1:15:42.680
 And none of them seem to correlate especially well with the actual known trajectory of human evolution in terms of cave art and these kind of things.

1:15:42.680 --> 1:15:50.680
 That seems to work much better just with population density and number of interactions between different groups.

1:15:50.680 --> 1:15:58.680
 All of which is really about human interactions, human human interactions and the complexity of those.

1:15:58.680 --> 1:16:03.680
 But population density is the thing that increases the number of interactions.

1:16:03.680 --> 1:16:14.680
 But then there must have been inventions forced by that number of interactions that actually led to humans.

1:16:14.680 --> 1:16:21.680
 So like Richard Rangham talks about that it's basically the beta males had to beat up the alpha male.

1:16:21.680 --> 1:16:35.680
 So that's what collaboration looks like is when you're living together, our early ancestors don't like the dictatorial aspect of a single individual at the top of a tribe.

1:16:35.680 --> 1:16:46.680
 So they learn to collaborate how to basically create a democracy of sorts, a democracy that prevents, minimizes or lessens the amount of violence.

1:16:46.680 --> 1:16:54.680
 Which essentially gives strength to the tribe and make the war between tribes versus the dictator.

1:16:54.680 --> 1:16:59.680
 I mean, I think one of the most wonderful things about humans is where all of those things.

1:16:59.680 --> 1:17:04.680
 I mean, we are deeply social as a species and we're also deeply selfish.

1:17:04.680 --> 1:17:10.680
 And it seems to me the conflict between capitalism and communism is really just two aspects of human nature, both of which are.

1:17:10.680 --> 1:17:11.680
 We have both.

1:17:11.680 --> 1:17:12.680
 We have both.

1:17:12.680 --> 1:17:15.680
 And we have a constant kind of vying between the two sides.

1:17:15.680 --> 1:17:20.680
 We really do care about other people beyond our families, beyond our immediate people.

1:17:20.680 --> 1:17:23.680
 We care about society and the society that we live in.

1:17:23.680 --> 1:17:28.680
 And you could say that's a, you know, a drawing towards socialism or communism on the other side.

1:17:28.680 --> 1:17:30.680
 We really do care about ourselves.

1:17:30.680 --> 1:17:34.680
 We really do care about our families about working for something that we gain from.

1:17:34.680 --> 1:17:35.680
 And that's the capitalist side of it.

1:17:35.680 --> 1:17:38.680
 They're both really deeply ingrained in human nature.

1:17:38.680 --> 1:17:46.680
 In terms of violence and interactions between groups, yes, all this dynamic of if you're interacting between groups,

1:17:46.680 --> 1:17:52.680
 you can be certain that they're going to be burning each other and all kinds of physical violent interactions as well,

1:17:52.680 --> 1:17:57.680
 which will drive the kind of cleverness of how do you resist this?

1:17:57.680 --> 1:17:58.680
 Let's build a tower.

1:17:58.680 --> 1:18:04.680
 Let's see, what are we going to do to prevent being overrun by those marauding gangs from over there?

1:18:04.680 --> 1:18:10.680
 And you look, you look outside humans and you look at chimps and bonobos and so on,

1:18:10.680 --> 1:18:12.680
 and they're very, very different structures to society.

1:18:12.680 --> 1:18:18.680
 Chimps tend to have an aggressive alpha male type structure and bonobos are, you know,

1:18:18.680 --> 1:18:22.680
 there's basically a female society where the males are predominantly excluded

1:18:22.680 --> 1:18:24.680
 and only brought in at the behest of the female.

1:18:24.680 --> 1:18:28.680
 We have a lot in common with both of those groups.

1:18:28.680 --> 1:18:30.680
 And there's again tension there.

1:18:30.680 --> 1:18:34.680
 And probably chimps, more violence of bonobos, probably more sex.

1:18:34.680 --> 1:18:36.680
 That's another tension.

1:18:36.680 --> 1:18:41.680
 How serious do we want to be?

1:18:41.680 --> 1:18:43.680
 How much fun we want to be?

1:18:43.680 --> 1:18:47.680
 Asking for a friend again, what do you think happened to Neanderthals?

1:18:47.680 --> 1:18:52.680
 What did we cheeky humans do to the Neanderthals, homo sapiens?

1:18:52.680 --> 1:18:54.680
 Do you think we murdered them?

1:18:54.680 --> 1:18:56.680
 How do we murder them?

1:18:56.680 --> 1:18:58.680
 How do we outcompete them?

1:18:58.680 --> 1:19:00.680
 Do we outmate them?

1:19:00.680 --> 1:19:01.680
 I don't know.

1:19:01.680 --> 1:19:05.680
 I mean, I think there's unequivocal evidence that we mated with them.

1:19:05.680 --> 1:19:07.680
 We always try to mate with everything.

1:19:07.680 --> 1:19:08.680
 Yes, pretty much.

1:19:08.680 --> 1:19:13.680
 There's some interesting, the first sequences that came along were in mitochondrial DNA.

1:19:13.680 --> 1:19:17.680
 And that was back to about 2002 or thereabouts.

1:19:17.680 --> 1:19:22.680
 What was found was that Neanderthal mitochondrial DNA was very different to human mitochondria.

1:19:22.680 --> 1:19:23.680
 Oh, that's so interesting.

1:19:23.680 --> 1:19:28.680
 You could do a clock on it and they said the divergent state was about 600,000 years ago or something like that.

1:19:28.680 --> 1:19:30.680
 So not so long ago.

1:19:30.680 --> 1:19:35.680
 And then the first full genomes were sequenced maybe 10 years after that.

1:19:35.680 --> 1:19:39.680
 And they showed plenty of signs of mating between.

1:19:39.680 --> 1:19:42.680
 So the mitochondrial DNA effectively says no mating.

1:19:42.680 --> 1:19:47.680
 And the nuclear genes say, yeah, lots of mating.

1:19:47.680 --> 1:19:53.680
 So can you explain the difference between mitochondrial DNA and nucleus?

1:19:53.680 --> 1:19:56.680
 I've talked before about the mitochondria, which are the power packs in cells.

1:19:56.680 --> 1:20:00.680
 These are the paired down control units is their DNA.

1:20:00.680 --> 1:20:03.680
 So it's passed on by the mother only.

1:20:03.680 --> 1:20:09.680
 And in the egg cell, we might have half a million copies of mitochondrial DNA.

1:20:09.680 --> 1:20:16.680
 There's only 37 genes left and they do basically the control unit of energy production.

1:20:16.680 --> 1:20:18.680
 That's what it's doing.

1:20:18.680 --> 1:20:21.680
 It's a basic old school machine that does.

1:20:21.680 --> 1:20:28.680
 And it's got genes that were considered to be effectively trivial because they did a very narrowly defined job.

1:20:28.680 --> 1:20:35.680
 But they're not trivial in the sense that that narrowly defined job is about everything that is being alive.

1:20:35.680 --> 1:20:37.680
 So they're much easier to sequence.

1:20:37.680 --> 1:20:41.680
 You've got many more copies of these things and you can sequence them very quickly.

1:20:41.680 --> 1:20:49.680
 But the problem is because they go down only the maternal line from mother to daughter, your mitochondrial DNA and mine is going nowhere.

1:20:49.680 --> 1:20:51.680
 Doesn't matter any kids we have.

1:20:51.680 --> 1:20:59.680
 They get their mother's mitochondrial DNA, except in very, very rare and strange circumstances.

1:20:59.680 --> 1:21:06.680
 And so it tells a different story and it's not a story which is easy to reconcile always.

1:21:06.680 --> 1:21:17.680
 And what it seems to suggest to my mind at least is that there was one way traffic of genes probably going from humans into Neanderthals rather than the other way around.

1:21:17.680 --> 1:21:19.680
 Why did the Neanderthals disappear?

1:21:19.680 --> 1:21:20.680
 I don't know.

1:21:20.680 --> 1:21:31.680
 I suspect that they were probably less violent, less clever, less populace, less willing to fight.

1:21:31.680 --> 1:21:32.680
 I don't know.

1:21:32.680 --> 1:21:36.680
 I mean, I think I already drove them to extinction at the margins of Europe.

1:21:36.680 --> 1:21:55.680
 And it's interesting how much, if we ran Earth over and over again, how many of these branches of intelligent beings that have figured out some kind of how to leverage collective intelligence, which ones of them emerge, which ones of them succeed?

1:21:55.680 --> 1:21:57.680
 Is it the more violent ones?

1:21:57.680 --> 1:22:01.680
 Is it the more isolated ones?

1:22:01.680 --> 1:22:03.680
 What dynamics result in more productivity?

1:22:03.680 --> 1:22:05.680
 And I suppose we'll never know.

1:22:05.680 --> 1:22:10.680
 The more complex the organism, the harder it is to run the experiment in the lab.

1:22:10.680 --> 1:22:11.680
 Yes.

1:22:11.680 --> 1:22:14.680
 And in some respects, maybe it's best if we don't know.

1:22:14.680 --> 1:22:15.680
 Yeah.

1:22:15.680 --> 1:22:17.680
 The truth might be very painful.

1:22:17.680 --> 1:22:24.680
 What about if we actually step back a couple of interesting things that we humans do?

1:22:24.680 --> 1:22:28.680
 One is object manipulation and movement.

1:22:28.680 --> 1:22:31.680
 And of course, movement was something that was done.

1:22:31.680 --> 1:22:35.680
 That was another big invention, being able to move around the environment.

1:22:35.680 --> 1:22:40.680
 And the other one is this sensory mechanism, how we sense the environment.

1:22:40.680 --> 1:22:44.680
 One of the coolest, high definition ones is vision.

1:22:44.680 --> 1:22:50.680
 How big are those inventions in the history of life on Earth?

1:22:50.680 --> 1:23:00.680
 Vision, movement, again, extremely important, going back to the origin of animals, the Cambrian explosion, where suddenly you're seeing eyes in the fossil record.

1:23:00.680 --> 1:23:07.680
 And it's not necessarily, again, lots of people historically have said what use is half an eye.

1:23:07.680 --> 1:23:20.680
 You can go in a series of steps from a light sensitive spot on a flat piece of tissue to an eyeball with a lens and so on.

1:23:20.680 --> 1:23:29.680
 If you assume no more than, I don't remember this, but this was a specific model that I have in mind, but it was one percent change or half a percent change for each generation.

1:23:29.680 --> 1:23:31.680
 How long would it take to evolve an eye as we know it?

1:23:31.680 --> 1:23:33.680
 And the answer is half a million years.

1:23:33.680 --> 1:23:38.680
 It doesn't have to take long. That's not how evolution works. That's not an answer to the question.

1:23:38.680 --> 1:23:44.680
 It just shows you can reconstruct the steps and you can work out roughly how it can work.

1:23:44.680 --> 1:23:48.680
 So it's not that big a deal to evolve an eye.

1:23:48.680 --> 1:23:51.680
 But once you have one, then there's no way to hide.

1:23:51.680 --> 1:23:54.680
 And again, we're back to predator prey relationships.

1:23:54.680 --> 1:23:57.680
 We're back to all the benefits that being able to see brings you.

1:23:57.680 --> 1:24:03.680
 And if you think philosophically what bats are doing with the eco location and so on, I have no idea.

1:24:03.680 --> 1:24:07.680
 But I suspect that they form an image of the world in pretty much the same way that we do.

1:24:07.680 --> 1:24:09.680
 It's just a matter of mental reconstruction.

1:24:09.680 --> 1:24:21.680
 So I suppose the other thing about sight, there are single celled organisms that have got a lens and a retina and a cornea and so on.

1:24:21.680 --> 1:24:24.680
 Basically, they've got a camera tie by in a single cell.

1:24:24.680 --> 1:24:26.680
 They don't have a brain.

1:24:26.680 --> 1:24:30.680
 What they understand about their world is impossible to say.

1:24:30.680 --> 1:24:34.680
 But they're capable of coming up with the same structures to do so.

1:24:34.680 --> 1:24:38.680
 So I suppose then is that once you've got things like eyes,

1:24:38.680 --> 1:24:43.680
 then you have a big driving pressure on the central nervous system to figure out what it all means.

1:24:43.680 --> 1:24:47.680
 And we come around to your other point about manipulation, sensory input and so on.

1:24:47.680 --> 1:24:58.680
 Now you have a huge requirement to understand what your environment is and what it means and how it reacts and where you should run away and where you should stay put.

1:24:58.680 --> 1:25:08.680
 Actually, on that point, let me, I don't know if you know the work of Donald Hoffman who talks about, who uses the argument,

1:25:08.680 --> 1:25:22.680
 the mechanism of evolution to say that there's not necessarily a strong evolutionary value to seeing the world as it is.

1:25:22.680 --> 1:25:29.680
 So objective reality, that our perception actually is very different from what's objectively real.

1:25:29.680 --> 1:25:41.680
 We're living inside an illusion and we're basically the entire set of species on Earth, I think, I guess are competing in a space that's an illusion that's distinct from,

1:25:41.680 --> 1:25:45.680
 that's far away from physical reality as it is defined by physics.

1:25:45.680 --> 1:25:48.680
 I'm not sure it's an illusion so much as a bubble.

1:25:48.680 --> 1:25:53.680
 I mean, we have a sensory input which is a fraction of what we could have a sensory input on.

1:25:53.680 --> 1:25:57.680
 And we interpret it in terms of what's useful for us to know to stay alive.

1:25:57.680 --> 1:26:03.680
 So yes, it's an illusion in that sense, but the tree is physically there.

1:26:03.680 --> 1:26:09.680
 And if you walk into that tree, there is, it's not purely a delusion of some physical reality to it.

1:26:09.680 --> 1:26:18.680
 So it's a sensory slice into reality as it is, but because it's just a slice, you're missing a big picture.

1:26:18.680 --> 1:26:25.680
 But he says that that slice doesn't necessarily need to be a slice, it could be a complete fabrication.

1:26:25.680 --> 1:26:39.680
 That's just consistent amongst the species, which is an interesting or at least it's a humbling realization that our perception is limited and our cognitive abilities are limited.

1:26:39.680 --> 1:26:44.680
 And at least to me, it's argument from evolution.

1:26:44.680 --> 1:26:54.680
 I don't know how much, how strong that is as an argument, but I do think that life can exist in the mind.

1:26:54.680 --> 1:26:56.680
 Yes.

1:26:56.680 --> 1:27:02.680
 In the same way that you can do a virtual reality video game and you can have a vibrant life inside that place.

1:27:02.680 --> 1:27:13.680
 And that place is not real in some sense, but you can still have a vibrant, all the same forces of evolution, all the same competition, the dynamics between humans you can have.

1:27:13.680 --> 1:27:23.680
 But I don't know if, I don't know if there's evidence for that being the thing that happened on Earth.

1:27:23.680 --> 1:27:24.680
 It seems that Earth...

1:27:24.680 --> 1:27:29.680
 I think in either environment, I wouldn't deny that you could have exactly the world that you talk about.

1:27:29.680 --> 1:27:41.680
 And it would be very difficult to, you know, the idea in Matrix movies and so on that the whole world is completely a construction.

1:27:41.680 --> 1:27:43.680
 And we're fundamentally deluded.

1:27:43.680 --> 1:27:51.680
 It's difficult to say that's impossible or couldn't happen and certainly we construct in our minds what the outside world is.

1:27:51.680 --> 1:27:59.680
 But we do it on input and that input, I would hesitate to say it's not real because it's precisely how we do understand the world.

1:27:59.680 --> 1:28:08.680
 We, you know, we have eyes, but if you keep someone in this, apparently this kind of thing happens, someone kept in a dark room for five years or something like that.

1:28:08.680 --> 1:28:17.680
 And they never see properly again, because the neural wiring that underpins how we interpret vision never developed.

1:28:17.680 --> 1:28:24.680
 You know, you need, when you watch a child develop, it walks into a table, it bangs his head on the table and it hurts.

1:28:24.680 --> 1:28:27.680
 And now you've got two inputs.

1:28:27.680 --> 1:28:32.680
 You've got one pain from this sharp edge and number two, you've touched it and realized it's there.

1:28:32.680 --> 1:28:37.680
 It's a sharp edge and you've got the visual input and you put the three things together and think, I don't want to walk into a table again.

1:28:37.680 --> 1:28:42.680
 So you're learning and it's a limited reality, but it's a true reality.

1:28:42.680 --> 1:28:48.680
 And if you don't learn that properly, then you will get eaten, you will get hit by a bus, you will not survive.

1:28:48.680 --> 1:28:55.680
 And same if you're in some kind of, let's say, computer construction of reality.

1:28:55.680 --> 1:29:04.680
 I'm not in my ground here, but if you construct the laws that this is what reality is inside this, then you play by those laws.

1:29:04.680 --> 1:29:06.680
 Yeah, well, I mean, as long as the laws are consistent.

1:29:06.680 --> 1:29:14.680
 So just like you said in the lab, the interesting thing about the simulation question, yes, it's hard to know if we're living inside a simulation,

1:29:14.680 --> 1:29:19.680
 but also, yes, it's possible to do these kinds of experiments in the lab now.

1:29:19.680 --> 1:29:29.680
 More and more, to me, the interesting question is how realistic does a virtual reality game need to be for us to not be able to tell the difference?

1:29:29.680 --> 1:29:42.680
 A more interesting question to me is how realistic or interesting does a virtual reality world need to be in order for us to want to stay there forever,

1:29:42.680 --> 1:29:47.680
 or much longer than physical reality, prefer that place.

1:29:47.680 --> 1:29:57.680
 And also prefer it not as we prefer hard drugs, but prefer it in a deep, meaningful way in the way we enjoy life.

1:29:57.680 --> 1:30:06.680
 I mean, I suppose the issue with the matrix, I imagine that it's possible to delude the mind sufficiently that you genuinely, in that way,

1:30:06.680 --> 1:30:13.680
 do think that you are interacting with the real world when, in fact, the whole thing's a simulation.

1:30:13.680 --> 1:30:16.680
 How good does a simulation need to be to be able to do that?

1:30:16.680 --> 1:30:26.680
 Well, it needs to convince you that all your sensory input is correct and accurate and joins up and makes sense.

1:30:26.680 --> 1:30:32.680
 Now, that sensory input is not something that we're born with, we're born with a sense of touch, we're born with eyes and so on,

1:30:32.680 --> 1:30:35.680
 but we don't know how to use them, we don't know what to make of them.

1:30:35.680 --> 1:30:47.680
 We go around, we bump into trees, we cry a lot, we're in pain a lot, we're basically booting up the system so that it can make head a tail of the sensory input that it's getting.

1:30:47.680 --> 1:30:53.680
 And that sensory input is not just a one way flux of things, it's also you have to walk into things, you have to hear things, you have to put it together.

1:30:53.680 --> 1:31:02.680
 Now, if you've got just babies in the matrix who are slotted into this, I don't think they have that kind of sensory input.

1:31:02.680 --> 1:31:08.680
 I don't think they would have any way to make sense of New York as a world that they're part of.

1:31:08.680 --> 1:31:10.680
 The brain is just not developed in that way.

1:31:10.680 --> 1:31:13.680
 Well, I can't make sense of New York in this physical reality either.

1:31:13.680 --> 1:31:25.680
 But you said pain and the walking into things, well, you can create a pain signal and as long as it's consistent that certain things result in pain, you can start to construct a reality.

1:31:25.680 --> 1:31:38.680
 There are some, maybe you disagree with this, but I think we are born almost with a desire to be convinced by our reality, like a desire to make sense of our reality.

1:31:38.680 --> 1:31:39.680
 Oh, I'm sure we are, yes.

1:31:39.680 --> 1:31:55.680
 So there's an imperative, so whatever that reality is given to us, like the table hurts, fire is hot, I think we want to be deluded in the sense that we want to make a simple Einstein simple theory of the thing around us.

1:31:55.680 --> 1:31:57.680
 We want that simplicity.

1:31:57.680 --> 1:32:07.680
 And so maybe the hunger for the simplicity is the thing that could be used to construct a pretty dumb simulation that tricks us.

1:32:07.680 --> 1:32:10.680
 So maybe tricking humans doesn't require building a universe.

1:32:10.680 --> 1:32:15.680
 No, I don't, I mean, this is not what I work on, so I don't know how close to it we are.

1:32:15.680 --> 1:32:25.680
 But I agree with you that, yeah, I'm not sure that it's a morally justifiable thing to do, but is it possible in principle?

1:32:25.680 --> 1:32:31.680
 I think it would be very difficult, but I don't see why in principle it wouldn't be possible.

1:32:31.680 --> 1:32:41.680
 I agree with you that we try to understand the world, we try to integrate the sensory inputs that we have, and we try to come up with a hypothesis that explains what's going on.

1:32:41.680 --> 1:32:48.680
 I think, though, that we have huge input from the social context that we're in.

1:32:48.680 --> 1:32:50.680
 We don't do it by ourselves.

1:32:50.680 --> 1:32:55.680
 We don't kind of blunder around in a universe by ourselves and understand the whole thing.

1:32:55.680 --> 1:33:01.680
 We're told by the people around us what things are and what they do and languages coming in here and so on.

1:33:01.680 --> 1:33:07.680
 So it would have to be an extremely impressive simulation to simulate all of that.

1:33:07.680 --> 1:33:15.680
 Yeah, simulate all of that, including the social construct, the thing, the spread of ideas and the exchange of ideas.

1:33:15.680 --> 1:33:21.680
 I don't know, but those questions are really important to understand as we become more and more digital creatures.

1:33:21.680 --> 1:33:25.680
 It seems like the next step of evolution is us becoming partial.

1:33:25.680 --> 1:33:31.680
 All the same mechanisms we've talked about are becoming more and more plugged in into the machine.

1:33:31.680 --> 1:33:43.680
 We're becoming cyborgs, and there's an interesting interplay between wires and biology, you know, zeros and ones and the biological systems.

1:33:43.680 --> 1:33:52.680
 I don't think we'll have the luxury to see humans as disjoint from the technology we've created for much longer.

1:33:52.680 --> 1:33:55.680
 We are an organism that's...

1:33:55.680 --> 1:34:07.680
 Yeah, I mean, I agree with you, but we come really with this to consciousness and is there a distinction there?

1:34:07.680 --> 1:34:16.680
 Because what you're saying, the natural end point says we are indistinguishable that if you are capable of building an AI

1:34:16.680 --> 1:34:27.680
 which is sufficiently close and similar that we merge with it, then to all intents and purposes, that AI is conscious as we know it.

1:34:27.680 --> 1:34:34.680
 And I don't have a strong view, but I have a view.

1:34:34.680 --> 1:34:45.680
 And I wrote about it in the epilogue to my last book because 10 years ago I wrote a chapter in a book called Life Ascending about consciousness.

1:34:45.680 --> 1:34:53.680
 And the subtitle of Life Ascending was the 10 Great Inventions of Evolution, and I couldn't possibly write a book with a subtitle like that that did not include consciousness,

1:34:53.680 --> 1:34:58.680
 and specifically consciousness as one of the great inventions.

1:34:58.680 --> 1:35:05.680
 And it was in part because I was just curious to know more and I read more for that chapter. I never worked on it, but I've always...

1:35:05.680 --> 1:35:08.680
 How can anyone not be interested in the question?

1:35:08.680 --> 1:35:20.680
 And I was left with the feeling that A, nobody knows, and B, there are two main schools of thought out there with a big kind of skew in distribution.

1:35:20.680 --> 1:35:29.680
 One of them says, oh, it's a property of matter, it's an unknown law of physics, panpsychism, everything is conscious, the sun is conscious, it's just a matter of...

1:35:29.680 --> 1:35:32.680
 Or a rock is conscious, it's just a matter of how much.

1:35:32.680 --> 1:35:35.680
 And I find that very unpersuasive.

1:35:35.680 --> 1:35:44.680
 I can't say that it's wrong, it's just that I think we somehow can tell the difference between something that's living and something that's not.

1:35:44.680 --> 1:35:51.680
 And then the other end is it's an emergent property of a very complex central nervous system.

1:35:51.680 --> 1:35:58.680
 And I never quite understand what people mean by words like emergence.

1:35:58.680 --> 1:36:08.680
 I mean, there are genuine examples, which I think we very often tend to use it to plaster over ignorance.

1:36:08.680 --> 1:36:16.680
 As a biochemist, the question for me then was, okay, it's a concoction of a central nervous system.

1:36:16.680 --> 1:36:27.680
 A depolarizing neuron gives rise to a feeling, to a feeling of pain, or to a feeling of love, or anger, or whatever it may be.

1:36:27.680 --> 1:36:31.680
 So what is then a feeling in biophysical terms in the central nervous system?

1:36:31.680 --> 1:36:40.680
 Which bit of the wiring gives rise to... And I've never seen anyone answer that question in a way that makes sense to me.

1:36:40.680 --> 1:36:43.680
 And that's an important question to answer.

1:36:43.680 --> 1:36:46.680
 I think if we want to understand consciousness, that's the only question to answer.

1:36:46.680 --> 1:36:54.680
 Because certainly an AI is capable of out thinking and it's only a matter of time, maybe it's already happened.

1:36:54.680 --> 1:36:59.680
 In terms of just information processing and computational skill,

1:36:59.680 --> 1:37:06.680
 I don't think we have any problem in designing a mind which is at least the equal of the human mind.

1:37:06.680 --> 1:37:19.680
 But in terms of what we value the most as humans, which is to say our feelings, our emotions, our sense of what the world is in a very personal way,

1:37:19.680 --> 1:37:24.680
 that I think means as much or more to people than their information processing.

1:37:24.680 --> 1:37:32.680
 And that's where I don't think that AI necessarily will become conscious because I think it's the property of life.

1:37:32.680 --> 1:37:36.680
 Well, let's talk about it more. You're an incredible writer. What are my favorite writers?

1:37:36.680 --> 1:37:42.680
 So let me read from your latest book, Transformers, what you write about consciousness.

1:37:42.680 --> 1:37:48.680
 I think therefore I am, said Descartes, is one of the most celebrated lines ever written.

1:37:48.680 --> 1:37:51.680
 But what am I exactly?

1:37:51.680 --> 1:37:56.680
 An artificial intelligence can think too, by definition, and therefore is.

1:37:56.680 --> 1:38:06.680
 Yet few of us could agree whether AI is capable in principle of anything resembling human emotions, of love or hate, fear and joy,

1:38:06.680 --> 1:38:13.680
 of spiritual yearnings for oneness or oblivion or corporeal pangs of thirst and hunger.

1:38:13.680 --> 1:38:19.680
 The problem is we don't know what emotions are, as you were saying.

1:38:19.680 --> 1:38:25.680
 What is the feeling in physical terms? How does a discharging neuron give rise to a feeling of anything at all?

1:38:25.680 --> 1:38:28.680
 This is the hard problem of consciousness.

1:38:28.680 --> 1:38:34.680
 The seeming duality of mind and matter, the physical makeup of our innermost self.

1:38:34.680 --> 1:38:41.680
 We can understand in principle how an extremely sophisticated parallel processing system could be capable of wondrous feats of intelligence.

1:38:41.680 --> 1:38:48.680
 But we can't answer in principle whether such a supreme intelligence would experience joy or melancholy.

1:38:48.680 --> 1:38:52.680
 What is the quantum of solace?

1:38:52.680 --> 1:39:00.680
 I, speaking to the question of emergence, you know, there's just technical...

1:39:00.680 --> 1:39:07.680
 There's an excellent paper on this recently about this kind of phase transition,

1:39:07.680 --> 1:39:14.680
 emergence of performance in neural networks on the problem of NLP, natural language processing.

1:39:14.680 --> 1:39:18.680
 So language models, there seems to be this question of size.

1:39:18.680 --> 1:39:25.680
 At some point, there is a phase transition as you grow the size of the neural network.

1:39:25.680 --> 1:39:31.680
 So the question is somewhat of a technical question that you can philosophize over.

1:39:31.680 --> 1:39:40.680
 The technical question is, is there a size of a neural network that starts to be able to form the kind of representations that can capture a language

1:39:40.680 --> 1:39:50.680
 and therefore be able to not just language, but linguistically capture knowledge that's sufficient to solve a lot of problems in language,

1:39:50.680 --> 1:39:52.680
 like be able to have a conversation.

1:39:52.680 --> 1:39:56.680
 And there seems to be not a gradual increase, but a phase transition.

1:39:56.680 --> 1:40:00.680
 And they're trying to construct the science of where that is.

1:40:00.680 --> 1:40:03.680
 Like, what is the good size of a neural network?

1:40:03.680 --> 1:40:05.680
 And why does such a phase transition happen?

1:40:05.680 --> 1:40:08.680
 Anyway, that sort of points to emergence.

1:40:08.680 --> 1:40:23.680
 That there could be stages where a thing goes from being, oh, you're very intelligent toaster to a toaster that's feeling sad today

1:40:23.680 --> 1:40:30.680
 and turns away and looks out the window, sighing, having an existential crisis.

1:40:30.680 --> 1:40:32.680
 I was thinking of Marvin, the paranoid android.

1:40:32.680 --> 1:40:37.680
 Exactly. Well, no, Marvin is simplistic because Marvin is just cranky.

1:40:37.680 --> 1:40:39.680
 Yes.

1:40:39.680 --> 1:40:41.680
 So easily programmed.

1:40:41.680 --> 1:40:44.680
 Yeah, easily programmed, nonstop existential crisis.

1:40:44.680 --> 1:40:52.680
 You're almost basically, what is it, notes from underground, but just constantly complaining about life.

1:40:52.680 --> 1:41:03.680
 No, they're capturing the full rollercoaster of human emotion, the excitement, the bliss, the connection, the empathy and all that kind of stuff.

1:41:03.680 --> 1:41:09.680
 And then the selfishness, the anger, the depression, all that kind of stuff.

1:41:09.680 --> 1:41:13.680
 They're capturing all of that and be able to experience it deeply.

1:41:13.680 --> 1:41:17.680
 Like it's the most important thing you could possibly experience today.

1:41:17.680 --> 1:41:20.680
 The highest highs, the lowest lows, this is it.

1:41:20.680 --> 1:41:22.680
 My life will be over.

1:41:22.680 --> 1:41:29.680
 I cannot possibly go on that feeling and then like after a nap, you're feeling amazing.

1:41:29.680 --> 1:41:33.680
 That might be something that emerges.

1:41:33.680 --> 1:41:41.680
 So why would a nap make an AI being feel better?

1:41:41.680 --> 1:41:44.680
 First of all, we don't know that for a human either, right?

1:41:44.680 --> 1:41:48.680
 But we do know that that's actually true for many people much of the time.

1:41:48.680 --> 1:41:52.680
 Maybe you're depressed and you have an app and you do, in fact, feel better.

1:41:52.680 --> 1:41:59.680
 Oh, you are actually asking the technical question there, so there's a biological answer to that.

1:41:59.680 --> 1:42:16.680
 And so the question is whether AI needs to have the same kind of attachments to its body, bodily function, preservation of the brain's successful function, self preservation essentially in some deep biological sense.

1:42:16.680 --> 1:42:27.680
 I mean, to my mind, it comes back round to the problem we were talking about before about simulations and sensory input and learning what all of this stuff means.

1:42:27.680 --> 1:42:35.680
 And life and death, that biology, unlike society, has a death penalty over everything.

1:42:35.680 --> 1:42:38.680
 And natural selection works on that death penalty.

1:42:38.680 --> 1:42:46.680
 That if you make this decision wrongly, you die.

1:42:46.680 --> 1:42:55.680
 And the next generation is represented by beings that made a slightly different decision on balance.

1:42:55.680 --> 1:43:05.680
 And that is something that's intrinsically difficult to simulate in all this richness, I would say.

1:43:05.680 --> 1:43:08.680
 So what is...

1:43:08.680 --> 1:43:11.680
 Death in all its richness.

1:43:11.680 --> 1:43:16.680
 Our relationship with death or the whole of it.

1:43:16.680 --> 1:43:21.680
 So when you say richness, of course, there's a lot in that.

1:43:21.680 --> 1:43:23.680
 Which is hard to simulate?

1:43:23.680 --> 1:43:27.680
 What's part of the richness that's hard to simulate?

1:43:27.680 --> 1:43:37.680
 I suppose the complexity of the environment and your position of an organism in that environment, in the full richness of that environment,

1:43:37.680 --> 1:43:43.680
 over its entire life, over multiple generations, with changes in gene sequence over those generations.

1:43:43.680 --> 1:43:47.680
 So slight changes in the makeup of those individuals over generations.

1:43:47.680 --> 1:43:53.680
 But if you take it back to the level of single cells, which I do in the book,

1:43:53.680 --> 1:44:01.680
 and ask how does a single cell in effect know it exists as an unit, as an entity?

1:44:01.680 --> 1:44:06.680
 I mean, no, in inverted commas, obviously it doesn't know anything.

1:44:06.680 --> 1:44:13.680
 But it acts as a unit and it acts with astonishing precision as a unit.

1:44:13.680 --> 1:44:19.680
 And I had suggested that that's linked to the electrical fields on the membranes themselves.

1:44:19.680 --> 1:44:27.680
 And that they give some indication of how am I doing in relation to my environment as a kind of real time feedback on the world.

1:44:27.680 --> 1:44:34.680
 And this is something physical, which can be selected over generations.

1:44:34.680 --> 1:44:41.680
 That if you are, if you get this wrong, it's linked with this set of circumstances.

1:44:41.680 --> 1:44:50.680
 As an individual, I have a moment of blind panic and run as a bacterium or something.

1:44:50.680 --> 1:44:56.680
 You have some electrical discharge that says blind panic and it runs whatever it may be.

1:44:56.680 --> 1:45:06.680
 And you associate over generations, multiple generations, that this electrical phase that I'm in now is associated with a response like that.

1:45:06.680 --> 1:45:21.680
 And it's easy to see how feelings come in through the back door almost with that kind of giving real time feedback on your position in the world in relation to how am I doing?

1:45:21.680 --> 1:45:23.680
 And then you complexify the system.

1:45:23.680 --> 1:45:27.680
 And yes, I have no problem with phase transition.

1:45:27.680 --> 1:45:41.680
 And can all of this be done purely by the language, by the issues with how the system understands itself?

1:45:41.680 --> 1:45:44.680
 Maybe it can, I honestly don't know.

1:45:44.680 --> 1:45:58.680
 But the philosophers for a long time have talked about the possibility that you can have a zombie intelligence and that there are no feelings there, but everything else is the same.

1:45:58.680 --> 1:46:00.680
 I mean, I have to throw this back to you really.

1:46:00.680 --> 1:46:03.680
 How do you deal with a zombie intelligence?

1:46:03.680 --> 1:46:12.680
 So first of all, I can see that from a biologist perspective, you think of all the complexities that led up to the human being.

1:46:12.680 --> 1:46:24.680
 The entirety of the history of four billion years that in some deep sense integrated the human being into this environment and that dance of the organism and the environment.

1:46:24.680 --> 1:46:31.680
 You could see how emotions arise from that and their emotions are deeply connected and creating a human experience.

1:46:31.680 --> 1:46:36.680
 And from that you mix in consciousness and the full mess of it.

1:46:36.680 --> 1:46:51.680
 But from a perspective of an intelligent organism that's already here, like a baby that learns, it doesn't need to learn how to be a collection of cells or how to do all the things he needs to do.

1:46:51.680 --> 1:47:06.680
 The basic function of a baby as it learns is to interact with its environment, to learn from its environment, to learn how to fit in to the social society.

1:47:06.680 --> 1:47:08.680
 And the basic response of the baby is to cry a lot of the time.

1:47:08.680 --> 1:47:24.680
 Well, maybe convince the humans to protect it or to discipline it, to teach it. We've developed a bunch of different tricks, how to get our parents to take care of us, to educate us, to teach us about the world.

1:47:24.680 --> 1:47:32.680
 Also, we've constructed the world in such a way that it's safe enough for us to survive in and yet dangerous enough for learning the valuable lessons.

1:47:32.680 --> 1:47:38.680
 The tables are still hard with corners, so it can still run into them. It hurts like hell.

1:47:38.680 --> 1:47:53.680
 So AI needs to solve that problem, not the problem of constructing this super complex organism that leads up to make an apple pie to build the whole universe.

1:47:53.680 --> 1:47:55.680
 You need to build the whole universe.

1:47:55.680 --> 1:48:18.680
 I think the zombie question is something I would leave to the philosophers, and I will also leave to them the definition of love and what happens between two human beings when there's a magic that just grabs them.

1:48:18.680 --> 1:48:27.680
 Like nothing else matters in the world and somehow you've been searching for this feeling, this moment, this person, your whole life, that feeling.

1:48:27.680 --> 1:48:36.680
 The philosophers can have a lot of fun with that one and also say that that's just, you can have a biological explanation, you can have all kinds of, it's all fake.

1:48:36.680 --> 1:48:43.680
 It's actually, I'm Rand will say it's all selfish. There's a lot of different interpretations. I'll leave it to the philosophers.

1:48:43.680 --> 1:48:55.680
 The point is the feeling, sure as hell feels very real. And if my toaster makes me feel like it's the only toaster in the world.

1:48:55.680 --> 1:49:10.680
 And when I leave and I miss the toaster and when I come back, I'm excited to see the toaster and my life is meaningful and joyful and the friends I have around me get a better version of me because that toaster exists.

1:49:10.680 --> 1:49:15.680
 That sure as hell feels like a conscious toaster. Is that psychologically different to having a dog?

1:49:15.680 --> 1:49:16.680
 No.

1:49:16.680 --> 1:49:24.680
 Because I mean, most people would dispute whether we can say a dog. I would say a dog is undoubtedly conscious, but some people would say it doesn't.

1:49:24.680 --> 1:49:32.680
 But there's degrees of consciousness and so on, but people are definitely much more uncomfortable saying a toaster can be conscious than a dog.

1:49:32.680 --> 1:49:41.680
 And there's still a deep connection. You could say our relationship with the dog has more to do with anthropomorphism, like we kind of project the human being onto it.

1:49:41.680 --> 1:49:42.680
 Maybe.

1:49:42.680 --> 1:49:45.680
 We can do the same damn thing with a toaster.

1:49:45.680 --> 1:49:53.680
 Yes. But you can look into the dog's eyes and you can see that it's sad that it's delighted to see you again. I don't have a dog, by the way.

1:49:53.680 --> 1:49:58.680
 And a dog is actually incredibly good at using their eyes to do just that.

1:49:58.680 --> 1:50:11.680
 They are. Now, I don't imagine that a dog is remotely as close to being intelligent as an AI intelligence, but it's certainly capable of communicating emotionally with us.

1:50:11.680 --> 1:50:20.680
 But here's what I would venture to say. We tend to think because AI plays chess well and is able to fold proteins now well that it's intelligent.

1:50:20.680 --> 1:50:28.680
 I would argue that in order to communicate with humans in order to have emotional intelligence, it actually requires another order of magnitude of intelligence.

1:50:28.680 --> 1:50:33.680
 It's not easy to be flawed.

1:50:33.680 --> 1:50:41.680
 Solving a mathematical puzzle is not the same as the full complexity of human to human interaction.

1:50:41.680 --> 1:50:51.680
 That's actually, we humans just take for granted the things we're really good at. Nonstop people tell me how shitty people are driving.

1:50:51.680 --> 1:50:55.680
 No. Humans are incredible at driving.

1:50:55.680 --> 1:51:01.680
 Bipedal walking, walking, object manipulation, we're incredible at this.

1:51:01.680 --> 1:51:06.680
 And so people tend to discount the things we all just take for granted.

1:51:06.680 --> 1:51:14.680
 And one of those things that they discount is our ability, the dance of conversation and interaction with each other.

1:51:14.680 --> 1:51:21.680
 The ability to morph ideas together, the ability to get angry at each other and then to miss each other.

1:51:21.680 --> 1:51:27.680
 Like to create attention that makes life fun and difficult and challenging in a way that's meaningful.

1:51:27.680 --> 1:51:32.680
 That is a skill that's learned and AI would need to solve that problem.

1:51:32.680 --> 1:51:41.680
 I mean, in some sense, what you're saying is AI cannot become meaningfully emotional, let's say,

1:51:41.680 --> 1:51:53.680
 until it experiences some kind of internal conflict that is unable to reconcile these various aspects of reality or its reality with a decision to make.

1:51:53.680 --> 1:51:58.680
 And then it feels sad necessarily because it doesn't know what to do.

1:51:58.680 --> 1:52:02.680
 And I certainly can't dispute that. That may very well be how it works.

1:52:02.680 --> 1:52:05.680
 I think the only way to find out is to do it.

1:52:05.680 --> 1:52:10.680
 To build it, yeah. And leave it to the philosophers if it actually feels sad or not.

1:52:10.680 --> 1:52:16.680
 The point is the robot will be sitting there alone having an internal conflict, an existential crisis,

1:52:16.680 --> 1:52:20.680
 and that's required for it to have a deep, meaningful connection with another human being.

1:52:20.680 --> 1:52:23.680
 Now, does it actually feel that? I don't know.

1:52:23.680 --> 1:52:30.680
 But I'd like to throw something else at you, which troubles me on reading it.

1:52:30.680 --> 1:52:34.680
 Noah Harar is book 21, Lessons for the 21st Century.

1:52:34.680 --> 1:52:37.680
 And he's written about this kind of thing on various occasions.

1:52:37.680 --> 1:52:40.680
 And he sees biochemistry as an algorithm.

1:52:40.680 --> 1:52:46.680
 And then AI will necessarily be able to hack that algorithm and do it better than humans.

1:52:46.680 --> 1:52:53.680
 So there will be AI better at writing music that we appreciate than Mozart ever could or writing better than Shakespeare ever did and so on.

1:52:53.680 --> 1:53:02.680
 Because biochemistry is algorithmic and all you need to do is figure out which bits of the algorithm to play to make us feel good or bad or appreciate things.

1:53:02.680 --> 1:53:12.680
 And as a biochemist, I find that argument close to irrefutable and not very enjoyable.

1:53:12.680 --> 1:53:16.680
 I don't like the sound of it. That's just my reaction as a human being.

1:53:16.680 --> 1:53:25.680
 You might like the sound of it because that says that AI is capable of the same kind of emotional feelings about the world as we are.

1:53:25.680 --> 1:53:30.680
 Because the whole thing is an algorithm and you can program an algorithm and there you are.

1:53:30.680 --> 1:53:37.680
 He then has a peculiar final chapter where he talks about consciousness in rather separate terms.

1:53:37.680 --> 1:53:42.680
 And he's talking about meditating and so on and getting in touch with his inner conscious. I don't meditate.

1:53:42.680 --> 1:53:44.680
 I don't know anything about that.

1:53:44.680 --> 1:53:51.680
 But he wrote in very different terms about it as if somehow it's a way out of the algorithm.

1:53:51.680 --> 1:53:58.680
 Now, it seems to me that consciousness in that sense is capable of scuppering the algorithm.

1:53:58.680 --> 1:54:04.680
 I think in terms of the biochemical feedback loops and so on, it is undoubtedly algorithmic.

1:54:04.680 --> 1:54:14.680
 But in terms of what we decide to do, it can be much more based on an emotion.

1:54:14.680 --> 1:54:21.680
 We can just think, I don't care. I can't resolve this complex situation. I'm going to do that.

1:54:21.680 --> 1:54:29.680
 And that can be based on, in effect, a different currency, which is the currency of feelings and something where we don't have very much personal control over.

1:54:29.680 --> 1:54:34.680
 And then it comes back around to you and what are you trying to get at with AI?

1:54:34.680 --> 1:54:44.680
 Do we need to have some system which is capable of overriding a rational decision which cannot be made because there's too much conflicting information

1:54:44.680 --> 1:54:50.680
 by effectively an emotional judgmental decision that just says, do this and see what happens.

1:54:50.680 --> 1:54:52.680
 That's what consciousness is really doing, in my view.

1:54:52.680 --> 1:54:58.680
 Yeah. And the question is whether it's a different process or just a higher level process.

1:54:58.680 --> 1:55:06.680
 The idea that biochemistry is an algorithm is, to me, an oversimplistic view.

1:55:06.680 --> 1:55:20.680
 There's a lot of things that, the moment you say it, it's irrefutable, but it simplifies and in the process loses something fundamental.

1:55:20.680 --> 1:55:29.680
 So, for example, calling a universe and an information processing system, sure, yes. You can make that.

1:55:29.680 --> 1:55:42.680
 It's a computer that's performing computations, but you're missing the process of the entropy somehow leading to pockets of complexity

1:55:42.680 --> 1:55:48.680
 that creates these beautiful artifacts that are incredibly complex and they're like machines.

1:55:48.680 --> 1:55:53.680
 And then those machines are through the process of evolution are constructing even further complexity.

1:55:53.680 --> 1:56:04.680
 In calling a universe and information processing machine, you're missing those little local pockets and how difficult it is to create them.

1:56:04.680 --> 1:56:13.680
 So, the question to me is, if biochemistry is an algorithm, how difficult is it to create a software system that runs the human body,

1:56:13.680 --> 1:56:19.680
 which I think is incorrect. I think that is going to take so long.

1:56:19.680 --> 1:56:24.680
 I mean, that's going to be centuries from now to be able to reconstruct the human.

1:56:24.680 --> 1:56:33.680
 Now, what I would venture to say to get some of the magic of a human being, what we're saying with the emotions and the interactions

1:56:33.680 --> 1:56:38.680
 and like a dog makes a smile and joyful and all those kinds of things, that will come much sooner.

1:56:38.680 --> 1:56:43.680
 But that doesn't require us to reverse engineer the algorithm of biochemistry.

1:56:43.680 --> 1:56:46.680
 Yes, but the toaster is making you happy.

1:56:46.680 --> 1:56:47.680
 Yes.

1:56:47.680 --> 1:56:50.680
 It's not about whether you make the toaster happy.

1:56:50.680 --> 1:56:52.680
 No, it has to be.

1:56:52.680 --> 1:56:57.680
 It has to be. It has to be. The toaster has to be able to leave me.

1:56:57.680 --> 1:56:59.680
 Yes, but it's the toaster is the AI in this case.

1:56:59.680 --> 1:57:05.680
 The toaster has to be able to be unhappy and leave me. That's essential.

1:57:05.680 --> 1:57:08.680
 Yeah, that's essential for my being able to miss the toaster.

1:57:08.680 --> 1:57:15.680
 If the toaster is just my servant, that's not or a provider of like services.

1:57:15.680 --> 1:57:22.680
 Like tells me the weather makes toast. That's not going to deep connection.

1:57:22.680 --> 1:57:26.680
 It has to have internal conflict. You write about life and death.

1:57:26.680 --> 1:57:32.680
 It has to be able to be conscious of its mortality and the finiteness of its existence.

1:57:32.680 --> 1:57:37.680
 And that life is for its temporary and therefore needs to be more selective.

1:57:37.680 --> 1:57:44.680
 One of the most moving moments in the movies from when I was a boy was the unplugging of Hal in 2001,

1:57:44.680 --> 1:57:50.680
 where that was the death of a sentient being and Hal knew it.

1:57:50.680 --> 1:58:02.680
 So I think we all kind of know that a sufficiently intelligent being is going to have some form of consciousness.

1:58:02.680 --> 1:58:07.680
 But whether it would be like biological consciousness, I just don't know.

1:58:07.680 --> 1:58:15.680
 And if you're thinking about how do we bring together, I mean, obviously we're going to interact more closely with AI.

1:58:15.680 --> 1:58:25.680
 But is a dog really like a toaster or is there really some kind of difference there?

1:58:25.680 --> 1:58:32.680
 You were talking about biochemistry is algorithmic, but it's not single algorithm and it's very complex, of course it is.

1:58:32.680 --> 1:58:36.680
 So it may be that there are again conflicts in the circuits of biochemistry,

1:58:36.680 --> 1:58:51.680
 but I have a feeling that the level of complexity of the total biochemical system at the level of a single cell is less complex than the level of neural networking in the human brain or in an AI.

1:58:51.680 --> 1:58:58.680
 Well, I guess I assumed that we were including the brain in the biochemistry algorithm because you have to...

1:58:58.680 --> 1:59:02.680
 I would see that as a higher level of organization of neural networks.

1:59:02.680 --> 1:59:05.680
 They're all using the same biochemical wiring within themselves.

1:59:05.680 --> 1:59:13.680
 Yeah, but the human brain is not just neurons, it's the immune system, it's the whole package.

1:59:13.680 --> 1:59:21.680
 I mean, to have a biochemical algorithm that runs an intelligent biological system, you have to include the whole damn thing.

1:59:21.680 --> 1:59:26.680
 And it's pretty fascinating that it comes from an embryo.

1:59:26.680 --> 1:59:36.680
 I mean, oh boy, I mean, what is a human being? Because it's just some code and then you build.

1:59:36.680 --> 1:59:41.680
 So it's DNA doesn't just tell you what to build but how to build it.

1:59:41.680 --> 1:59:51.680
 I mean, the thing is impressive and the question is how difficult is it to reverse engineer the whole shebang?

1:59:51.680 --> 1:59:53.680
 Very difficult.

1:59:53.680 --> 1:59:58.680
 I would say it's...

1:59:58.680 --> 2:00:06.680
 I don't want to say impossible, but it's much easier to build a human than to reverse engineer...

2:00:06.680 --> 2:00:15.680
 to build like a fake human, human like thing than to reverse engineer the entirety of the process of evolution.

2:00:15.680 --> 2:00:20.680
 I'm not sure if we are capable of reverse engineering the whole thing.

2:00:20.680 --> 2:00:23.680
 If the human mind is capable of doing that.

2:00:23.680 --> 2:00:30.680
 I mean, I wouldn't be a biologist if I wasn't trying, but I know I can't understand the whole problem.

2:00:30.680 --> 2:00:34.680
 I'm just trying to understand the rudimentary outlines of the problem.

2:00:34.680 --> 2:00:40.680
 There's another aspect, though, you're talking about developing from a single cell to the human mind

2:00:40.680 --> 2:00:48.680
 and all the subsystems that are part of the immune system and so on.

2:00:48.680 --> 2:00:54.680
 This is something that you'll talk about, I imagine, with Michael Levin.

2:00:54.680 --> 2:01:00.680
 But so little is known about...

2:01:00.680 --> 2:01:05.680
 You talk about reverse engineers, so little is known about the developmental pathways that go from a genome

2:01:05.680 --> 2:01:08.680
 to going to a fully wired organism.

2:01:08.680 --> 2:01:14.680
 And a lot of it seems to depend on the same intellectual interactions

2:01:14.680 --> 2:01:19.680
 that I was talking about happening at the level of single cells and its interaction with the environment.

2:01:19.680 --> 2:01:26.680
 There's a whole electrical field side to biology that is not yet written into any of the textbooks,

2:01:26.680 --> 2:01:32.680
 which is about how does an embryo develop into or a single cell develop into these complex systems,

2:01:32.680 --> 2:01:36.680
 what defines the head, what defines the immune system, what defines the brain and so on.

2:01:36.680 --> 2:01:40.680
 That really is written in a language that we're only just beginning to understand,

2:01:40.680 --> 2:01:47.680
 particularly biologists, most biologists are still very reluctant to even get themselves tangled up

2:01:47.680 --> 2:01:51.680
 in questions like electrical fields influencing development.

2:01:51.680 --> 2:01:57.680
 It seems like mumbo jumbo to a lot of biologists, and it should not be because this is the 21st century biology.

2:01:57.680 --> 2:01:59.680
 This is where it's going.

2:01:59.680 --> 2:02:04.680
 But we're not going to reverse engineer a human being or the mind or any of these subsystems

2:02:04.680 --> 2:02:09.680
 until we understand how this developmental process is, how electricity in biology really works.

2:02:09.680 --> 2:02:15.680
 And if it is linked with feelings and with consciousness and so on,

2:02:15.680 --> 2:02:18.680
 in the meantime, we have to try.

2:02:18.680 --> 2:02:22.680
 But I think that's where the answer lies.

2:02:22.680 --> 2:02:31.680
 So you think it's possible that the key to things like consciousness are some of the more tricky aspects of cognition

2:02:31.680 --> 2:02:38.680
 might lie in that early development, the interaction of electricity and biology.

2:02:38.680 --> 2:02:40.680
 Electrical fields.

2:02:40.680 --> 2:02:44.680
 But we already know the EEG and so on is telling us a lot about brain function,

2:02:44.680 --> 2:02:48.680
 but we don't know which cells, which parts of a neural network is giving rise to the EEG.

2:02:48.680 --> 2:02:50.680
 We don't know the basics.

2:02:50.680 --> 2:02:54.680
 The assumption is, I mean, we know it's neural networks, we know it's multiple cells,

2:02:54.680 --> 2:02:56.680
 hundreds or thousands of cells involved in it,

2:02:56.680 --> 2:03:02.680
 and we assume that it's to do with depolarization during action potentials and so on.

2:03:02.680 --> 2:03:08.680
 But the mitochondria which are in there have much more membranes than the plasma membrane of the neuron

2:03:08.680 --> 2:03:10.680
 and there's a much greater membrane potential.

2:03:10.680 --> 2:03:14.680
 And it's formed in parallel, very often parallel Christi,

2:03:14.680 --> 2:03:20.680
 which are capable of reinforcing a field and generating fields over longer distances.

2:03:20.680 --> 2:03:24.680
 And nobody knows if that plays a role in consciousness or not.

2:03:24.680 --> 2:03:28.680
 There's reasons to argue that it could, but frankly, we simply do not know.

2:03:28.680 --> 2:03:30.680
 And it's not taken into consideration.

2:03:30.680 --> 2:03:34.680
 You look at the structure of the mitochondrial membranes

2:03:34.680 --> 2:03:39.680
 in the brains of simple things like josophila, the fruit fly,

2:03:39.680 --> 2:03:41.680
 and they have amazing structures.

2:03:41.680 --> 2:03:47.680
 You can see lots of little rectangular things all lined up in amazing patterns.

2:03:47.680 --> 2:03:48.680
 What are they doing?

2:03:48.680 --> 2:03:49.680
 Why are they like that?

2:03:49.680 --> 2:03:51.680
 We haven't the first clue.

2:03:51.680 --> 2:03:54.680
 What do you think about organoids and brain organoids?

2:03:54.680 --> 2:04:04.680
 So in a lab trying to study the development of these in the Petru dish development of organs,

2:04:04.680 --> 2:04:05.680
 do you think that's promising?

2:04:05.680 --> 2:04:07.680
 Do you have to look at the whole systems?

2:04:07.680 --> 2:04:09.680
 I've never done anything like that.

2:04:09.680 --> 2:04:10.680
 I don't know much about it.

2:04:10.680 --> 2:04:14.680
 The people who I've talked to who do work on it say amazing things can happen

2:04:14.680 --> 2:04:20.680
 and a bit of a brain drone in a dish is capable of experiencing some kind of feelings

2:04:20.680 --> 2:04:23.680
 or even memories of its former brain.

2:04:23.680 --> 2:04:29.680
 Again, I have a feeling that until we understand how to control the electrical fields

2:04:29.680 --> 2:04:35.680
 that control development, we're not going to understand how to turn an organoid into a real functional system.

2:04:35.680 --> 2:04:38.680
 But how do we get that understanding?

2:04:38.680 --> 2:04:41.680
 It's so incredibly difficult.

2:04:41.680 --> 2:04:44.680
 I mean, you would have to, I mean, one promising direction.

2:04:44.680 --> 2:04:46.680
 I'd love to get your opinion on this.

2:04:46.680 --> 2:04:51.680
 I don't know if you're familiar with the work of DeepMind and AlphaFold with protein folding and so on.

2:04:51.680 --> 2:04:57.680
 Do you think it's possible that that will give us some breakthroughs in biology

2:04:57.680 --> 2:05:06.680
 trying to basically simulate and model the behavior of trivial biological systems

2:05:06.680 --> 2:05:10.680
 as they become complex biological systems?

2:05:10.680 --> 2:05:12.680
 I'm sorry, Will.

2:05:12.680 --> 2:05:18.680
 The interesting thing to me about protein folding is that for a long time,

2:05:18.680 --> 2:05:21.680
 my understanding, this is not what I work on, so I may have got this wrong,

2:05:21.680 --> 2:05:28.680
 but my understanding is that you take the sequence of a protein and you try to fold it.

2:05:28.680 --> 2:05:30.680
 And there are multiple ways in which it can fold.

2:05:30.680 --> 2:05:34.680
 And to come up with the correct confirmation is not a very easy thing

2:05:34.680 --> 2:05:37.680
 because you're doing it from first principles from a string of letters

2:05:37.680 --> 2:05:39.680
 which specify the string of amino acids.

2:05:39.680 --> 2:05:45.680
 But what actually happens is when a protein is coming out of a ribosome,

2:05:45.680 --> 2:05:49.680
 it's coming out of a charged tunnel and it's in a very specific environment

2:05:49.680 --> 2:05:52.680
 which is going to force this to go there now and then this one to go there

2:05:52.680 --> 2:05:53.680
 and this one to come like that.

2:05:53.680 --> 2:05:56.680
 And so you're forcing a specific conformational set of changes onto it

2:05:56.680 --> 2:05:58.680
 as it comes out of the ribosome.

2:05:58.680 --> 2:06:01.680
 So by the time it's fully emerged, it's already got its shape

2:06:01.680 --> 2:06:07.680
 and that shape depended on the immediate environment that it was emerging into

2:06:07.680 --> 2:06:11.680
 one letter, one amino acid at a time.

2:06:11.680 --> 2:06:16.680
 And I don't think that the field was looking at it that way.

2:06:16.680 --> 2:06:20.680
 And if that's correct, then that's very characteristic of science

2:06:20.680 --> 2:06:22.680
 which is to say it asks very often the wrong question

2:06:22.680 --> 2:06:25.680
 and then does really amazingly sophisticated analyses on something

2:06:25.680 --> 2:06:27.680
 having never thought to actually think,

2:06:27.680 --> 2:06:28.680
 well, what is biology doing?

2:06:28.680 --> 2:06:31.680
 And biology is giving you a charged electrical environment

2:06:31.680 --> 2:06:32.680
 that forces you to be this way.

2:06:32.680 --> 2:06:39.680
 Now, did deep mind come up through patterns with some answer that was like that?

2:06:39.680 --> 2:06:41.680
 I've got absolutely no idea.

2:06:41.680 --> 2:06:46.680
 It ought to be possible to deduce that from the shapes of proteins.

2:06:46.680 --> 2:06:52.680
 It would require much greater skill than the human mind has.

2:06:52.680 --> 2:06:54.680
 But the human mind is capable of saying,

2:06:54.680 --> 2:06:56.680
 well, hang on, let's look at this exit tunnel

2:06:56.680 --> 2:06:58.680
 and try and work out what shape is this protein going to take

2:06:58.680 --> 2:06:59.680
 and we can figure that out.

2:06:59.680 --> 2:07:01.680
 That's really interesting about the exit tunnel.

2:07:01.680 --> 2:07:06.680
 But sometimes we get lucky and just like in science,

2:07:06.680 --> 2:07:11.680
 the simplified view or the static view will actually solve the problem for us.

2:07:11.680 --> 2:07:15.680
 So in this case, it's very possible that the sequence of letters

2:07:15.680 --> 2:07:21.680
 has a unique mapping to our structure without considering how it unraveled.

2:07:21.680 --> 2:07:23.680
 So without considering the tunnel.

2:07:23.680 --> 2:07:27.680
 And so that seems to be the case in this situation

2:07:27.680 --> 2:07:29.680
 where the cool thing about proteins,

2:07:29.680 --> 2:07:31.680
 all the different shapes they can possibly take,

2:07:31.680 --> 2:07:35.680
 it actually seems to take very specific unique shapes given the sequence.

2:07:35.680 --> 2:07:37.680
 That's forced on you by an exit tunnel.

2:07:37.680 --> 2:07:39.680
 So the problem is actually much simpler than you thought.

2:07:39.680 --> 2:07:43.680
 And then there's a whole army of proteins

2:07:43.680 --> 2:07:48.680
 which change the conformational state, chaperone proteins.

2:07:48.680 --> 2:07:52.680
 And they're only used when there's some,

2:07:52.680 --> 2:07:55.680
 presumably, issue with how it came out of the exit tunnel

2:07:55.680 --> 2:07:57.680
 and you want to do it differently to that.

2:07:57.680 --> 2:07:59.680
 So very often the chaperone proteins will go there

2:07:59.680 --> 2:08:02.680
 and will influence the way in which it falls.

2:08:02.680 --> 2:08:06.680
 So there's two ways of doing it.

2:08:06.680 --> 2:08:10.680
 Either you can look at the structures and the sequences of all the proteins

2:08:10.680 --> 2:08:12.680
 and you can apply an immense mind to it

2:08:12.680 --> 2:08:15.680
 and figure out what the patterns are and figure out what how,

2:08:15.680 --> 2:08:17.680
 or you can look at the actual situation where it is and say,

2:08:17.680 --> 2:08:19.680
 well, hang on, it was actually quite simple.

2:08:19.680 --> 2:08:22.680
 It's got a charged environment and it's forced to come out this way.

2:08:22.680 --> 2:08:23.680
 And then the question will be,

2:08:23.680 --> 2:08:26.680
 well, do different ribosomes have different charged environments

2:08:26.680 --> 2:08:28.680
 for what happens if a chaperone, you know,

2:08:28.680 --> 2:08:31.680
 you're asking a different set of questions to come to the same answer

2:08:31.680 --> 2:08:34.680
 in a way which is telling you a much simpler story

2:08:34.680 --> 2:08:35.680
 and explains why it is.

2:08:35.680 --> 2:08:37.680
 Rather than saying it could be,

2:08:37.680 --> 2:08:41.680
 this is one in a billion different possible conformational states

2:08:41.680 --> 2:08:42.680
 that this protein could have,

2:08:42.680 --> 2:08:45.680
 you're saying, well, it has this one because that was the only one

2:08:45.680 --> 2:08:47.680
 it could take given its setting.

2:08:47.680 --> 2:08:49.680
 Well, yeah, I mean,

2:08:49.680 --> 2:08:52.680
 currently humans are very good at that kind of first principles thinking.

2:08:52.680 --> 2:08:54.680
 I was stepping back.

2:08:54.680 --> 2:08:56.680
 But I think AI is really good at, you know,

2:08:56.680 --> 2:08:58.680
 collecting a huge amount of data

2:08:58.680 --> 2:09:01.680
 and a huge amount of data of observation of planets

2:09:01.680 --> 2:09:04.680
 and figure out that Earth is not at the center of the universe,

2:09:04.680 --> 2:09:07.680
 that there's actually a sun orbiting the sun.

2:09:07.680 --> 2:09:09.680
 But then you can, as a human being, ask,

2:09:09.680 --> 2:09:12.680
 well, how did solar systems come to be?

2:09:12.680 --> 2:09:16.680
 What are the different forces that are required

2:09:16.680 --> 2:09:19.680
 to make this kind of pattern emerge?

2:09:19.680 --> 2:09:22.680
 And then you start to invent things like gravity.

2:09:22.680 --> 2:09:25.680
 I mean, obviously,

2:09:25.680 --> 2:09:29.680
 I mixed up the ordering of gravity,

2:09:29.680 --> 2:09:32.680
 wasn't considered as a thing that connects planets,

2:09:32.680 --> 2:09:37.680
 but we are able to think about those big picture things as human beings.

2:09:37.680 --> 2:09:41.680
 AI is just very good to infer simple models

2:09:41.680 --> 2:09:44.680
 from a huge amount of data.

2:09:44.680 --> 2:09:47.680
 And the question is with biology,

2:09:47.680 --> 2:09:50.680
 we kind of go back and forth to how we solve biology.

2:09:50.680 --> 2:09:54.680
 Listen, protein folding was thought to be impossible to solve.

2:09:54.680 --> 2:09:56.680
 And there's a lot of brilliant PhD students

2:09:56.680 --> 2:10:00.680
 that worked one protein at a time trying to figure out the structure.

2:10:00.680 --> 2:10:02.680
 And in fact, I was able to do that.

2:10:02.680 --> 2:10:05.680
 Oh, I'm not knocking it at all,

2:10:05.680 --> 2:10:09.680
 but I think that people have been asking the wrong question.

2:10:09.680 --> 2:10:16.680
 But then as the people start to ask better and bigger questions,

2:10:16.680 --> 2:10:20.680
 the AI kind of enters the chat and says,

2:10:20.680 --> 2:10:22.680
 I'll help you out with that.

2:10:22.680 --> 2:10:26.680
 Can I give you another example of my own work?

2:10:26.680 --> 2:10:31.680
 The risk of getting a disease as we get older,

2:10:31.680 --> 2:10:34.680
 there are genetic aspects to it.

2:10:34.680 --> 2:10:38.680
 If you spend your whole life overeating and smoking and whatever,

2:10:38.680 --> 2:10:41.680
 that's a whole separate question.

2:10:41.680 --> 2:10:43.680
 But there's a genetic side to the risk.

2:10:43.680 --> 2:10:47.680
 And we know a few genes that increase your risk of certain things.

2:10:47.680 --> 2:10:49.680
 And for probably 20 years now,

2:10:49.680 --> 2:10:54.680
 people have been doing what's called GWAS, which is genome wide association studies.

2:10:54.680 --> 2:10:58.680
 So you've effectively scanned the entire genome

2:10:58.680 --> 2:11:01.680
 for any single nucleotide polymorphisms,

2:11:01.680 --> 2:11:04.680
 which is, say, a single letter change in one place

2:11:04.680 --> 2:11:08.680
 that has a higher association of being linked with a particular disease or not.

2:11:08.680 --> 2:11:11.680
 And you can come out with thousands of these things across the genome.

2:11:11.680 --> 2:11:16.680
 And if you add them all up and try and say,

2:11:16.680 --> 2:11:23.680
 well, so do they add up to explain the known genetic risk of this disease?

2:11:23.680 --> 2:11:25.680
 And the known genetic risk often comes from twin studies.

2:11:25.680 --> 2:11:30.680
 And you can say that if this twin gets epilepsy,

2:11:30.680 --> 2:11:35.680
 there's a 40 or 50% risk that the other twin, identical twin, will also get epilepsy.

2:11:35.680 --> 2:11:38.680
 Therefore, the genetic factor is about 50%.

2:11:38.680 --> 2:11:45.680
 And so the gene similarities that you see should account for 50% of that known risk.

2:11:45.680 --> 2:11:49.680
 Very often it accounts for less than a tenth of the known risk.

2:11:49.680 --> 2:11:52.680
 And there's two possible explanations.

2:11:52.680 --> 2:11:54.680
 And there's one which people tend to do, which is to say,

2:11:54.680 --> 2:11:57.680
 ah, well, we don't have enough statistical power.

2:11:57.680 --> 2:12:01.680
 If we, maybe there's a million, we've only found a thousand of them.

2:12:01.680 --> 2:12:03.680
 But if we find the other million, they're weekly related,

2:12:03.680 --> 2:12:04.680
 but there's a huge number of them.

2:12:04.680 --> 2:12:06.680
 And so we'll account for that whole risk.

2:12:06.680 --> 2:12:10.680
 Maybe there's a billion of them.

2:12:10.680 --> 2:12:12.680
 So that's one way.

2:12:12.680 --> 2:12:15.680
 The other way is to say, well, hang on a minute.

2:12:15.680 --> 2:12:16.680
 You're missing a system here.

2:12:16.680 --> 2:12:18.680
 That system is the mitochondrial DNA,

2:12:18.680 --> 2:12:22.680
 which people tend to dismiss because it's small and it's not.

2:12:22.680 --> 2:12:26.680
 It doesn't change very much.

2:12:26.680 --> 2:12:30.680
 But a few single letter changes in that mitochondrial DNA,

2:12:30.680 --> 2:12:33.680
 it controls some really basic processes.

2:12:33.680 --> 2:12:37.680
 It controls not only all the energy that we need to live

2:12:37.680 --> 2:12:39.680
 and to move around and do everything we do,

2:12:39.680 --> 2:12:44.680
 but also biosynthesis to make the new building blocks

2:12:44.680 --> 2:12:47.680
 to make new cells.

2:12:47.680 --> 2:12:50.680
 And cancer cells very often kind of take over the mitochondria

2:12:50.680 --> 2:12:54.680
 and rewire them so that instead of using them for making energy,

2:12:54.680 --> 2:12:56.680
 they're effectively using them as precursors

2:12:56.680 --> 2:12:58.680
 for the building blocks for biosynthesis.

2:12:58.680 --> 2:13:01.680
 You need to make new amino acids, new nucleotides for DNA.

2:13:01.680 --> 2:13:04.680
 You want to make new lipids to make your membranes and so on.

2:13:04.680 --> 2:13:06.680
 So they kind of rewire metabolism.

2:13:06.680 --> 2:13:09.680
 Now, the problem is that we've got all these interactions

2:13:09.680 --> 2:13:12.680
 between mitochondrial DNA and the genes in the nucleus

2:13:12.680 --> 2:13:16.680
 that are overlooked completely because people throw away,

2:13:16.680 --> 2:13:18.680
 literally throw away the mitochondrial genes.

2:13:18.680 --> 2:13:20.680
 And we can see in fruit flies that they interact

2:13:20.680 --> 2:13:23.680
 and produce big differences in risk.

2:13:23.680 --> 2:13:28.680
 So you can set, you can set AI onto this question

2:13:28.680 --> 2:13:34.680
 of exactly what, you know, how many of these base changes there are.

2:13:34.680 --> 2:13:36.680
 And that's just one possible solution

2:13:36.680 --> 2:13:38.680
 that maybe there are a million of them

2:13:38.680 --> 2:13:40.680
 and it does account for the greatest part of the risk.

2:13:40.680 --> 2:13:42.680
 Well, the other one is they aren't.

2:13:42.680 --> 2:13:43.680
 It's just not there.

2:13:43.680 --> 2:13:46.680
 Actually, the risk lies in something you weren't even looking at.

2:13:46.680 --> 2:13:50.680
 And this is where human intuition is very important

2:13:50.680 --> 2:13:52.680
 and just this feeling that, well, I'm working on this

2:13:52.680 --> 2:13:55.680
 and I think it's important and I'm bloody minded about it

2:13:55.680 --> 2:13:57.680
 and in the end, some people are right.

2:13:57.680 --> 2:13:59.680
 It turns out that it was important.

2:13:59.680 --> 2:14:02.680
 Can you get AI to do that, to be bloody minded?

2:14:02.680 --> 2:14:06.680
 And that hang on a minute.

2:14:06.680 --> 2:14:10.680
 You might be missing a whole other system here that's much bigger.

2:14:10.680 --> 2:14:16.680
 That's the moment of discovery of scientific revolution.

2:14:16.680 --> 2:14:21.680
 I'm giving up on saying AI can't do something.

2:14:21.680 --> 2:14:24.680
 I've said enough times about enough things.

2:14:24.680 --> 2:14:26.680
 I think there's been a lot of progress.

2:14:26.680 --> 2:14:31.680
 And instead, I'm excited by the possibility of AI helping humans.

2:14:31.680 --> 2:14:33.680
 At the same time, just like I said,

2:14:33.680 --> 2:14:36.680
 we seem to dismiss the power of humans.

2:14:36.680 --> 2:14:37.680
 Yes.

2:14:37.680 --> 2:14:44.680
 We're so limited in so many ways that we kind of,

2:14:44.680 --> 2:14:50.680
 in what we feel like dumb ways, we're not strong.

2:14:50.680 --> 2:14:56.680
 We're kind of, our attention, our memory is limited.

2:14:56.680 --> 2:14:59.680
 Our ability to focus on things is limited.

2:14:59.680 --> 2:15:02.680
 In our own perception of what limited is.

2:15:02.680 --> 2:15:06.680
 But that actually, there's an incredible computer behind the whole thing

2:15:06.680 --> 2:15:08.680
 that makes this whole system work.

2:15:08.680 --> 2:15:11.680
 Our ability to interact with the environment,

2:15:11.680 --> 2:15:12.680
 to reason about the environment.

2:15:12.680 --> 2:15:14.680
 There's magic there.

2:15:14.680 --> 2:15:18.680
 And I'm hopeful that AI can capture some of that same magic.

2:15:18.680 --> 2:15:22.680
 But that magic is not going to look like deep blue playing chess.

2:15:22.680 --> 2:15:24.680
 It's going to be more interesting.

2:15:24.680 --> 2:15:27.680
 But I don't think it's going to look like pattern finding either.

2:15:27.680 --> 2:15:29.680
 I mean, that's essentially what you're telling me.

2:15:29.680 --> 2:15:30.680
 It does very well at the moment.

2:15:30.680 --> 2:15:35.680
 And my point is, it works very well where you're looking for the right pattern.

2:15:35.680 --> 2:15:38.680
 But we are storytelling animals.

2:15:38.680 --> 2:15:40.680
 And the hypothesis is a story.

2:15:40.680 --> 2:15:42.680
 It's a testable story.

2:15:42.680 --> 2:15:46.680
 But a new hypothesis is a leap into the unknown.

2:15:46.680 --> 2:15:48.680
 And it's a new story, basically.

2:15:48.680 --> 2:15:50.680
 And it says, this leads to this leads to that.

2:15:50.680 --> 2:15:54.680
 It's a causal set of storytelling.

2:15:54.680 --> 2:15:58.680
 It's also possible that the leap into the unknown has a pattern of its own.

2:15:58.680 --> 2:15:59.680
 Yes, it is.

2:15:59.680 --> 2:16:01.680
 And it's possible that's learnable.

2:16:01.680 --> 2:16:03.680
 I'm sure it is.

2:16:03.680 --> 2:16:10.680
 There's a nice book by Arthur Kustler on the nature of creativity.

2:16:10.680 --> 2:16:15.680
 And he likens it to a joke where the punchline goes off in a completely unexpected direction

2:16:15.680 --> 2:16:18.680
 and says that this is the basis of human creativity.

2:16:18.680 --> 2:16:24.680
 Some creative switch of direction to an unexpected place is similar to a joke.

2:16:24.680 --> 2:16:26.680
 I'm not saying that's how it works.

2:16:26.680 --> 2:16:30.680
 But it's a nice idea and there must be some truth in it.

2:16:30.680 --> 2:16:34.680
 And it's one of these, most of the stories we tell are probably the wrong story

2:16:34.680 --> 2:16:37.680
 and probably going nowhere and probably not helpful.

2:16:37.680 --> 2:16:41.680
 And we definitely don't do as well at seeing patterns in things.

2:16:41.680 --> 2:16:45.680
 But some of the most enjoyable human aspects is finding a new story

2:16:45.680 --> 2:16:47.680
 that goes to an unexpected place.

2:16:47.680 --> 2:16:51.680
 And these are all aspects of what being human means to me.

2:16:51.680 --> 2:16:55.680
 And maybe these are all things that AI figures out for itself

2:16:55.680 --> 2:16:57.680
 or maybe they're just aspects.

2:16:57.680 --> 2:17:04.680
 But I just have the feeling sometimes that the people who are trying to understand

2:17:04.680 --> 2:17:12.680
 what we are like, if we wish to craft an AI system which is somehow human like

2:17:12.680 --> 2:17:18.680
 that we don't have a firm enough grasp of what humans really are like

2:17:18.680 --> 2:17:20.680
 in terms of how we are built.

2:17:20.680 --> 2:17:24.680
 But we get a better, better understanding of that.

2:17:24.680 --> 2:17:26.680
 I agree with you completely.

2:17:26.680 --> 2:17:30.680
 We try to build a thing and then we go, hang on in a minute.

2:17:30.680 --> 2:17:35.680
 There's another system here and that's actually the attempt to build AI

2:17:35.680 --> 2:17:39.680
 that's human like is getting us to a deeper understanding of human beings.

2:17:39.680 --> 2:17:42.680
 The funny thing that I recently talked to Magnus Carlson,

2:17:42.680 --> 2:17:45.680
 why they consider to be the greatest chess player of all time.

2:17:45.680 --> 2:17:51.680
 And he talked about AlphaZero, which is a system from DeepMind that plays chess.

2:17:51.680 --> 2:17:53.680
 And he had a funny comment.

2:17:53.680 --> 2:17:57.680
 He has a kind of dry sense of humor.

2:17:57.680 --> 2:18:01.680
 But he was extremely impressed when he first saw AlphaZero play.

2:18:01.680 --> 2:18:07.680
 And he said that it did a lot of things that could easily be mistaken for creativity.

2:18:07.680 --> 2:18:16.680
 So he like, as a typical human, refused to give the system sort of its due.

2:18:16.680 --> 2:18:22.680
 Because he came up with a lot of things that a lot of people are extremely impressed by.

2:18:22.680 --> 2:18:26.680
 Not just the sheer calculation, but the brilliance of play.

2:18:26.680 --> 2:18:34.680
 So one of the things that it does in really interesting ways is it sacrifices pieces.

2:18:34.680 --> 2:18:40.680
 So in chess, that means you basically take a few steps back and it takes a step forward.

2:18:40.680 --> 2:18:44.680
 You give away pieces for some future reward.

2:18:44.680 --> 2:18:49.680
 And that for us humans is where art is in chess.

2:18:49.680 --> 2:18:57.680
 You take big risks that for us humans, those risks are especially painful

2:18:57.680 --> 2:19:01.680
 because you have a fog of uncertainty before you.

2:19:01.680 --> 2:19:06.680
 So to take a risk now based on intuition, if I think this is the right risk to take,

2:19:06.680 --> 2:19:10.680
 but there's so many possibilities that that's where it takes guts.

2:19:10.680 --> 2:19:13.680
 That's where art is. That's that danger.

2:19:13.680 --> 2:19:21.680
 And then AlphaZero takes those same kind of risks and does them even greater degree.

2:19:21.680 --> 2:19:33.680
 But of course, it does it from what you could easily reduce down to a cold calculation over patterns.

2:19:33.680 --> 2:19:41.680
 But boy, when you see the final result, it sure looks like the same kind of magic that we see in creativity.

2:19:41.680 --> 2:19:46.680
 We see creative play on the chessboard, but the chessboard is very limited.

2:19:46.680 --> 2:19:55.680
 And the question is, as we get better and better, can we do that same kind of creativity in mathematics, in programming,

2:19:55.680 --> 2:20:03.680
 and then venturing biology, psychology, and expand into more and more complex systems?

2:20:03.680 --> 2:20:10.680
 I used to go running when I was a boy and fell running, which is say running up and down mountains.

2:20:10.680 --> 2:20:18.680
 And I was never particularly great at it, but there were some people who were amazingly fast, especially at running down.

2:20:18.680 --> 2:20:24.680
 And I realized in trying to do this, that there's only really two ways.

2:20:24.680 --> 2:20:27.680
 There are three possible ways of doing it, and there's only two that work.

2:20:27.680 --> 2:20:32.680
 Either you go extremely slowly and carefully, and you figure out, OK, there's a stone.

2:20:32.680 --> 2:20:37.680
 I'll put my foot on this stone, and then there's another, there's a muddy puddle I'm going to avoid.

2:20:37.680 --> 2:20:41.680
 It's slow, it's laborious. You figure it out step by step.

2:20:41.680 --> 2:20:45.680
 Or you can just go incredibly fast, and you don't think about it at all.

2:20:45.680 --> 2:20:49.680
 The entire conscious mind is shut out of it, and it's probably the same, playing table tennis or something.

2:20:49.680 --> 2:20:55.680
 There's something in the mind which is doing a whole lot of subconscious calculations about it, and it's amazing.

2:20:55.680 --> 2:20:59.680
 You can run at an astonishing speed down a hillside with no idea how you did it at all.

2:20:59.680 --> 2:21:03.680
 And then you panic, and you think, I'm going to break my leg if I keep doing this.

2:21:03.680 --> 2:21:07.680
 I've got to think about where I'm going to put my foot. So you slow down a bit and try to bring those conscious mind in,

2:21:07.680 --> 2:21:13.680
 and then you do, you crash, you cannot think consciously while running downhill.

2:21:13.680 --> 2:21:20.680
 So it's amazing how many calculations the mind is able to make.

2:21:20.680 --> 2:21:27.680
 Now, the problem with playing chess or something, if you were able to make all of those subconscious kind of forward calculations

2:21:27.680 --> 2:21:34.680
 about what is the likely outcome of this move now in the way that we can by running down a hillside or something.

2:21:34.680 --> 2:21:40.680
 It's partly about what we have adapted to do. It's partly about the reality of the world that we're in.

2:21:40.680 --> 2:21:45.680
 Running fast downhill is something that we better be bloody good at, otherwise we're going to be eaten.

2:21:45.680 --> 2:21:53.680
 Whereas trying to calculate multiple, multiple moves into the future is not something we've ever been called on to do.

2:21:53.680 --> 2:21:59.680
 Two or three, four moves into the future is quite enough for most of us most of the time.

2:21:59.680 --> 2:22:16.680
 Yeah, yeah. So just solving chess may not, we may not be as far towards solving the problem of downhill running as we might think just because we solve chess.

2:22:16.680 --> 2:22:28.680
 Still, it's beautiful to see creativity. Humans create machines that are able to create art and art on the chess board and art otherwise.

2:22:28.680 --> 2:22:31.680
 Who knows how far that takes us.

2:22:31.680 --> 2:22:36.680
 So I mentioned Andre Carpathi earlier. Him and I are big fans of yours.

2:22:36.680 --> 2:22:42.680
 If you're taking votes, his suggestion was you should write your next book on the Fermi Paradox.

2:22:42.680 --> 2:22:48.680
 So let me ask you on the topic of alien life.

2:22:48.680 --> 2:22:52.680
 Since we've been talking about life and we're a kind of aliens.

2:22:52.680 --> 2:22:57.680
 How many alien civilizations are out there? Do you think?

2:22:57.680 --> 2:23:16.680
 Well, the universe is very big, so some, but not as many as most people would like to think is my view because the idea that there is a trajectory going from simple cellular life like bacteria all the way through to humans.

2:23:16.680 --> 2:23:26.680
 It seems to me there's some big gaps along that way that the eukaryotic cell, the complex cell that we have is the biggest of them, but also photosynthesis is another.

2:23:26.680 --> 2:23:38.680
 Another interesting gap is a long gap from the origin of the eukaryotic cell to the first animals. That was about a billion years, maybe more than that.

2:23:38.680 --> 2:23:42.680
 A long delay in where oxygen began to accumulate in the atmosphere.

2:23:42.680 --> 2:23:51.680
 So from the first appearance of oxygen in the Great Oxidation Event to enough for animals to respire, it was close to two billion years.

2:23:51.680 --> 2:24:00.680
 Why so long? It seems to be planetary factors. It seems to be geology as much as anything else, and we don't really know what was going on.

2:24:00.680 --> 2:24:11.680
 So the idea that there's a kind of an inevitable march towards complexity and sentient life, I don't think is right.

2:24:11.680 --> 2:24:17.680
 It doesn't, not to say it's not going to happen, but I think it's not going to happen often.

2:24:17.680 --> 2:24:31.680
 So if you think of Earth, given the geological constraints and all that kind of stuff, do you have a sense that life, complex life, intelligent life happen really quickly on Earth or really long?

2:24:31.680 --> 2:24:46.680
 So just to get a sense of, are you more sort of saying that it's very unlikely to get the kind of conditions required to create humans, or is it even if you have the condition it's just statistically difficult?

2:24:46.680 --> 2:24:56.680
 I think the single great problem at the center of all of that, to my mind, is the origin of the eukaryotic cell, which happened once and without eukaryotes, nothing else would have happened.

2:24:56.680 --> 2:24:58.680
 And that is something that...

2:24:58.680 --> 2:25:02.680
 That's because you're saying it's super important, the eukaryotes, but...

2:25:02.680 --> 2:25:08.680
 I'm saying tantamount to saying that it is impossible to build something as complex as a human being from bacterial cells.

2:25:08.680 --> 2:25:17.680
 Totally agree in some deep fundamental way, but it's just like a one cell going inside another. Is that so difficult to get to work right?

2:25:17.680 --> 2:25:24.680
 Well, again, it happened once, and if you think about...

2:25:24.680 --> 2:25:33.680
 I'm in a minority view in this position, most biologists probably wouldn't agree with me anyway, but if you think about the starting point, we've got a simple cell.

2:25:33.680 --> 2:25:41.680
 It's an archaeal cell, we can be fairly sure about that, so it looks a lot like a bacterium, but it's in fact from this other domain of life.

2:25:41.680 --> 2:25:49.680
 So it looks a lot like a bacterial cell, that means it doesn't have anything, it doesn't have a nucleus, it doesn't really have complex endomembrane.

2:25:49.680 --> 2:25:52.680
 It has a little bit of stuff, but not that much.

2:25:52.680 --> 2:25:55.680
 And it takes up an endosymbiont.

2:25:55.680 --> 2:25:57.680
 So what happens next?

2:25:57.680 --> 2:26:01.680
 And the answer is basically everything to do with complexity.

2:26:01.680 --> 2:26:05.680
 To me, there's a beautiful paradox here.

2:26:05.680 --> 2:26:15.680
 Plants and animals and fungi all have exactly the same type of cell, but they all have really different ways of living.

2:26:15.680 --> 2:26:23.680
 So a plant cell is photosynthetic, they started out as algae in the oceans and so on.

2:26:23.680 --> 2:26:34.680
 So think of algal, blooms, single cell things, the basic cell structure that it's built from is exactly the same with a couple of small differences.

2:26:34.680 --> 2:26:38.680
 It's got chloroplasts as well, it's got a vacuole, it's got a cell wall, but that's about it.

2:26:38.680 --> 2:26:42.680
 Pretty much everything else is exactly the same in a plant cell and an animal cell.

2:26:42.680 --> 2:26:45.680
 And yet the ways of life are completely different.

2:26:45.680 --> 2:26:54.680
 So this cell structure did not evolve in response to different ways of life, different environments.

2:26:54.680 --> 2:26:58.680
 I'm in the ocean doing photosynthesis, I'm on land running around as part of an animal, I'm a fungus in a soil,

2:26:58.680 --> 2:27:03.680
 spending out long kind of shoots into whatever it may be, mycelium.

2:27:03.680 --> 2:27:06.680
 So they all have the same underlying cell structure.

2:27:06.680 --> 2:27:17.680
 Why? Almost certainly it was driven by adaptation to the internal environment, to having these pesky endosymbionts that forced all kinds of change on the host cell.

2:27:17.680 --> 2:27:22.680
 Now in one way you could see that as a really good thing, because it may be that there's some inevitability to this process,

2:27:22.680 --> 2:27:25.680
 that as soon as you've got endosymbionts you're more or less bound to go in that direction,

2:27:25.680 --> 2:27:32.680
 or it could be that there's a huge fluke about it and it's almost certain to go wrong in just about every case possible,

2:27:32.680 --> 2:27:38.680
 that the conflict will lead to effectively war leading to death and extinction and it simply doesn't work out.

2:27:38.680 --> 2:27:45.680
 So maybe it happened millions of times and it went wrong every time, or maybe it only happened once and it worked out because it was inevitable.

2:27:45.680 --> 2:27:51.680
 And actually we simply do not know enough now to say which of those two possibilities is true, but both of them are a bit grim.

2:27:51.680 --> 2:27:58.680
 But you're leaning towards, we just got really lucky in that one leap.

2:27:58.680 --> 2:28:07.680
 So do you have a sense that our galaxy, for example, has just maybe millions of planets with bacteria living on it?

2:28:07.680 --> 2:28:12.680
 I would expect billions, tens of billions of planets with bacteria living on it practically.

2:28:12.680 --> 2:28:20.680
 I mean there's probably five to ten planets per star of which I would hope that at least one would have bacteria on.

2:28:20.680 --> 2:28:23.680
 So I expect bacteria to be very common.

2:28:23.680 --> 2:28:28.680
 I simply can't put a number otherwise, I mean I expect it will happen elsewhere.

2:28:28.680 --> 2:28:36.680
 It's not that I think we're living in a completely empty universe, but I think that it's not going to happen inevitably and there's something,

2:28:36.680 --> 2:28:43.680
 that's not the only problem with complex life on Earth, I mentioned, and animals and so on as well.

2:28:43.680 --> 2:28:45.680
 And even humans, we came along very late.

2:28:45.680 --> 2:28:51.680
 You go back five million years and would we be that impressed if we came across a planet full of giraffes?

2:28:51.680 --> 2:28:55.680
 I mean, you'd think, hey, there's life here and there's a nice planet to colonize or something.

2:28:55.680 --> 2:28:59.680
 We wouldn't think, oh, let's try and have a conversation with this giraffe.

2:28:59.680 --> 2:29:03.680
 Yeah, I'm not sure what exactly we would think.

2:29:03.680 --> 2:29:11.680
 I'm not exactly sure what makes humans so interesting from an alien perspective or how they would notice.

2:29:11.680 --> 2:29:17.680
 I'll talk to you about cities too because that's an interesting perspective of how to look at human civilization.

2:29:17.680 --> 2:29:23.680
 But your sense, I mean, of course you don't know, but it's an interesting world.

2:29:23.680 --> 2:29:25.680
 It's an interesting galaxy.

2:29:25.680 --> 2:29:38.680
 It's an interesting universe to live in that's just like every sun, like 90% of solar systems have bacteria in it.

2:29:38.680 --> 2:29:50.680
 Imagine that world and the galaxy maybe has just a handful, if not one, intelligent civilization.

2:29:50.680 --> 2:29:52.680
 That's a wild world.

2:29:52.680 --> 2:29:55.680
 I didn't even think about that world.

2:29:55.680 --> 2:30:03.680
 There's a kind of thought that one of the reasons it would be so exciting to find life on Mars or Titan or whatever,

2:30:03.680 --> 2:30:17.680
 is like if it's life is elsewhere, then surely, statistically, that life, no matter how unlikely you carry as multi cell organisms, sex, violence,

2:30:17.680 --> 2:30:19.680
 what else is extremely difficult?

2:30:19.680 --> 2:30:30.680
 I mean, photosynthesis is figuring out some machinery that involves the chemistry and the environment to allow the building up of complex organisms.

2:30:30.680 --> 2:30:32.680
 Surely that would arise.

2:30:32.680 --> 2:30:37.680
 But man, I don't know how I would feel about just bacteria everywhere.

2:30:37.680 --> 2:30:40.680
 Well, it would be depressing if it was true.

2:30:40.680 --> 2:30:41.680
 I suppose depressing.

2:30:41.680 --> 2:30:42.680
 I don't think that's true.

2:30:42.680 --> 2:30:46.680
 I don't know what's more depressing, bacteria everywhere, nothing everywhere.

2:30:46.680 --> 2:30:48.680
 Yes, either of them are chilling.

2:30:48.680 --> 2:30:49.680
 Yeah.

2:30:49.680 --> 2:30:56.680
 But whether it's chilling or not, I don't think should force us to change our view about whether it's real or not.

2:30:56.680 --> 2:30:57.680
 Yes.

2:30:57.680 --> 2:30:59.680
 And what I'm saying may or may not be true.

2:30:59.680 --> 2:31:02.680
 So how would you feel if we discovered life on Mars?

2:31:02.680 --> 2:31:08.680
 It sounds like you would be less excited than some others because you're like, wow.

2:31:08.680 --> 2:31:11.680
 What I would be most interested in is how similar to life on Earth it would be.

2:31:11.680 --> 2:31:25.680
 It would actually turn into quite a subtle problem because the likelihood of life having gone to and fro between Mars and the Earth is quite, I wouldn't say high, but it's not low.

2:31:25.680 --> 2:31:26.680
 It's quite feasible.

2:31:26.680 --> 2:31:33.680
 And so if we found life on Mars and it had very similar genetic code, but it was slightly different.

2:31:33.680 --> 2:31:41.680
 Most people would interpret that immediately as evidence that there'd been transit one way or the other and that it was a common origin of life on Mars or on the Earth.

2:31:41.680 --> 2:31:42.680
 And it went one way or the other way.

2:31:42.680 --> 2:31:56.680
 The other way to see that question, though, would be to say, well, actually the beginnings of life lie in deterministic chemistry and thermodynamics, starting with the most likely abundant materials, CO2 and water and wet rocky planet.

2:31:56.680 --> 2:31:59.680
 And Mars was wet and rocky at the beginning.

2:31:59.680 --> 2:32:08.680
 And we'll, I won't say inevitably, but potentially almost inevitably come up with a genetic code, which is not very far away from the genetic code that we already have.

2:32:08.680 --> 2:32:11.680
 So we see subtle differences in the genetic code.

2:32:11.680 --> 2:32:12.680
 What does it mean?

2:32:12.680 --> 2:32:14.680
 It could be very difficult to interpret.

2:32:14.680 --> 2:32:19.680
 Is it possible, do you think, to tell the difference or something that truly originated?

2:32:19.680 --> 2:32:32.680
 I think if the stereochemistry was different, we have sugars, for example, that are the L form or the D form and we have D sugars and L amino acids right across all of life.

2:32:32.680 --> 2:32:41.680
 But lipids, the bacteria have one stereoisomer and the bacteria have the other, the opposite stereoisomer.

2:32:41.680 --> 2:32:45.680
 So it's perfectly possible to use one or the other one.

2:32:45.680 --> 2:32:55.680
 And the same would almost certainly go for, and I think George Church has been trying to make life based on the opposite stereoisomer.

2:32:55.680 --> 2:32:58.680
 So it's perfectly possible to do and it will work.

2:32:58.680 --> 2:33:08.680
 And if we were to find life on Mars that was using the opposite stereoisomer, that would be unequivocal evidence that life had started independently there.

2:33:08.680 --> 2:33:17.680
 So hopefully the life we find will be on Titan and Europa or something like that, where it's less likely that we shared and it's harsher conditions.

2:33:17.680 --> 2:33:19.680
 So there's going to be weird kind of life.

2:33:19.680 --> 2:33:25.680
 I wouldn't count on that because life started in deep sea hydrothermal vents.

2:33:25.680 --> 2:33:26.680
 It's harsh.

2:33:26.680 --> 2:33:28.680
 That's pretty harsh, yeah.

2:33:28.680 --> 2:33:29.680
 So Titan is different.

2:33:29.680 --> 2:33:33.680
 Europa is probably quite similar to Earth in the sense that we're dealing with an ocean.

2:33:33.680 --> 2:33:38.680
 It's an acidic ocean there as the early Earth would have been.

2:33:38.680 --> 2:33:42.680
 And it almost certainly has hydrothermal systems, same with Enceladus.

2:33:42.680 --> 2:33:46.680
 We can tell that from these plumes coming from the surface through the ice.

2:33:46.680 --> 2:33:50.680
 We know there's a liquid ocean and we can tell roughly what the chemistry is.

2:33:50.680 --> 2:34:00.680
 For Titan, we're dealing with liquid methane and things like that. So that would really, if there really is life there, it would really have to be very, very different to anything that we know on Earth.

2:34:00.680 --> 2:34:08.680
 So the hardest leap, the hardest leap, the most important leap is from prokaryotes to eukaryotes.

2:34:08.680 --> 2:34:12.680
 What's the second if we're ranking?

2:34:12.680 --> 2:34:17.680
 You gave a lot of emphasis on photosynthesis.

2:34:17.680 --> 2:34:20.680
 Yeah, and that would be my second one, I think.

2:34:20.680 --> 2:34:24.680
 But it's not so much, I mean, photosynthesis is part of the problem.

2:34:24.680 --> 2:34:26.680
 It's a difficult thing to do.

2:34:26.680 --> 2:34:29.680
 Again, we know it happened once.

2:34:29.680 --> 2:34:32.680
 We don't know why it happened once.

2:34:32.680 --> 2:34:43.680
 But the fact that it was kind of taken on board completely by plants and algae and so on as chloroplasts,

2:34:43.680 --> 2:34:48.680
 and did very well in completely different environments and then on land and whatever else,

2:34:48.680 --> 2:34:53.680
 seems to suggest that there's no problem with exploring.

2:34:53.680 --> 2:34:59.680
 You could have a separate origin that explored this whole domain over there that the bacteria had never gone into.

2:34:59.680 --> 2:35:06.680
 So that kind of says that the reason that it only happened once is probably because it's difficult, because the wiring is difficult.

2:35:06.680 --> 2:35:13.680
 But then it happened at least 2.2 billion years ago, right before the GOE,

2:35:13.680 --> 2:35:18.680
 maybe as long as 3 billion years ago, when some people say there are whiffs of oxygen,

2:35:18.680 --> 2:35:23.680
 there's just kind of traces in the fossil in the geochemical record that say maybe there was a bit of oxygen then,

2:35:23.680 --> 2:35:25.680
 that's really disputed.

2:35:25.680 --> 2:35:32.680
 Some people say it goes all the way back 4 billion years ago and that it was the common ancestor of life on Earth was photosynthetic.

2:35:32.680 --> 2:35:40.680
 And immediately you've got groups of people who disagree over a 2 billion year period of time about when it started.

2:35:40.680 --> 2:35:47.680
 But let's take the latest date when it's unequivocal, that's 2.2 billion years ago,

2:35:47.680 --> 2:35:53.680
 through to around about the time of the Cambrian explosion when oxygen levels definitely got close to modern levels,

2:35:53.680 --> 2:35:56.680
 which was around about 550 million years ago.

2:35:56.680 --> 2:36:02.680
 So we've gone more than one and a half billion years where the Earth was in stasis,

2:36:02.680 --> 2:36:07.680
 nothing much changed, as known as the Boring Billion, in fact.

2:36:07.680 --> 2:36:14.680
 Probably stuff was, that was when Eukaryotes arose somewhere in there, but it's...

2:36:14.680 --> 2:36:20.680
 So this idea that the world is constantly changing, that we're constantly evolving, that we're moving up some ramp,

2:36:20.680 --> 2:36:32.680
 it's a very human idea, but in reality there are tipping points to a new stable equilibrium,

2:36:32.680 --> 2:36:39.680
 where the cells that are producing oxygen are precisely counterbalanced by the cells that are consuming that oxygen,

2:36:39.680 --> 2:36:44.680
 which is why it's 21% now and has been that way for hundreds of millions of years.

2:36:44.680 --> 2:36:46.680
 We have a very precise balance.

2:36:46.680 --> 2:36:51.680
 You go through a tipping point and you don't know where the next stable state's going to be,

2:36:51.680 --> 2:36:53.680
 but it can be a long way from here.

2:36:53.680 --> 2:36:58.680
 And so if we change the world with global warming, there will be a tipping point.

2:36:58.680 --> 2:37:01.680
 The question is where and when, and what's the next stable state?

2:37:01.680 --> 2:37:03.680
 It may be uninhabitable to us.

2:37:03.680 --> 2:37:06.680
 It'll be habitable to life, for sure.

2:37:06.680 --> 2:37:11.680
 But there may be something like the Permian extinction, where 95% of species go extinct.

2:37:11.680 --> 2:37:16.680
 There's a 5 to 10 million year gap and then life recovers, but without humans.

2:37:16.680 --> 2:37:19.680
 And the question statistically, well, without humans, but statistically,

2:37:19.680 --> 2:37:25.680
 does that ultimately lead to greater complexity, more interesting life, more intelligent life?

2:37:25.680 --> 2:37:30.680
 Well, after the first appearance of oxygen with the GOE, there was a tipping point,

2:37:30.680 --> 2:37:34.680
 which led to a long term stable state that was equivalent to the Black Sea today,

2:37:34.680 --> 2:37:42.680
 which is to say oxygenated at the very surface and stagnant sterile, not sterile, but sulfurous, lower down.

2:37:42.680 --> 2:37:49.680
 And that was stable certainly around the continental margins for more than a billion years.

2:37:49.680 --> 2:37:54.680
 It was not a state that led to progression in an obvious way.

2:37:54.680 --> 2:38:00.680
 Yeah, I mean, it's interesting to think about evolution, like what leads to stable states

2:38:00.680 --> 2:38:10.680
 and how often are evolutionary pressures emerging from the environment?

2:38:10.680 --> 2:38:16.680
 So maybe other planets are able to create evolutionary pressures, chemical pressures, whatever.

2:38:16.680 --> 2:38:23.680
 Some kind of pressure that say, you're screwed unless you get your shit together in the next, like, 10,000 years.

2:38:23.680 --> 2:38:25.680
 Like a lot of pressure.

2:38:25.680 --> 2:38:30.680
 It seems like Earth, like the boring building might be explained in two ways.

2:38:30.680 --> 2:38:34.680
 One is super difficult to take any kind of next step.

2:38:34.680 --> 2:38:38.680
 And the second way it could be explained is there's no reason to take the next step.

2:38:38.680 --> 2:38:40.680
 No, I think there is no reason.

2:38:40.680 --> 2:38:44.680
 But at the end of it, there was a snowball Earth.

2:38:44.680 --> 2:38:54.680
 So there was a planetary catastrophe on a huge scale where the sea was frozen at the equator.

2:38:54.680 --> 2:38:58.680
 And that forced change in one way or another.

2:38:58.680 --> 2:39:02.680
 It's not long after that, 100 million years, perhaps after that, so not a short time,

2:39:02.680 --> 2:39:04.680
 but this is when we begin to see animals.

2:39:04.680 --> 2:39:11.680
 There was a shift again, another tipping point that led to catastrophic change that led to a takeoff then.

2:39:11.680 --> 2:39:20.680
 We don't really know why, but one of the reasons why that I discuss in the book is about sulfate being washed into the oceans,

2:39:20.680 --> 2:39:23.680
 which sounds incredibly parochial.

2:39:23.680 --> 2:39:35.680
 But what the data is showing, we can track roughly how oxygen was going into the atmosphere from carbon isotopes.

2:39:35.680 --> 2:39:39.680
 So there's two main isotopes of carbon that we need to think about here.

2:39:39.680 --> 2:39:42.680
 One is carbon 12, 99% of carbon is carbon 12.

2:39:42.680 --> 2:39:45.680
 And then 1% of carbon is carbon 13, which is a stable isotope.

2:39:45.680 --> 2:39:50.680
 And then there's carbon 14, which is a trivial radioactiveness, trivial amount.

2:39:50.680 --> 2:39:52.680
 So carbon 13 is 1%.

2:39:52.680 --> 2:40:01.680
 And life and enzymes generally, you can think of carbon atoms as little balls bouncing around, ping pong balls bouncing around.

2:40:01.680 --> 2:40:05.680
 Carbon 12 moves a little bit faster than carbon 13 because it's lighter.

2:40:05.680 --> 2:40:08.680
 And it's more likely to encounter an enzyme.

2:40:08.680 --> 2:40:11.680
 And so it's more likely to be fixed into organic matter.

2:40:11.680 --> 2:40:14.680
 And so organic matter is enriched, and this is just an observation.

2:40:14.680 --> 2:40:18.680
 It's enriched in carbon 12 by a few percent compared to carbon 13,

2:40:18.680 --> 2:40:21.680
 relative to what you would expect if it was just equal.

2:40:21.680 --> 2:40:31.680
 And if you then bury organic matter as coal or oil or whatever it may be, then it's no longer oxidized.

2:40:31.680 --> 2:40:34.680
 So some oxygen remains left over in the atmosphere.

2:40:34.680 --> 2:40:37.680
 And that's how oxygen accumulates in the atmosphere.

2:40:37.680 --> 2:40:43.680
 And you can work out historically how much oxygen there must have been in the atmosphere by how much carbon was being buried.

2:40:43.680 --> 2:40:46.680
 And you think, well, how can we possibly know how much carbon was being buried?

2:40:46.680 --> 2:40:51.680
 And the answer is, well, if you're burying carbon 12, what you're leaving behind is more carbon 13 in the oceans.

2:40:51.680 --> 2:40:53.680
 And that precipitates out in limestone.

2:40:53.680 --> 2:40:58.680
 So you can look at limestones over these ages and work out what's the carbon 13 signal.

2:40:58.680 --> 2:41:02.680
 And that gives you a kind of a feedback on what the oxygen content.

2:41:02.680 --> 2:41:08.680
 Right before the Cambrian explosion, there was what's called a negative isotope anomaly excursion,

2:41:08.680 --> 2:41:14.680
 which is basically the carbon 13 goes down by a massive amount and then back up again 10 million years later.

2:41:14.680 --> 2:41:25.680
 And what that seems to be saying is the amount of carbon 12 in the oceans was disappearing,

2:41:25.680 --> 2:41:29.680
 which is to say it was being oxidized.

2:41:29.680 --> 2:41:33.680
 And if it's being oxidized, it's consuming oxygen and that should.

