 So, no, I mean, I think I can understand the wiring of a brain as a series of...

2:49:07.680 --> 2:49:16.680
 In pretty much the same way as a computer in theory, in terms of the circuitry of it.

2:49:16.680 --> 2:49:23.680
 The mystery to me is how this system gives rise to feelings as we were talking about earlier on.

2:49:23.680 --> 2:49:28.680
 Yeah, I think we oversimplify intelligence.

2:49:28.680 --> 2:49:35.680
 The magic of reasoning is as interesting as the magic of feeling.

2:49:35.680 --> 2:49:44.680
 We tend to think of reasoning as like running a very simplistic algorithm.

2:49:44.680 --> 2:49:54.680
 I think reasoning is the interplay between memory, whatever the hell is going on, the unconscious mind, all of that.

2:49:54.680 --> 2:49:58.680
 I'm not trying to diminish it in any way at all.

2:49:58.680 --> 2:50:06.680
 Obviously, it's extraordinarily exquisitely complex, but I don't see a logical difficulty with how it works.

2:50:06.680 --> 2:50:15.680
 Yeah, no, I mean, I agree with you, but sometimes, yeah, there's a big cloak of mystery around consciousness.

2:50:15.680 --> 2:50:19.680
 Let me compare it with classical versus quantum physics.

2:50:19.680 --> 2:50:27.680
 You know, classical physics is logical and you can understand the kind of language we're dealing with.

2:50:27.680 --> 2:50:31.680
 It's almost at the human level, we're dealing with stars and things that we can see.

2:50:31.680 --> 2:50:39.680
 And when you get to quantum mechanics and things, it's practically impossible for the human mind to compute what just happened there.

2:50:39.680 --> 2:50:41.680
 Yeah, I mean, that is the same.

