3:02:50.680 --> 3:02:58.680
 So some of the work we're doing on the origin of life is thinking about how does genes arise,

3:02:58.680 --> 3:03:01.680
 how does information arise in biology,

3:03:01.680 --> 3:03:05.680
 and thinking about it from the point of view of reacting CO2 with hydrogen,

3:03:05.680 --> 3:03:09.680
 what do you get? Well, what you're going to get is coboxylic acids and amino acids.

3:03:09.680 --> 3:03:14.680
 It's quite hard to make nucleotides, and it's possible to make them,

3:03:14.680 --> 3:03:17.680
 and it's been done, and it's been done following this pathway as well.

3:03:17.680 --> 3:03:19.680
 But you make trace amounts.

3:03:19.680 --> 3:03:23.680
 And so the next question, assuming that this is the right way of seeing the question,

3:03:23.680 --> 3:03:26.680
 which maybe it's just not, but let's assume it is,

3:03:26.680 --> 3:03:29.680
 is, well, how do you reliably make more nucleotides then?

3:03:29.680 --> 3:03:34.680
 How do you become more complex and better at becoming a nucleotide generating machine?

3:03:34.680 --> 3:03:37.680
 And the answer is, well, you need positive feedback loops,

3:03:37.680 --> 3:03:39.680
 some form of autocatalysis.

3:03:39.680 --> 3:03:42.680
 So that can work, and we know it happens in biology.

3:03:42.680 --> 3:03:47.680
 If this nucleotide, for example, catalyzes CO2 fixation,

3:03:47.680 --> 3:03:50.680
 then you're going to increase the rate of flux through the whole system,

3:03:50.680 --> 3:03:55.680
 and you're going to effectively steepen the driving force to make more nucleotides.

3:03:55.680 --> 3:04:02.680
 And this can be inherited because there are forms of membrane heredity that you can have,

3:04:02.680 --> 3:04:07.680
 and effectively, if a cell divides in two and it's got a lot of stuff inside it,

3:04:07.680 --> 3:04:13.680
 and that stuff is basically bound as a network which is capable of regenerating itself,

3:04:13.680 --> 3:04:16.680
 then it will inevitably regenerate itself.

3:04:16.680 --> 3:04:20.680
 And so you can develop greater complexity.

3:04:20.680 --> 3:04:25.680
 But everything that I've said depends on the underlying rules of thermodynamics.

3:04:25.680 --> 3:04:27.680
 There is no evolvability about that.

3:04:27.680 --> 3:04:32.680
 It's simply an inevitable outcome of your starting point,

3:04:32.680 --> 3:04:36.680
 assuming that you're able to increase the driving force through the system.

3:04:36.680 --> 3:04:39.680
 You will generate more of the same, you'll expand on what you can do,

3:04:39.680 --> 3:04:42.680
 but you'll never get anything different than that.

3:04:42.680 --> 3:04:46.680
 And it's only when you introduce information into that as a gene,

3:04:46.680 --> 3:04:53.680
 as a kind of small stretch of RNA, which can be random stretch,

3:04:53.680 --> 3:04:56.680
 then you get real evolvability, then you get biology as we know it.

3:04:56.680 --> 3:04:59.680
 But you also have selection as we know it.

3:04:59.680 --> 3:05:04.680
 Yeah, I mean, I don't know how to think about information.

3:05:04.680 --> 3:05:07.680
 That's the kind of memory of the system.

3:05:07.680 --> 3:05:12.680
 At the local level, it's propagation of copying yourself and changing

3:05:12.680 --> 3:05:16.680
 and improving your adaptability to the environment.

3:05:16.680 --> 3:05:22.680
 But if you look at Earth as a whole, it has a kind of memory.

3:05:22.680 --> 3:05:24.680
 That's the key feature of it.

3:05:24.680 --> 3:05:27.680
 In what way?

3:05:27.680 --> 3:05:30.680
 It remembers the stuff it tries.

3:05:30.680 --> 3:05:33.680
 Like if you were to describe Earth,

3:05:33.680 --> 3:05:41.680
 I think evolution is something that we experience as individual organisms.

3:05:41.680 --> 3:05:45.680
 That's how the individual organisms interact with each other.

3:05:45.680 --> 3:05:47.680
 There's a natural selection.

3:05:47.680 --> 3:05:53.680
 But when you look at Earth as an organism in its entirety,

3:05:53.680 --> 3:05:55.680
 how would you describe it?

3:05:55.680 --> 3:05:57.680
 Well, not as an organism.

3:05:57.680 --> 3:06:00.680
 I mean, the idea of Gaia is lovely.

3:06:00.680 --> 3:06:06.680
 And James Lovelock originally put Gaia out as an organism that had somehow evolved.

3:06:06.680 --> 3:06:09.680
 And he was immediately attacked by lots of people.

3:06:09.680 --> 3:06:13.680
 And he's not wrong, but he backpedaled somewhat,

3:06:13.680 --> 3:06:19.680
 because that was more of a poetic vision than the science.

3:06:19.680 --> 3:06:23.680
 The science is now called Earth systems science.

3:06:23.680 --> 3:06:26.680
 And it's really about how does the world kind of regulate itself,

3:06:26.680 --> 3:06:29.680
 so it remains within the limits which are hospitable to life.

3:06:29.680 --> 3:06:31.680
 And it does it amazingly well.

3:06:31.680 --> 3:06:38.680
 And it is working at a planetary level of kind of integration, of regulation.

3:06:38.680 --> 3:06:41.680
 But it's not evolving by natural selection.

3:06:41.680 --> 3:06:43.680
 And it can't because there's only one of it.

3:06:43.680 --> 3:06:46.680
 And so it can change over time, but it's not evolving.

3:06:46.680 --> 3:06:50.680
 All the evolution is happening in the parts of the system.

3:06:50.680 --> 3:06:52.680
 Yeah, but it's a self sustaining organism.

3:06:52.680 --> 3:06:55.680
 No, it's sustained by the sun.

3:06:55.680 --> 3:06:56.680
 Right.

3:06:56.680 --> 3:07:02.680
 So you don't think it's possible to see Earth as its own organism?

3:07:02.680 --> 3:07:04.680
 I think it's poetic and beautiful.

3:07:04.680 --> 3:07:07.680
 And I often refer to the Earth as a living planet.

3:07:07.680 --> 3:07:12.680
 But it's not in biological terms an organism.

3:07:12.680 --> 3:07:14.680
 No.

3:07:14.680 --> 3:07:20.680
 If aliens were to visit Earth, what would they notice?

3:07:20.680 --> 3:07:23.680
 What would be the basic unit of light they would notice?

3:07:23.680 --> 3:07:24.680
 Trees, probably.

3:07:24.680 --> 3:07:26.680
 I mean, it's green and blue.

3:07:26.680 --> 3:07:28.680
 I think that's the first thing you'd notice.

3:07:28.680 --> 3:07:32.680
 It stands out from space as being different to any of the other planets.

3:07:32.680 --> 3:07:35.680
 So it would notice the trees at first?

3:07:35.680 --> 3:07:38.680
 Well, I would notice the green, yes.

3:07:38.680 --> 3:07:42.680
 And then probably notice to figure out the photosynthesis.

3:07:42.680 --> 3:07:46.680
 Probably notice cities a second, I suspect, at first.

3:07:46.680 --> 3:07:47.680
 They arrived at night.

3:07:47.680 --> 3:07:49.680
 They noticed cities first, that's for sure.

3:07:49.680 --> 3:07:51.680
 It depends the time.

3:07:51.680 --> 3:07:55.680
 You write quite beautifully in Transformers once again.

3:07:55.680 --> 3:07:57.680
 I think you opened the book in this way.

3:07:57.680 --> 3:07:58.680
 I don't remember.

3:07:58.680 --> 3:08:05.680
 From space describing Earth, it's such an interesting idea of what Earth is.

3:08:05.680 --> 3:08:13.680
 You also, I mean, Hitchhiker's Guide summarizing it as harmless, or mostly harmless,

3:08:13.680 --> 3:08:15.680
 which is a beautifully poetic thing.

3:08:15.680 --> 3:08:21.680
 You open Transformers with from space, it looks gray and crystalline,

3:08:21.680 --> 3:08:24.680
 obliterating the blue, green colors of the living Earth.

3:08:24.680 --> 3:08:30.680
 It is crisscrossed by regular patterns and convergent striations.

3:08:30.680 --> 3:08:34.680
 There's a central amorphous density where these scratches seem lighter.

3:08:34.680 --> 3:08:40.680
 This, quote, growth does not look alive, although it has extended out along some lines

3:08:40.680 --> 3:08:44.680
 and there is something grasping and parasitic about it.

3:08:44.680 --> 3:08:48.680
 Across the globe, there are thousands of them, varying in shape and detail,

3:08:48.680 --> 3:08:53.680
 but all of them gray, angular, and organic, spreading.

3:08:53.680 --> 3:08:56.680
 Yet, at night, they light up.

3:08:56.680 --> 3:08:59.680
 Going up the dark sky, suddenly beautiful.

3:08:59.680 --> 3:09:04.680
 Perhaps these cankers on the landscape are, in some sense, living.

3:09:04.680 --> 3:09:06.680
 There's a controlled flow of energy.

3:09:06.680 --> 3:09:11.680
 There must be information and some form of metabolism, some turnover of materials.

3:09:11.680 --> 3:09:13.680
 Are they alive?

3:09:13.680 --> 3:09:15.680
 No, of course not.

3:09:15.680 --> 3:09:17.680
 They are cities.

3:09:17.680 --> 3:09:21.680
 So is there some sense that cities are living beings?

3:09:21.680 --> 3:09:24.680
 You think aliens would think of them as living beings?

3:09:24.680 --> 3:09:29.680
 Well, it would be easy to see it that way, wouldn't it?

3:09:29.680 --> 3:09:32.680
 It wakes up at night, they wake up at night.

3:09:32.680 --> 3:09:35.680
 Strictly nocturnal, yes.

3:09:35.680 --> 3:09:39.680
 I imagine that any aliens that are smart enough to get here would understand

3:09:39.680 --> 3:09:42.680
 that they're not living beings.

3:09:42.680 --> 3:09:52.680
 My reason for saying that is that we tend to think of biology in terms of information

3:09:52.680 --> 3:09:54.680
 and forget about cells.

3:09:54.680 --> 3:09:57.680
 I was trying to draw a comparison between the cell as a city

3:09:57.680 --> 3:10:01.680
 and the energy flow through the city and the energy flow through cells

3:10:01.680 --> 3:10:03.680
 and the turnover of materials.

3:10:03.680 --> 3:10:11.680
 An interesting thing about cities is that they're not really exactly governed by anybody.

3:10:11.680 --> 3:10:18.680
 There are regulations and systems and whatever else, but it's pretty loose.

3:10:18.680 --> 3:10:23.680
 They have their own life, their own way of developing over time.

3:10:23.680 --> 3:10:26.680
 In that sense, they're quite biological.

3:10:26.680 --> 3:10:30.680
 There was a plan after the Great Fire of London.

3:10:30.680 --> 3:10:35.680
 Christopher Wren was making plans not only for St Paul's Cathedral,

3:10:35.680 --> 3:10:39.680
 but also to rebuild in large Parisian type boulevards,

3:10:39.680 --> 3:10:44.680
 a large part of the area of central London that was burnt.

3:10:44.680 --> 3:10:47.680
 It never happened because they didn't have enough money, I think.

3:10:47.680 --> 3:10:49.680
 But it's interesting what was in the plan.

3:10:49.680 --> 3:10:56.680
 There were all these boulevards, but there were no pubs and no coffee houses or anything like that.

3:10:56.680 --> 3:11:02.680
 The reality was London just kind of grew up in a set of jumbled streets.

3:11:02.680 --> 3:11:06.680
 It was the coffee house and the pubs where all the business of the city of London was being done.

3:11:06.680 --> 3:11:08.680
 That was where the real life of the city was.

3:11:08.680 --> 3:11:09.680
 No one had planned it.

3:11:09.680 --> 3:11:13.680
 The whole thing was unplanned and works much better that way.

3:11:13.680 --> 3:11:17.680
 And in that sense, the cell is completely unplanned, is not controlled by the genes in the nucleus

3:11:17.680 --> 3:11:19.680
 in the way that we might like to think that it is.

3:11:19.680 --> 3:11:25.680
 But it's this kind of evolved entity that has the same kind of flux, the same animation, the same life.

3:11:25.680 --> 3:11:31.680
 So I think it's a beautiful analogy, but I wouldn't get too stuck with it as a metaphor.

3:11:31.680 --> 3:11:33.680
 See, I disagree with you.

3:11:33.680 --> 3:11:34.680
 I disagree with you.

3:11:34.680 --> 3:11:43.680
 I think you are so steeped in actually the entirety of science.

3:11:43.680 --> 3:11:49.680
 The history of science is steeped in a biological framework of thinking about what is life.

3:11:49.680 --> 3:11:53.680
 And not just biological, it's very human centric too.

3:11:53.680 --> 3:12:00.680
 The human organism is the epitome of life on Earth.

3:12:00.680 --> 3:12:01.680
 I don't know.

3:12:01.680 --> 3:12:08.680
 I think there is some defundamental way in which a city is a living being in the same way that a human...

3:12:08.680 --> 3:12:12.680
 But it doesn't give rise to an offspring city.

3:12:12.680 --> 3:12:15.680
 It doesn't work by natural selection.

3:12:15.680 --> 3:12:17.680
 It works by, if anything, memes.

3:12:17.680 --> 3:12:23.680
 It works by copying itself conceptually as a mode of being.

3:12:23.680 --> 3:12:31.680
 So maybe memes, maybe ideas are the organisms that are really essential to life on Earth.

3:12:31.680 --> 3:12:36.680
 Maybe it's much more important about the collective aspect of human nature,

3:12:36.680 --> 3:12:39.680
 the collective intelligence than the individual intelligence.

3:12:39.680 --> 3:12:43.680
 Maybe the collective humanity is the organism.

3:12:43.680 --> 3:12:49.680
 And the thing that defines the collective intelligence of humanity is the ideas.

3:12:49.680 --> 3:12:53.680
 And maybe the way that manifests itself is cities.

3:12:53.680 --> 3:12:59.680
 Or societies or geographically constrained societies or nations and all that kind of stuff.

3:12:59.680 --> 3:13:08.680
 I mean, from an alien perspective, it's possible that that is the more deeply noticeable thing, not from a place of ignorance.

3:13:08.680 --> 3:13:11.680
 What's noticeable doesn't tell you how it works.

3:13:11.680 --> 3:13:17.680
 I don't have any problem with what you're saying, really, except that it's not possible

3:13:17.680 --> 3:13:20.680
 without the humans...

3:13:20.680 --> 3:13:26.680
 We went from a hunter gatherer type economy, if you like, without cities.

3:13:26.680 --> 3:13:32.680
 And as soon as we get into human evolution and culture and society and so on,

3:13:32.680 --> 3:13:37.680
 then yes, there are other forms of evolution, other forms of change.

3:13:37.680 --> 3:13:41.680
 But cities don't directly propagate themselves.

3:13:41.680 --> 3:13:43.680
 They propagate themselves through human societies.

3:13:43.680 --> 3:13:48.680
 In fact, human societies only exist because humans, as individuals, propagate themselves.

3:13:48.680 --> 3:13:51.680
 So there is a hierarchy there.

3:13:51.680 --> 3:13:54.680
 And without the humans in the first place, none of the rest of it exists.

3:13:54.680 --> 3:14:01.680
 So do you... life is primarily defined by the basic unit on which evolution can operate?

3:14:01.680 --> 3:14:04.680
 I think it's a really important thing, yes.

3:14:04.680 --> 3:14:06.680
 Yeah.

3:14:06.680 --> 3:14:10.680
 And we don't have any other better ideas than evolution for how to create one.

3:14:10.680 --> 3:14:13.680
 I never came across a better idea than evolution.

3:14:13.680 --> 3:14:16.680
 I mean, maybe I'm just ignorant and I don't know.

3:14:16.680 --> 3:14:19.680
 You mentioned automator and so on.

3:14:19.680 --> 3:14:24.680
 And I don't think specifically about that, but I have thought about it in terms of selective units

3:14:24.680 --> 3:14:29.680
 at the origin of life and the difference between evolvability and complexity,

3:14:29.680 --> 3:14:35.680
 or just increasing complexity, but within very narrowly defined limits.

3:14:35.680 --> 3:14:41.680
 The great thing about genes and about selection is it just knocks down all those limits.

3:14:41.680 --> 3:14:47.680
 It gives you a world of information in the end, which is limited only by the biophysical reality

3:14:47.680 --> 3:14:52.680
 of what kind of an organism you are, what kind of a planet you live on and so on.

3:14:52.680 --> 3:14:57.680
 And cities and all these other forms that look alive and could be described as alive,

3:14:57.680 --> 3:15:04.680
 because they can't propagate themselves, can only exist as the product of something that did propagate itself.

3:15:04.680 --> 3:15:06.680
 Yeah.

3:15:06.680 --> 3:15:11.680
 I mean, there's a deeply compelling truth to that kind of way of looking at things,

3:15:11.680 --> 3:15:18.680
 but I just hope that we don't miss the giant cloud among us.

3:15:18.680 --> 3:15:25.680
 I kind of hope that I'm wrong about a lot of this, because I can't say that my world view is particularly uplifting.

3:15:25.680 --> 3:15:29.680
 But in some sense, it doesn't matter if it's uplifting or not.

3:15:29.680 --> 3:15:33.680
 Science is about what's reality, what's out there.

3:15:33.680 --> 3:15:35.680
 Why is it this way?

3:15:35.680 --> 3:15:38.680
 And I think there's beauty in that too.

3:15:38.680 --> 3:15:40.680
 There's beauty in darkness.

3:15:40.680 --> 3:15:45.680
 You write about life and death sort of at the biological level.

3:15:45.680 --> 3:15:53.680
 Does the question of suicide, why live, does the question of why the human mind is capable of depression,

3:15:53.680 --> 3:15:59.680
 are you able to introspect that from a place of biology?

3:15:59.680 --> 3:16:04.680
 Why our minds, why we humans can go to such dark places?

3:16:04.680 --> 3:16:07.680
 Why can we commit suicide?

3:16:07.680 --> 3:16:15.680
 Why can we go, you know, suffer, suffer a period,

3:16:15.680 --> 3:16:22.680
 but also suffer from a feeling of meaninglessness of going to a dark place that depression can take you?

3:16:22.680 --> 3:16:26.680
 Is this a feature of life or is it a bug?

3:16:26.680 --> 3:16:30.680
 I don't know.

3:16:30.680 --> 3:16:35.680
 I mean, if it's a feature of life, then I suppose it would have to be true of other organisms as well.

3:16:35.680 --> 3:16:43.680
 And I don't know, we were talking about dogs earlier on and they can certainly be very sad and upset

3:16:43.680 --> 3:16:47.680
 and may mooch for days after their owner died or something like that.

3:16:47.680 --> 3:16:51.680
 So I suspect in some sense it's a feature of biology.

3:16:51.680 --> 3:16:57.680
 It's probably a feature of mortality.

3:16:57.680 --> 3:17:01.680
 But beyond all of that, I mean, I guess there's two ways you could come at it.

3:17:01.680 --> 3:17:09.680
 There's one of them would be to say, well, you can effectively do the math and come to the conclusion that it's all pointless

3:17:09.680 --> 3:17:13.680
 and that there's really no point in me being here any longer.

3:17:13.680 --> 3:17:21.680
 And maybe that's true in the greater scheme of things, you can justify yourself in terms of society, but society will be gone soon enough as well.

3:17:21.680 --> 3:17:25.680
 And you end up with a very bleak place just by logic.

3:17:25.680 --> 3:17:29.680
 In some sense, it's surprising that we can find any meaning at all.

3:17:29.680 --> 3:17:33.680
 Well, maybe this is where consciousness comes in, that we have transient joy.

3:17:33.680 --> 3:17:36.680
 But with transient joy, we have transient misery as well.

3:17:36.680 --> 3:17:44.680
 And sometimes with everything in biology, getting the regulation right is practically impossible.

3:17:44.680 --> 3:17:51.680
 You will always have a bell shaped curve where some people, unfortunately, are at the joy end and some people are at the misery end.

3:17:51.680 --> 3:17:54.680
 And that's the way brains are wired.

3:17:54.680 --> 3:17:57.680
 And I doubt there's ever an escape from that.

3:17:57.680 --> 3:18:00.680
 It's the same with sex and everything else as well.

3:18:00.680 --> 3:18:11.680
 Or dealing with it, whether you can't regulate it, so anything goes, it's all part of biology.

3:18:11.680 --> 3:18:13.680
 Amen to that.

