 The vital question, the first book I've read of yours, the vital question, why is life the way it is?

3:18:57.680 --> 3:19:02.680
 And the new book, Transformer, the Deep Chemistry of Life and Death.

3:19:02.680 --> 3:19:12.680
 In Power, Sex and Suicide, you write about writing, or about a lot of things, but I have a question about writing.

3:19:12.680 --> 3:19:26.680
 You write, in the Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, Ford Perfect spends 15 years researching his revision to the guide's entry on the Earth, which originally read, harmless.

3:19:26.680 --> 3:19:34.680
 By the way, I would also, as a side quest, as a side question, would like to ask you what would be your summary of what Earth is.

3:19:34.680 --> 3:19:41.680
 You write, his long essay on the subject is edited down by the guide to read, mostly harmless.

3:19:41.680 --> 3:19:51.680
 I suspect that too many new additions suffer similar fate, if not through absurd editing decisions, at least through a lack of meaningful change in content.

3:19:51.680 --> 3:20:02.680
 As it happens, nearly 15 years have passed since the first edition of Power, Sex, Suicide was published, and I am resisting the temptation to make any lame revisions.

3:20:02.680 --> 3:20:15.680
 Some say that even Darwin lessened the power of his arguments in the origin of species through his multiple revisions, in which he dealt with criticisms and sometimes shifted his views in the wrong direction.

3:20:15.680 --> 3:20:22.680
 I prefer my original to speak for itself, even if it turns out to be wrong.

3:20:22.680 --> 3:20:32.680
 Let me ask the question about writing, both your students in the academic setting, but also writing some of the most brilliant writings on science and humanity I've ever read.

3:20:32.680 --> 3:20:35.680
 What's the process of writing?

3:20:35.680 --> 3:20:42.680
 How do you advise other humans?

3:20:42.680 --> 3:20:55.680
 If you were to talk to young Darwin or the young you and just young anybody and give advice about how to write and how to write well about these big topics, what would you say?

3:20:55.680 --> 3:20:58.680
 I suppose there's a couple of points.

3:20:58.680 --> 3:21:02.680
 One of them is what's the story?

3:21:02.680 --> 3:21:04.680
 What do I want to know?

3:21:04.680 --> 3:21:05.680
 What do I want to convey?

3:21:05.680 --> 3:21:08.680
 Why does it matter to anybody?

3:21:08.680 --> 3:21:23.680
 And very often the biggest, most interesting questions, the childlike questions are the one that actually everybody wants to ask, but then quite do it in case they look stupid.

3:21:23.680 --> 3:21:33.680
 And one of the nice things about being in science is the longer you're in, the more you realize that everybody doesn't know the answer to these questions and it's not so stupid to ask them after all.

3:21:33.680 --> 3:21:57.680
 So trying to ask the questions that I would have been asking myself at the age of 15, 16 when I was really hungry to know about the world and didn't know very much about it and wanted to go to the edge of what we know, but be helped to get there.

3:21:57.680 --> 3:22:06.680
 I don't want to be too much terminology and so I want someone to keep a clean eye on what the question is.

3:22:06.680 --> 3:22:12.680
 Beyond that, I've wondered a lot about who am I writing for?

3:22:12.680 --> 3:22:19.680
 And that was in the end, the only answer I had was myself at the age of 15 or 16.

3:22:19.680 --> 3:22:27.680
 Because even if you just don't know who's reading but also where are they reading it?

3:22:27.680 --> 3:22:34.680
 Are they reading it in the bath or in bed or on the metro or listening to an audiobook?

3:22:34.680 --> 3:22:43.680
 Do you want to have a recapitulation every few pages because you read three pages at a time or are you really irritated by that?

3:22:43.680 --> 3:22:51.680
 You're going to get criticism from people who are irritated by what you're doing and you don't know who they are or what you're going to do that's going to irritate people.

3:22:51.680 --> 3:22:56.680
 And in the end, all you can do is just try and please yourself.

3:22:56.680 --> 3:23:02.680
 And that means, well, what are these big fun, fascinating, big questions?

3:23:02.680 --> 3:23:04.680
 And what do we know about it?

3:23:04.680 --> 3:23:06.680
 And can I convey that?

3:23:06.680 --> 3:23:13.680
 And I kind of learned in trying to write, first of all, say what we know.

3:23:13.680 --> 3:23:20.680
 And I was shocked in the first couple of books how often I came up quickly against all the stuff we don't know.

3:23:20.680 --> 3:23:33.680
 And if you're trying to, I've realized later on in supervising various physicists and mathematicians who are PhD students and their maths is way beyond what I can do.

3:23:33.680 --> 3:23:37.680
 But the process of trying to work out, what are we actually going to model here?

3:23:37.680 --> 3:23:38.680
 What's going into this equation?

3:23:38.680 --> 3:23:39.680
 It's a very similar one to writing.

3:23:39.680 --> 3:23:41.680
 What am I going to put on a page?

3:23:41.680 --> 3:23:49.680
 What's the simplest possible way I can encapsulate this idea so that I now have it as a unit that I can kind of see how it interacts with the other units?

3:23:49.680 --> 3:23:57.680
 And you realize that, well, if this is like that and this is like this, then that can't be true.

3:23:57.680 --> 3:24:04.680
 So you end up navigating your own path through this landscape and that can be thrilling because you don't know where it's going.

3:24:04.680 --> 3:24:13.680
 And I'd like to think that that's one of the reasons my books have worked for people because this sense of the thrilling adventure ride, I don't know where it's going either.

3:24:13.680 --> 3:24:22.680
 So finding the simplest possible way to explain the things we know and the simplest possible way to explain the things we don't know and the tension between those two.

3:24:22.680 --> 3:24:24.680
 And that's where the story emerges.

3:24:24.680 --> 3:24:26.680
 What about the edit?

3:24:26.680 --> 3:24:35.680
 Do you find yourself to the point of this editing doll to mostly harmless?

3:24:35.680 --> 3:24:43.680
 To arrive at simplicity, do you find the edit is productive or does it destroy the magic that was originally there?

3:24:43.680 --> 3:24:48.680
 No, I usually find, I think I'm perhaps a better editor than I am a writer.

3:24:48.680 --> 3:24:50.680
 I write and rewrite and rewrite and rewrite.

3:24:50.680 --> 3:24:55.680
 Put a bunch of crap on the page first and then see where the edit where it takes place.

3:24:55.680 --> 3:24:59.680
 But then there's the professional editors who come along as well.

3:24:59.680 --> 3:25:07.680
 And I mean, in Transformer, the editor came back to me after I'd sent him two months after I sent the first edition.

3:25:07.680 --> 3:25:13.680
 He'd read the whole thing and he said, the first two chapters prevent a formidable hurdle to the general reader.

3:25:13.680 --> 3:25:15.680
 Go and do something about it.

3:25:15.680 --> 3:25:18.680
 And it was the last thing I really wanted to do.

3:25:18.680 --> 3:25:21.680
 Your editor sounds very eloquent in speech.

3:25:21.680 --> 3:25:28.680
 Well, this was an email, but I thought about it and, you know, the bottom line is he was right.

3:25:28.680 --> 3:25:33.680
 And so I put the whole thing aside for about two months, spent the summer.

3:25:33.680 --> 3:25:36.680
 This would have been, I guess, last summer.

3:25:36.680 --> 3:25:42.680
 And then turn to it with full attention in about September or something and rewrote those chapters almost from scratch.

3:25:42.680 --> 3:25:48.680
 I kept some of the material, but it took me a long time to process it to work out what needs to change.

3:25:48.680 --> 3:25:51.680
 Where does it need to change? I wasn't writing in this time.

3:25:51.680 --> 3:25:54.680
 How am I going to tell the story better so it's more accessible and interesting?

3:25:54.680 --> 3:25:56.680
 And in the end, I think it worked.

3:25:56.680 --> 3:25:59.680
 It's still difficult. It's still biochemistry.

3:25:59.680 --> 3:26:03.680
 But as he ended up saying, now he's got a barreling energy to it.

3:26:03.680 --> 3:26:06.680
 And I was, you know, because he'd told me the truth the first time,

3:26:06.680 --> 3:26:12.680
 I decided to believe that he was telling me the truth the second time as well and was delighted.

3:26:12.680 --> 3:26:17.680
 Could you give advice to young people in general?

3:26:17.680 --> 3:26:22.680
 Folks in high school, folks in college, how to take on some of the big questions you've taken on.

3:26:22.680 --> 3:26:25.680
 Now you've done that in the space of biology and expanded out.

3:26:25.680 --> 3:26:34.680
 How can they have a career they can be proud of or have a life they can be proud of?

3:26:34.680 --> 3:26:37.680
 Gosh, that's a big question.

3:26:37.680 --> 3:26:45.680
 I'm sure you've gathered some wisdom that you can impart onto young populace.

3:26:45.680 --> 3:26:54.680
 So the only advice that I actually ever give to my students is follow what you're interested in.

3:26:54.680 --> 3:27:01.680
 Because they're often worried that if they make this decision now and do this course instead of that course,

3:27:01.680 --> 3:27:07.680
 then they're going to restrict their career opportunities and there isn't a career path in science.

3:27:07.680 --> 3:27:16.680
 It's not, I mean, there is, but there isn't. There's a lot of competition, there's a lot of death symbolically.

3:27:16.680 --> 3:27:18.680
 So who survives?

3:27:18.680 --> 3:27:24.680
 The people who survive are the people who care enough to still do it.

3:27:24.680 --> 3:27:32.680
 And they're very often the people who don't worry too much about the future and are able to live in the present.

3:27:32.680 --> 3:27:39.680
 Because if you do a PhD, you've competed hard to get onto the PhD, then you have to compete hard to get a postdoc job.

3:27:39.680 --> 3:27:45.680
 And you have the next one maybe on another continent and it's only two years anyway.

3:27:45.680 --> 3:27:51.680
 And there's no guarantee you're going to get a faculty position at the end of it.

3:27:51.680 --> 3:27:54.680
 And there's always the next step to compete.

3:27:54.680 --> 3:27:57.680
 If you get a faculty position, you get a tenure.

3:27:57.680 --> 3:28:02.680
 And with tenure, you go full professor, full professor, then you go to some kind of whatever the discipline is.

3:28:02.680 --> 3:28:03.680
 There's an award.

3:28:03.680 --> 3:28:06.680
 If you're in physics, you're always competing for the Nobel Prize.

3:28:06.680 --> 3:28:07.680
 There's different awards.

3:28:07.680 --> 3:28:12.680
 And then eventually you're all competing to, I mean, there's always a competition.

3:28:12.680 --> 3:28:14.680
 So there is no happiness. Happiness does not lie.

3:28:14.680 --> 3:28:16.680
 If you're looking into the future, yes.

3:28:16.680 --> 3:28:21.680
 And if what you're caring about is a career, then it's probably not the one for you.

3:28:21.680 --> 3:28:30.680
 If though you can put that aside, and you know, I've also worked in industry for a brief period and I was main redundant twice.

3:28:30.680 --> 3:28:37.680
 So I know that there's no guarantee that you've got a career that way either.

3:28:37.680 --> 3:28:38.680
 Yes.

3:28:38.680 --> 3:28:43.680
 So live in the moment and try and enjoy what you're doing.

3:28:43.680 --> 3:28:52.680
 And that means really go to the themes that you're most interested in and try and follow them as well as you can.

3:28:52.680 --> 3:28:56.680
 And that tends to pay back in surprising ways.

3:28:56.680 --> 3:29:03.680
 I don't know if you've found this as well, but I found that people will help you often.

3:29:03.680 --> 3:29:15.680
 If they see some light shining in the eye, you're excited about their subject and just want to talk about it.

3:29:15.680 --> 3:29:19.680
 And they know that their friend in California has got a job coming up.

3:29:19.680 --> 3:29:21.680
 They'll say, go for this, this guy's all right.

3:29:21.680 --> 3:29:26.680
 They'll use the network to help you out if you really care.

3:29:26.680 --> 3:29:29.680
 And you're not going to have a job two years down the line.

3:29:29.680 --> 3:29:35.680
 But if what you really care about is what you're doing now, then it doesn't matter if you have a job in two years time or not.

3:29:35.680 --> 3:29:39.680
 It'll work itself out if you've got the light in your eye.

3:29:39.680 --> 3:29:42.680
 And so that's the only advice I can give.

3:29:42.680 --> 3:29:49.680
 And most people probably drop out through that system because the fight is just not worth it for them.

3:29:49.680 --> 3:29:50.680
 Yeah.

3:29:50.680 --> 3:29:56.680
 When you have the light in your eye, when you have the excitement for the thing, what happens is you start to surround yourself with others.

3:29:56.680 --> 3:29:58.680
 They're interested in that same thing that also have the light.

3:29:58.680 --> 3:30:03.680
 If you really are rigorous about this, because I think it does take...

3:30:03.680 --> 3:30:06.680
 It takes effort to make...

3:30:06.680 --> 3:30:08.680
 Oh, you've got to be obsessive.

3:30:08.680 --> 3:30:12.680
 But if you're doing what you really love doing, then it's not work anymore, it's what you do.

3:30:12.680 --> 3:30:17.680
 Yeah, but I also mean the surrounding yourself with other people that are obsessed about the same thing.

3:30:17.680 --> 3:30:18.680
 Because depending on...

3:30:18.680 --> 3:30:20.680
 Oh, that takes some work as well, yes.

3:30:20.680 --> 3:30:21.680
 And luck.

3:30:21.680 --> 3:30:24.680
 Finding the right mentors, the collaborators.

3:30:24.680 --> 3:30:34.680
 Because I think one of the problems with the PhD process is people are not careful enough in picking their mentors.

3:30:34.680 --> 3:30:37.680
 Those are people, mentors and colleagues and so on.

3:30:37.680 --> 3:30:43.680
 Those are people are going to define the direction of your life, how much you love a thing.

3:30:43.680 --> 3:30:51.680
 I mean, the power of just the few little conversations you have in the hallway, it's incredible.

3:30:51.680 --> 3:30:54.680
 So you have to be a little bit careful in that.

3:30:54.680 --> 3:30:57.680
 Sometimes you just get randomly almost assigned.

3:30:57.680 --> 3:31:06.680
 Really pursue, I suppose, the subject as much as you pursue the people that do that subject.

3:31:06.680 --> 3:31:08.680
 So both, the whole dance of it.

3:31:08.680 --> 3:31:10.680
 They kind of go together really.

3:31:10.680 --> 3:31:11.680
 Yeah, they really do.

3:31:11.680 --> 3:31:14.680
 But take that part seriously.

3:31:14.680 --> 3:31:18.680
 And probably in the way you're describing it,

3:31:18.680 --> 3:31:21.680
 careful how you define success.

3:31:21.680 --> 3:31:24.680
 You'll never find happiness in success.

3:31:24.680 --> 3:31:28.680
 There's a lovely quote from Robert Louis Stevenson, I think, who said,

3:31:28.680 --> 3:31:32.680
 nothing in life is so disenchanting as attainment.

3:31:32.680 --> 3:31:43.680
 Yeah, so I mean, in some sense, the true definition of success is getting to do today what you really enjoy doing.

3:31:43.680 --> 3:31:46.680
 Just what fills you with joy.

3:31:46.680 --> 3:31:47.680
 And that's ultimately success.

3:31:47.680 --> 3:31:54.680
 Success isn't the thing beyond the horizon, the big trophy, the financials.

3:31:54.680 --> 3:31:57.680
 I think it's as close as we can get to happiness.

3:31:57.680 --> 3:32:03.680
 That's not to say you're full of joy all the time, but it's as close as we can get to a sustained human happiness

3:32:03.680 --> 3:32:06.680
 is by getting some fulfillment from what you're doing on a daily basis.

3:32:06.680 --> 3:32:15.680
 And if what you're looking for is the world giving you the stamp of approval with a Nobel Prize or a fellowship or whatever it is,

3:32:15.680 --> 3:32:26.680
 then I've known people like this who they're eaten away by the anger and kind of caustic resentment

3:32:26.680 --> 3:32:30.680
 that they've not been awarded this prize that they deserve.

3:32:30.680 --> 3:32:34.680
 And the other way, if you put too much value into those kinds of prizes and you win them,

3:32:34.680 --> 3:32:45.680
 I've got the chance to see that it also, the more, quote unquote, successful you are in that sense,

3:32:45.680 --> 3:32:55.680
 the more you run the danger of growing an ego so big that you don't get to actually enjoy the beauty of this life.

3:32:55.680 --> 3:33:00.680
 You start to believe that you figured it all out as opposed to, I think,

3:33:00.680 --> 3:33:05.680
 but ultimately the most fun thing is being curious about everything around you, being constantly surprised

3:33:05.680 --> 3:33:11.680
 and these little moments of discovery of enjoying beauty in small and big ways all around you.

3:33:11.680 --> 3:33:17.680
 And I think the bigger your ego grows, the more you start to take yourself seriously, the less you're able to enjoy that.

3:33:17.680 --> 3:33:20.680
 Oh man, I couldn't agree more.

3:33:20.680 --> 3:33:31.680
 So, you know, the summary from harmless to mostly harmless in Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy, how would you try to summarize Earth?

3:33:31.680 --> 3:33:38.680
 And, you know, if you were given, if you had to summarize the whole thing in a couple of sentences,

3:33:38.680 --> 3:33:45.680
 and maybe throwing meaning of life in there, like why, why, why?

3:33:45.680 --> 3:33:52.680
 Is that a defining thing about humans that we care about the meaning of the whole thing?

3:33:52.680 --> 3:33:58.680
 I wonder if that should be part of the, these creatures seem to be very lost.

3:33:58.680 --> 3:34:00.680
 Yes, I'm not always asking why.

3:34:00.680 --> 3:34:06.680
 I mean, that's my defining question is why people used to make a joke.

3:34:06.680 --> 3:34:10.680
 I have a small scar on my forehead from a climbing accident years ago,

3:34:10.680 --> 3:34:15.680
 and the guy I was climbing with had dislodged a rock and he shouted something.

3:34:15.680 --> 3:34:18.680
 He shouted below, I think, meaning that the rock was coming down.

3:34:18.680 --> 3:34:23.680
 And I hadn't caught what he said, so I looked up and it smashed straight on my forehead.

3:34:23.680 --> 3:34:32.680
 And everybody around me took the piss saying he looked up to ask why.

3:34:32.680 --> 3:34:34.680
 Yeah, but that's a human imperative.

3:34:34.680 --> 3:34:36.680
 That's part of what it means to be human.

3:34:36.680 --> 3:34:41.680
 Look up to the sky and ask why.

3:34:41.680 --> 3:34:48.680
 So your question, define the earth.

3:34:48.680 --> 3:34:50.680
 I'm not sure I can do that.

3:34:50.680 --> 3:34:54.680
 I mean, the first word that comes to mind is living.

3:34:54.680 --> 3:34:57.680
 I wouldn't like to say mostly living, but perhaps.

3:34:57.680 --> 3:34:58.680
 Mostly living?

3:34:58.680 --> 3:35:04.680
 Well, it's interesting because if you were to write the Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy,

3:35:04.680 --> 3:35:09.680
 I suppose, say our idea that we talked about,

3:35:09.680 --> 3:35:17.680
 that bacteria is the most prominent form of life throughout the galaxy and the universe.

3:35:17.680 --> 3:35:21.680
 I suppose that earth would be kind of unique and would require...

3:35:21.680 --> 3:35:23.680
 It's always abundance in that case.

3:35:23.680 --> 3:35:24.680
 Yeah.

3:35:24.680 --> 3:35:25.680
 It's profligate.

3:35:25.680 --> 3:35:26.680
 It's rich.

3:35:26.680 --> 3:35:29.680
 It's enormously living.

3:35:29.680 --> 3:35:32.680
 So how would you describe that it's not bacteria?

3:35:32.680 --> 3:35:37.680
 It's eukaryotic.

3:35:37.680 --> 3:35:38.680
 Yeah.

3:35:38.680 --> 3:35:42.680
 Well, I mean, that's the technical term, but it is basically it's...

3:35:42.680 --> 3:35:46.680
 Yeah, and then...

3:35:46.680 --> 3:35:47.680
 How would I describe that?

3:35:47.680 --> 3:35:53.680
 I've actually really struggled with that term because the word...

3:35:53.680 --> 3:35:57.680
 I mean, there's few words quite as good as eukaryotic to put everybody off immediately.

3:35:57.680 --> 3:36:00.680
 You start using words like that and they'll leave the room.

3:36:00.680 --> 3:36:04.680
 Krebs cycle is another one that gets people to leave the room.

3:36:04.680 --> 3:36:10.680
 But I've tried to think, is there another word for eukaryotic that I can use?

3:36:10.680 --> 3:36:13.680
 And really the only word that I've been able to use is complex.

3:36:13.680 --> 3:36:18.680
 Complex cells, complex life and so on.

3:36:18.680 --> 3:36:25.680
 And that word, it serves one immediate purpose, which is to convey an impression.

3:36:25.680 --> 3:36:33.680
 But then it means so many different things just everybody that actually is lost immediately.

3:36:33.680 --> 3:36:35.680
 And so it's kind of...

3:36:35.680 --> 3:36:39.680
 Well, that's unnoticeable from the perspective of other planets.

3:36:39.680 --> 3:36:46.680
 That is the noticeable phase transition of complexity is the eukaryotic.

3:36:46.680 --> 3:36:49.680
 What about the harmless and the mostly harmless?

3:36:49.680 --> 3:36:51.680
 Is that kind of...

3:36:51.680 --> 3:36:54.680
 Probably accurate on a universal kind of scale.

3:36:54.680 --> 3:37:01.680
 I don't think that humanity is in any danger of disturbing the universe at the moment.

3:37:01.680 --> 3:37:07.680
 At the moment, which is why the mostly, we don't know, depends on what Elon is up to.

3:37:07.680 --> 3:37:09.680
 Depends on how many rockets.

3:37:09.680 --> 3:37:10.680
 I think...

3:37:10.680 --> 3:37:17.680
 It'll be still even then a while, I think, before we disturb the fabric of time and space.

3:37:17.680 --> 3:37:29.680
 What was the aforementioned Andre Carpathia, I think he summarized Earth as a system where you hammer it with a bunch of photons.

3:37:29.680 --> 3:37:33.680
 The input is like photons and the output is rockets.

3:37:33.680 --> 3:37:36.680
 See if you just...

3:37:36.680 --> 3:37:39.680
 Well, that's the hell of a lot of photons before there was a rocket.

3:37:39.680 --> 3:37:45.680
 Yeah, but maybe in the span of the universe, it's not that much time.

3:37:45.680 --> 3:37:52.680
 And so, and I do wonder what the future is, whether we're just in the early beginnings of this Earth,

3:37:52.680 --> 3:37:57.680
 which is important when you try to summarize it, or we're at the end,

3:37:57.680 --> 3:38:05.680
 where humans have finally gained the ability to destroy the entirety of this beautiful project we've got going on.

3:38:05.680 --> 3:38:10.680
 That with nuclear weapons, with engineered viruses, with all those kinds of things.

3:38:10.680 --> 3:38:15.680
 That's inadvertently through global warming and pollution and so on.

3:38:15.680 --> 3:38:16.680
 We're quite capable of that.

3:38:16.680 --> 3:38:18.680
 I mean, we just need to pass the tipping point.

3:38:18.680 --> 3:38:24.680
 I mean, I think we're more likely to do it inadvertently than through a nuclear war, which could happen at any time.

3:38:24.680 --> 3:38:33.680
 But my fear is we just don't know where the tipping points are and we will...

3:38:33.680 --> 3:38:37.680
 We kind of think we're smart enough to fix the problem quickly if we really need to.

3:38:37.680 --> 3:38:42.680
 I think that's the overriding assumption that we're all right for now.

3:38:42.680 --> 3:38:45.680
 Maybe in 20 years time, it's going to be a calamitous problem

3:38:45.680 --> 3:38:49.680
 and then we'll really need to put some serious mental power into fixing it

3:38:49.680 --> 3:38:53.680
 without seriously worrying that perhaps that is too late

3:38:53.680 --> 3:38:59.680
 and that however brilliant we are, we miss the boat.

3:38:59.680 --> 3:39:01.680
 And just walk off the cliff.

3:39:01.680 --> 3:39:02.680
 I don't know.

3:39:02.680 --> 3:39:05.680
 I have optimism in humans being clever descendants.

3:39:05.680 --> 3:39:08.680
 Oh, I have no doubt that we can fix the problem.

3:39:08.680 --> 3:39:10.680
 It's an urgent problem.

3:39:10.680 --> 3:39:13.680
 We need to fix it pretty sharpish.

3:39:13.680 --> 3:39:18.680
 And I do have doubts about whether politically we are capable of coming together enough

3:39:18.680 --> 3:39:23.680
 to not just in any one country but around the planet.

3:39:23.680 --> 3:39:26.680
 I mean, I know we can do it, but do we have the will?

3:39:26.680 --> 3:39:30.680
 Do we have the vision to accomplish it?

3:39:30.680 --> 3:39:33.680
 That's what makes this whole ride fun.

3:39:33.680 --> 3:39:38.680
 I don't know. Not only do we not know if we can handle the crises before us,

3:39:38.680 --> 3:39:43.680
 we don't even know all the crises that are going to be before us in the next 20 years.

3:39:43.680 --> 3:39:49.680
 The ones I think that will most likely challenge us in the 21st century

3:39:49.680 --> 3:39:51.680
 are the ones we don't even expect.

3:39:51.680 --> 3:39:55.680
 People didn't expect World War II at the end of World War I.

3:39:55.680 --> 3:39:58.680
 Some folks do, but not at the end of World War I,

3:39:58.680 --> 3:40:02.680
 but by the late 1920s, I think people were beginning to worry about it.

3:40:02.680 --> 3:40:05.680
 Yeah, no, there's always people worrying about everything.

3:40:05.680 --> 3:40:07.680
 So if you focus on the thing that...

3:40:07.680 --> 3:40:09.680
 People worry about, yes.

3:40:09.680 --> 3:40:11.680
 Because there's a million things people worry about,

